ted States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "TomCat4680", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Second Battle of Krithia", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Second Battle of Krithia\n| image       = \n| caption     = ''Charge of the 2nd Infantry Brigade at Krithia'' by Charles Wheeler, 1927.\n| partof      = The [[World War I|First World War]]\n| date        = 6\u20138 May 1915\n| place       = {{Coord|40|04|44|N|26|12|14|E|display=inline,title|type:event}}<br/>[[Krithia]], [[Gallipoli]], [[Adrianople Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| result      = Ottoman victory\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|French Third Republic}}<BR>\n{{flag|British Empire}}\n*{{flagcountry|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland}}\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj}}\n*{{flag|Australia}} \n*{{flagcountry|Dominion of New Zealand}}<br />\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| commander1  = {{Flagicon|British Empire}}[[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]]\n| commander2  = Unknown\n| strength1   = 25,000 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}<br/>72 guns\n| strength2   = 20,000 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n| casualties1 = 6,300 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n| casualties2 = 2,000\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Gallipoli}}\n}}\nThe '''Second Battle of Krithia''' continued the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]]' attempts to advance on the Helles battlefield during the [[Battle of Gallipoli]] of the [[World War I|First World War]]. The village of [[Krithia]] and neighbouring hill of [[Achi Baba]] had to be captured in order for the British to advance up the [[Gallipoli]] peninsula to the forts that controlled passage of the [[Dardanelles]] straits. A small amount of ground was captured after two days of costly fighting but the objectives remained out of reach.\n\n==Prelude==\n===Forces===\nFollowing the failure of the [[First Battle of Krithia]], the exhausted soldiers of the [[British 29th Division]] halted to consolidate their positions. They had to endure a number of Ottoman counter-attacks on 1 and 4 May.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 7</ref> Similar counter-attacks were repulsed at the Anzac landing on 2 May so that General [[William Birdwood]], commander of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (army corps)|Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]] deemed his front sufficiently secure to enable two [[brigade]]s to be moved to Helles for the next assault on Krithia. These were the [[2nd Brigade (Australia)|Australian 2nd Infantry Brigade]] and the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade]], around 5,000 men.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 4</ref>\n\nOther British reinforcements included brigades from the [[Royal Naval Division]] and the 125th Brigade from the [[British 42nd (East Lancashire) Division]]. The 87th and 88th Brigades of the 29th Division would once again be at the forefront of the attack. The Anzac brigades and General [[Herbert Cox]]'s [[29th Indian Brigade]] (Indian Expeditionary Force G)would be in reserve. The commander at Helles, [[Major General]] [[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]], was woefully lacking in shells for his [[artillery]] and those he did have were [[shrapnel shell]]s which was ineffective against entrenched positions. The navy were somewhat ambitiously still hoarding shells for the anticipated assault on [[Constantinople]].\n\nThe Ottomans had also been reinforcing their defences around Krithia. According to [[Kiazim Pasha]] the following units were responsible for the defence of Krithia:<ref name=bean41>Bean (1941), p. 41</ref>\n*1/ and 2/29th Regt (10th Div),\n*2/56th Regt. (15th Div),\n*2/19th Regt. (7th Div),\n*1/ and 4/26th Regt. (9th Div), and\n*15th Regt. (5th Div).\n\nThe infantry actually in front of Krithia on 8 May comprised:\n*2/25th Regt. (9th Div),\n*1/20th Regt. (7th Div), and\n*2/56th Regt. (15th Div).\n\nThe Ottomans had seven field-batteries positioned on either side of Achi Baba, as well as a six-gun battery of {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} howitzers.<ref name=bean41/>\n\n===Terrain===\n[[Image:MapHellesWarZoneGallipoli1915.jpg|thumb|left|<center>Map of Helles war zone</center>]]\nWhile [[Cape Helles]] is more forgiving than the wild terrain at [[Anzac Cove]], the battlefield still presented difficulties to the attacking force. The ground looked flat but was riven by four large gullies, or ''deres'', running from Achi Baba towards the Cape. On the west was Gully Ravine which was separated from the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] shore by Gully Spur. Moving east was Fir Tree Spur then Krithia Valley (also known as Krithia Nullah or Kirte Dere) then Krithia Spur then Kanli Dere then Kereves Spur then Kereves Dere which flows into the [[Dardanelles]] at Morto Bay. Krithia Spur was bare and exposed so was not favoured for attacks. Gully Spur and Fir Tree Spur offered some cover and so the majority of the British advances were made on these spurs and in the shelter of the gullies.\n\n===Plan===\nLike the first battle, the plan was for a general advance on a broad front across the peninsula.  The attack was divided into three phases. The first phase involved a general advance of one mile across the entire front which would place the French, on the right of the line, astride Kereves Spur where they were to dig in. In the second phase, the British in the centre and on the left would pivot on the French position and sweep up Fir Tree Spur and Gully Spur then capture Krithia village. The third phase would be the capture of Achi Baba.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 11</ref>\n\nIn the end, after three days of fighting, the Allies would abandon the battle without even completing the first phase. In fact, the greatest advance achieved was a mere {{convert|600|yd|m|abbr=on}}. The plan was made despite the fact that the British had no clear idea where the Ottoman fortifications were. There was as yet no continuous system of trenches and aerial [[reconnaissance]] had failed to locate the defences. Consequently, the preliminary bombardments that were made before each advance were utterly ineffectual. Hunter-Weston also insisted that the attacks be made in broad daylight, fearing that an attack under the cover of darkness would become confused.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 3</ref> Having failed with this approach once during the first battle did not deter Hunter-Weston, and as the second battle progressed he would remain undeterred.\n\n==Battle==\nThe Allied advance began later than scheduled, around 11:00 on 6 May, and was swiftly halted by strong Ottoman resistance. The 88th Brigade of the 29th Division advancing on Fir Tree Spur managed to capture Fir Tree Wood, and the 6th (Hood) Battalion of the [[British 63rd (Royal Naval) Division]] advanced strongly along Kanli Dere, but at all points on the line the gains were never more than {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on}}. At no point were the Ottoman defences reached. The attack was resumed on 7 May; it used the same plan and produced largely the same results.\n\nOn the morning of 8 May, the 88th Brigade in front of Krithia on Fir Tree Spur was relieved by the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade|New Zealand]]ers who made yet another attempt which failed with huge losses. The Wellington, Canterbury and Auckland Battalions gained another {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on}} through Fir Tree Wood to a place called the 'Daisy Patch' before they became pinned down. [[Enfilade]]d on the left from Ottoman [[machine gun]]s in Gully Ravine, they could neither advance nor withdraw and still had no sight of the Ottoman positions.\n\nDespite their predicament, Hunter-Weston ordered the New Zealanders, including the Otago Battalion in reserve, to resume that attack at 17:30. The brigade commander, Colonel [[Francis Earl Johnston|Francis Johnston]], protested but Hunter-Weston insisted the attack proceed. However, General [[Ian Hamilton (British Army officer)|Sir Ian Hamilton]], commander of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]], who had landed at Helles to oversee the battle, ordered a general advance to be made at 17:30 along the entire front with the aim of capturing Krithia and Achi Baba.<ref>Bean (1941), pp. 18\u201319</ref>\n\nThe Australian 2nd Infantry Brigade, under the command of [[Brigadier-General]] [[James Whiteside M'Cay|M'Cay]], was given 35 minutes warning that it was about to join the attack. The Australians were to advance along Krithia Spur between the right flank of the New Zealand brigade and the edge of Kanli Dere,<ref name=bean23>Bean (1941), p. 23</ref> and had to travel up to {{convert|800|yd|m|abbr=on}} from their reserve position just to reach the start line at \"Tommy's Trench\". The brigade managed to advance a further {{convert|500|yd|m|abbr=on}} beyond the start line, suffering 50% casualties in the process.\n\nThe New Zealand brigade made another attempt to cross the Daisy Patch, and some troops managed to actually sight the Ottoman trenches. On the right, the French resumed their advance at 18:00 and made good progress, reaching the Ottoman trenches on Kereves Dere. They managed to capture and hold Bouchet Redoubt but were forced back everywhere else.\n\n==Aftermath==\nAbout \u2153 of the Allied soldiers who fought in the battle became casualties. General Hamilton could ill-afford such losses as they made it difficult enough to hold the little ground he had, let alone continue to capture more. The poor planning of the battle extended to the medical provisions for the wounded which were woeful. The few stretcher bearers that were available often had to carry their burdens all the way to the beach as there was no intermediate collecting station with wagon transport. The [[hospital ship]] arrangements were also inadequate so that once the wounded were taken off the beach they would have trouble finding a ship prepared to take them on board.\n\nWith the failure of the second battle, Hamilton made a request to the British [[Secretary of State for War]], [[Horatio Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener of Khartoum|Lord Kitchener]], for an additional four divisions. He was promised the [[British 52nd (Lowland) Division]] but would not receive any more until August. Another attempt to capture Krithia would not be made until early June.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bean |first=Charles |year=1941 |origyear=1926 |title=The Story of ANZAC from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula |edition=11th |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |volume=II |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] |location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069751/ |oclc=220051990}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=The White Gurkhas: the 2nd Australian Infantry Brigade at Krithia, Gallipoli| first=Ronald|last=Austin|year=1989|isbn=0-7316-5323-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*Commonwealth of Australia Gazette, No. 46, 27 May 1915, pp.&nbsp;981\u2013982 ([http://www.nla.gov.au/gallipolidespatches/1-06-second_battle.html online version at the National Library of Australia])\n*[[The Age]], 18 June 1915, p.&nbsp;10 ([http://www.nla.gov.au/gallipolidespatches/1-06-second_battle.html online transcript at the National Library of Australia])\n*Major Fred Waite: ''New Zealanders at Gallipoli''. Whitecomb and Tombs Limited 1919, Chapter 9 \u2013 Battle of Krithnia ([http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WaiNewZ.html Online-Version (New Zealand Electronic Text Center)])\n*[http://www.firstworldwar.com/battles/krithia2.htm 2nd Battle of Krithia at firstworldwar.com]\n{{Ottoman battles in the 20th century}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krithia, Second Battle of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Gallipoli Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Australia]]\n[[Category:May 1915 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Second Battle of Krithia\n| image       = \n| caption     = ''Charge of the 2nd Infantry Brigade at Krithia'' by Charles Wheeler, 1927.\n| partof      = The [[World War I|First World War]]\n| date        = 6\u20138 May 1915\n| place       = {{Coord|40|04|44|N|26|12|14|E|display=inline,title|type:event}}<br/>[[Krithia]], [[Gallipoli]], [[Adrianople Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| result      = Ottoman victory\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|French Third Republic}}<BR>\n{{flag|British Empire}}\n*{{flagcountry|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland}}\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj}}\n*{{flag|Australia}} \n*{{flagcountry|Dominion of New Zealand}}<br />\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| commander1  = {{Flagicon|British Empire}}[[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]]\n| commander2  = Unknown\n| strength1   = 25,000 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}<br/>72 guns\n| strength2   = 20,000 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n| casualties1 = 6,300 {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n| casualties2 = 2,000\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Gallipoli}}\n}}\nThe '''Second Battle of Krithia''' continued the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]]' attempts to advance on the Helles battlefield during the [[Battle of Gallipoli]] of the [[World War I|First World War]]. The village of [[Krithia]] and neighbouring hill of [[Achi Baba]] had to be captured in order for the British to advance up the [[Gallipoli]] peninsula to the forts that controlled passage of the [[Dardanelles]] straits. A small amount of ground was captured after two days of costly fighting but the objectives remained out of reach.\n\n==Prelude==\n===Forces===\nFollowing the failure of the [[First Battle of Krithia]], the exhausted soldiers of the [[British 29th Division]] halted to consolidate their positions. They had to endure a number of Ottoman counter-attacks on 1 and 4 May.<ref>Bean (1941), p.7</ref> Similar counter-attacks were repulsed at the Anzac landing on 2 May so that General [[William Birdwood]], commander of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (army corps)|Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]] deemed his front sufficiently secure to enable two [[brigade]]s to be moved to Helles for the next assault on Krithia. These were the [[2nd Brigade (Australia)|Australian 2nd Infantry Brigade]] and the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade]], around 5,000 men.<ref>Bean (1941), p.4</ref>\n\nOther British reinforcements included brigades from the [[Royal Naval Division]] and the 125th Brigade from the [[British 42nd (East Lancashire) Division]]. The 87th and 88th Brigades of the 29th Division would once again be at the forefront of the attack. The Anzac brigades and General [[Herbert Cox]]'s [[29th Indian Brigade]] (Indian Expeditionary Force G)would be in reserve. The commander at Helles, [[Major General]] [[Aylmer Hunter-Weston]], was woefully lacking in shells for his [[artillery]] and those he did have were [[shrapnel shell]]s which was ineffective against entrenched positions. The navy were somewhat ambitiously still hoarding shells for the anticipated assault on [[Constantinople]].\n\nThe Ottomans had also been reinforcing their defences around Krithia. According to [[Kiazim Pasha]] the following units were responsible for the defence of Krithia:<ref name=bean41>Bean (1941), p.41</ref>\n*1/ and 2/29th Regt (10th Div),\n*2/56th Regt. (15th Div),\n*2/19th Regt. (7th Div),\n*1/ and 4/26th Regt. (9th Div), and\n*15th Regt. (5th Div).\n\nThe infantry actually in front of Krithia on 8 May comprised:\n*2/25th Regt. (9th Div),\n*1/20th Regt. (7th Div), and\n*2/56th Regt. (15th Div).\n\nThe Ottomans had seven field-batteries positioned on either side of Achi Baba, as well as a six-gun battery of {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} howitzers.<ref name=bean41/>\n\n===Terrain===\n[[Image:MapHellesWarZoneGallipoli1915.jpg|thumb|left|<center>Map of Helles war zone</center>]]\nWhile [[Cape Helles]] is more forgiving than the wild terrain at [[Anzac Cove]], the battlefield still presented difficulties to the attacking force. The ground looked flat but was riven by four large gullies, or ''deres'', running from Achi Baba towards the Cape. On the west was Gully Ravine which was separated from the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] shore by Gully Spur. Moving east was Fir Tree Spur then Krithia Valley (also known as Krithia Nullah or Kirte Dere) then Krithia Spur then Kanli Dere then Kereves Spur then Kereves Dere which flows into the [[Dardanelles]] at Morto Bay. Krithia Spur was bare and exposed so was not favoured for attacks. Gully Spur and Fir Tree Spur offered some cover and so the majority of the British advances were made on these spurs and in the shelter of the gullies.\n\n===Plan===\nLike the first battle, the plan was for a general advance on a broad front across the peninsula.  The attack was divided into three phases. The first phase involved a general advance of one mile across the entire front which would place the French, on the right of the line, astride Kereves Spur where they were to dig in. In the second phase, the British in the centre and on the left would pivot on the French position and sweep up Fir Tree Spur and Gully Spur then capture Krithia village. The third phase would be the capture of Achi Baba.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 11</ref>\n\nIn the end, after three days of fighting, the Allies would abandon the battle without even completing the first phase. In fact, the greatest advance achieved was a mere {{convert|600|yd|m|abbr=on}}. The plan was made despite the fact that the British had no clear idea where the Ottoman fortifications were. There was as yet no continuous system of trenches and aerial [[reconnaissance]] had failed to locate the defences. Consequently, the preliminary bombardments that were made before each advance were utterly ineffectual. Hunter-Weston also insisted that the attacks be made in broad daylight, fearing that an attack under the cover of darkness would become confused.<ref>Bean (1941), p. 3</ref> Having failed with this approach once during the first battle did not deter Hunter-Weston, and as the second battle progressed he would remain undeterred.\n\n==Battle==\nThe Allied advance began later than scheduled, around 11:00 on 6 May, and was swiftly halted by strong Ottoman resistance. The 88th Brigade of the 29th Division advancing on Fir Tree Spur managed to capture Fir Tree Wood, and the 6th (Hood) Battalion of the [[British 63rd (Royal Naval) Division]] advanced strongly along Kanli Dere, but at all points on the line the gains were never more than {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on}}. At no point were the Ottoman defences reached. The attack was resumed on 7 May; it used the same plan and produced largely the same results.\n\nOn the morning of 8 May, the 88th Brigade in front of Krithia on Fir Tree Spur was relieved by the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade|New Zealand]]ers who made yet another attempt which failed with huge losses. The Wellington, Canterbury and Auckland Battalions gained another {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on}} through Fir Tree Wood to a place called the 'Daisy Patch' before they became pinned down. [[Enfilade]]d on the left from Ottoman [[machine gun]]s in Gully Ravine, they could neither advance nor withdraw and still had no sight of the Ottoman positions.\n\nDespite their predicament, Hunter-Weston ordered the New Zealanders, including the Otago Battalion in reserve, to resume that attack at 17:30. The brigade commander, Colonel [[Francis Earl Johnston|Francis Johnston]], protested but Hunter-Weston insisted the attack proceed. However, General [[Ian Hamilton (British Army officer)|Sir Ian Hamilton]], commander of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]], who had landed at Helles to oversee the battle, ordered a general advance to be made at 17:30 along the entire front with the aim of capturing Krithia and Achi Baba.<ref>Bean (1941), pp. 18\u201319</ref>\n\nThe Australian 2nd Infantry Brigade, under the command of [[Brigadier-General]] [[James Whiteside M'Cay|M'Cay]], was given 35 minutes warning that it was about to join the attack. The Australians were to advance along Krithia Spur between the right flank of the New Zealand brigade and the edge of Kanli Dere,<ref name=bean41>Bean (1941), p. 23</ref> and had to travel up to {{convert|800|yd|m|abbr=on}} from their reserve position just to reach the start line at \"Tommy's Trench\". The brigade managed to advance a further {{convert|500|yd|m|abbr=on}} beyond the start line, suffering 50% casualties in the process.\n\nThe New Zealand brigade made another attempt to cross the Daisy Patch, and some troops managed to actually sight the Ottoman trenches. On the right, the French resumed their advance at 18:00 and made good progress, reaching the Ottoman trenches on Kereves Dere. They managed to capture and hold Bouchet Redoubt but were forced back everywhere else.\n\n==Aftermath==\nAbout \u2153 of the Allied soldiers who fought in the battle became casualties. General Hamilton could ill-afford such losses as they made it difficult enough to hold the little ground he had, let alone continue to capture more. The poor planning of the battle extended to the medical provisions for the wounded which were woeful. The few stretcher bearers that were available often had to carry their burdens all the way to the beach as there was no intermediate collecting station with wagon transport. The [[hospital ship]] arrangements were also inadequate so that once the wounded were taken off the beach they would have trouble finding a ship prepared to take them on board.\n\nWith the failure of the second battle, Hamilton made a request to the British [[Secretary of State for War]], [[Horatio Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener of Khartoum|Lord Kitchener]], for an additional four divisions. He was promised the [[British 52nd (Lowland) Division]] but would not receive any more until August. Another attempt to capture Krithia would not be made until early June.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bean |first=Charles |year=1941 |origyear=1926 |title=The Story of ANZAC from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula |edition=11th |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |volume=II |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] |location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069751/ |oclc=220051990}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=The White Gurkhas: the 2nd Australian Infantry Brigade at Krithia, Gallipoli| first=Ronald|last=Austin|year=1989|isbn=0-7316-5323-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*Commonwealth of Australia Gazette, No. 46, 27 May 1915, pp.&nbsp;981\u2013982 ([http://www.nla.gov.au/gallipolidespatches/1-06-second_battle.html online version at the National Library of Australia])\n*[[The Age]], 18 June 1915, p.&nbsp;10 ([http://www.nla.gov.au/gallipolidespatches/1-06-second_battle.html online transcript at the National Library of Australia])\n*Major Fred Waite: ''New Zealanders at Gallipoli''. Whitecomb and Tombs Limited 1919, Chapter 9 \u2013 Battle of Krithnia ([http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WaiNewZ.html Online-Version (New Zealand Electronic Text Center)])\n*[http://www.firstworldwar.com/battles/krithia2.htm 2nd Battle of Krithia at firstworldwar.com]\n{{Ottoman battles in the 20th century}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krithia, Second Battle of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Gallipoli Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Australia]]\n[[Category:May 1915 events]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Battle_of_Krithia"}
{"title_page": "The Girl in Room 105", "text_new": "{{italics title}}\n{{short description|novel by Chetan Bhagat}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title = The Girl in Room 105...an unlove story\n| name = The Girl in Room 105\n| image = Girl in room 105.png\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Book cover image\n| author = [[Chetan Bhagat]]\n| audio_read_by = \n| title_orig = \n| orig_lang_code = \n| title_working = \n| translator = \n| illustrator = \n| cover_artist = [[Kashmira Irani]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Indian English]]\n| series = \n| release_number = \n| subject = \n| set_in = [[India]]\n| publisher = Westland\n| publisher2 = \n| pub_date = October 9, 2018\n| english_pub_date = \n| published = \n| media_type = [[Paperback]]\n| pages = 304\n| awards = \n| isbn = 978-1542040464\n| isbn_note = \n| oclc = \n| dewey = \n| congress = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource = \n| notes = \n| exclude_cover = \n| website = \n| genre = [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]], [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Girl in Room 105''''' is the eighth novel and the tenth book overall written by the Indian author [[Chetan Bhagat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thepost.co.in/english/book-review-the-girl-in-the-room-105/|title=Book Review : The Girl in Room 105 - The Post|date=6 November 2018|website=thepost.co.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/entertainment/2018/11/05/chetan-bhagat-new-book-released-sans-fanfare.html|title=Chetan Bhagat's latest book: Quiet release, cooler reception|website=theweek.in}}</ref> The book became a bestseller based on prearranged sales alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/meet/chetan-bhagat-being-at-the-right-place-at-the-right-time/article25575427.ece|title=Chetan Bhagat: Right place at the right time|website=thehindubusinessline.com}}</ref> It tells about a IIT coaching class tutor who goes to wish his ex-girlfriend on her birthday and finds her murdered. The rest of the story is his journey where he stands by his ex-girlfriend after her death to find justice. The book also addresses the stereotypes and political issues we face in India.\n\nThe novel opens up with a conversation of the author of the book, Chetan Bhagat with a fellow passenger on a midnight [[IndiGo]] flight from [[Hyderabad]] to [[Delhi]]. After an initial conversation, Chetan agrees to listen to the story of the fellow passenger. Soon after, the fellow passenger starts narrating his story to the author.<br />\n\n== Plot ==\nKeshav is a former [[Indian Institutes of Technology|IIT]] student who currently works as a teacher in a [[Joint Entrance Examination|JEE]] tuition center''.'' He hates his job and reaches out through [[LinkedIn]], but fails to find a proper job. He is a part of an orthodox family. His mother is a homemaker and his father is a part of the [[RSS (politics)|RSS]]. He has a love story with a colleague named Zara, who is pursuing her [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in IIT. Zara is from a [[Kashmiri Muslims|Kashmiri Muslim]] family and their love story ends due to their families, who fight over religious issues. Keshav couldn\u2019t come out of it and keeps remembering Zara, who then loves Raghu (Keshav\u2019s classmate). Raghu happens to be an intelligent person with a geeky look. Keshav often calls Zara begging her to come back to him, but she never agrees. Saurabh (Keshav's friend) bids Keshav to forget his past love and focus on his future.\n\nOn Zara's birthday, Keshav controls his urge to call Zara and wish her at midnight. He and Saurabh drink and fall asleep. Around 3 a.m. in the morning, he gets [[Text messaging|text messages]] from Zara asking him why he didn\u2019t wish her this year. Zara goes on and tells him to meet her in her room immediately. Keshav complies and rushes to Zara's room to wish her in person.\n\nAs Keshav enters the room, he finds that the room is dark and its utterly silent. Zara is asleep on the bed. He touches her forehead and feels a cold chill. He then switches on the light and sees her dead. He informs Saurabh who suggests they run away from the scene. But Keshav becomes determined to find the killer. He informs the police, Raghu, and Zara\u2019s parents. The police arrests the watchman of the hostel, who is missed from the [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] camera during the time Zara was killed. Although police close the case afterwords, Keshav continues his investigation. Keshav digs deeper, with the help of police Inspector Vikas Rana. He first suspects Prof. Saxena (Zara's [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]]. guide), who tries to harass Zara. Then, Prof. Saxena is withdrawn as a suspect in Zara's murder case after finding out the truth. \n\nAfter seeking of new suspects in the murder case, he tries to find Sikander, Zara\u2019s stepbrother who happens to be part of a terrorist group in [[Kashmir]]. Keshav seeks help from Zara\u2019s father and checks her room for clues. He finds a locker with gunpowder, pregnancy kits, and selfies of Sikander with a gun along with Zara who happens to be smiling in the picture. Keshav goes through the clues one by one. He first tries to meet Sikander and asks him about his group called Tehreek. Sikander gets afraid and threatens them with a gun and runs away. They try to reach him out through his mother in Kashmir. Sikander meets them again and tries to explain that he is not the murderer. But with the proper clues, Keshav almost gets convinced that Sikander killed his sister in the fear that Tehreek might be known to the army. The next day Sikander kills himself, telling that his existence would harm Tehreek and convince everyone that he did not kill his sister. After the suicide of Sikander, Keshav realizes he made a mistake by doubting upon him.\n\nHe then finds out about the pregnancy kits Zara had in her [[safe]] and sees a picture of an army officer (\"Captain Faiz Khan\") in [[Kashmir]] with Zara, in her [[Instagram]]. After proper investigation, he finds out that the army officer has gifted Zara expensive jewelry and they raid his house in Delhi. They find the same pregnancy kits and check his internet history, which has search histories related to abortion and divorce. They also find gold blocks in his house and get convinced with the theory that he made Zara pregnant and killed her in guilt. They arrange a dinner party to announce the victim and arrest him unknowingly by inviting everyone Zara knew, after the 100th day of her death. Just before Keshav announces the killer, he goes on a little trip to [[Hyderabad]]. This is when he realizes that Raghu is the real killer. Raghu confesses to have killed Zara. He killed Zara because he found out she had an affair with her childhood friend, Captain Faiz, and was perhaps pregnant with his child; Faiz tells, however, that she wasn't. While they did have an affair, it ended because Faiz was married and Zara didn't want him to leave his wife and kids, and because Zara loved Raghu. Keshav learns that Raghu had sent the text messages to him on Zara's birthday, and that Zara was already dead. Raghu is arrested by Inspector Rana. The novel ends with Keshav visiting Zara's grave, and Keshav and Saurabh opening a detective agency.\n\n== References ==\n<br />{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.chetanbhagat.com/books/the-girl-in-room-105/ Official Website]\n{{Chetan Bhagat}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl in Room 105}}\n[[Category:2018 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Chetan Bhagat]]\nhttps://contextreviews.com/the-girl-in-room-105-an-unlove-story/\n", "text_old": "{{italics title}}\n{{short description|novel by Chetan Bhagat}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title = The Girl in Room 105...an unlove story\n| name = The Girl in Room 105\n| image = Girl in room 105.png\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Book cover image\n| author = [[Chetan Bhagat]]\n| audio_read_by = \n| title_orig = \n| orig_lang_code = \n| title_working = \n| translator = \n| illustrator = \n| cover_artist = [[Kashmira Irani]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Indian English]]\n| series = \n| release_number = \n| subject = \n| set_in = [[India]]\n| publisher = Westland\n| publisher2 = \n| pub_date = October 9, 2018\n| english_pub_date = \n| published = \n| media_type = [[Paperback]]\n| pages = 304\n| awards = \n| isbn = 978-1542040464\n| isbn_note = \n| oclc = \n| dewey = \n| congress = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource = \n| notes = \n| exclude_cover = \n| website = \n| genre = [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]], [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Girl in Room 105''''' is the eighth novel and the tenth book overall written by the Indian author [[Chetan Bhagat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thepost.co.in/english/book-review-the-girl-in-the-room-105/|title=Book Review : The Girl in Room 105 - The Post|date=6 November 2018|website=thepost.co.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/entertainment/2018/11/05/chetan-bhagat-new-book-released-sans-fanfare.html|title=Chetan Bhagat's latest book: Quiet release, cooler reception|website=theweek.in}}</ref> The book became a bestseller based on prearranged sales alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/meet/chetan-bhagat-being-at-the-right-place-at-the-right-time/article25575427.ece|title=Chetan Bhagat: Right place at the right time|website=thehindubusinessline.com}}</ref> It tells about a IIT coaching class tutor who goes to wish his ex-girlfriend on her birthday and finds her murdered. The rest of the story is his journey where he stands by his ex-girlfriend after her death to find justice. The book also addresses the stereotypes and political issues we face in India.\n\nThe novel opens up with a conversation of the author of the book, Chetan Bhagat with a fellow passenger on a midnight [[IndiGo]] flight from [[Hyderabad]] to [[Delhi]]. After an initial conversation, Chetan agrees to listen to the story of the fellow passenger. Soon after, the fellow passenger starts narrating his story to the author.<br />\n\n== Plot ==\nKeshav is a former [[Indian Institutes of Technology|IIT]] student who currently works as a teacher in a [[Joint Entrance Examination|JEE]] tuition center''.'' He hates his job and reaches out through [[LinkedIn]], but fails to find a proper job. He is a part of an orthodox family. His mother is a homemaker and his father is a part of the [[RSS (politics)|RSS]]. He has a love story with a colleague named Zara, who is pursuing her [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in IIT. Zara is from a [[Kashmiri Muslims|Kashmiri Muslim]] family and their love story ends due to their families, who fight over religious issues. Keshav couldn\u2019t come out of it and keeps remembering Zara, who then loves Raghu (Keshav\u2019s classmate). Raghu happens to be an intelligent person with a geeky look. Keshav often calls Zara begging her to come back to him, but she never agrees. Saurabh (Keshav's friend) bids Keshav to forget his past love and focus on his future.\n\nOn Zara's birthday, Keshav controls his urge to call Zara and wish her at midnight. He and Saurabh drink and fall asleep. Around 3 a.m. in the morning, he gets [[Text messaging|text messages]] from Zara asking him why he didn\u2019t wish her this year. Zara goes on and tells him to meet her in her room immediately. Keshav complies and rushes to Zara's room to wish her in person.\n\nAs Keshav enters the room, he finds that the room is dark and its utterly silent. Zara is asleep on the bed. He touches her forehead and feels a cold chill. He then switches on the light and sees her dead. He informs Saurabh who suggests they run away from the scene. But Keshav becomes determined to find the killer. He informs the police, Raghu, and Zara\u2019s parents. The police arrests the watchman of the hostel, who is missed from the [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] camera during the time Zara was killed. Although police close the case afterwords, Keshav continues his investigation. Keshav digs deeper, with the help of police Inspector Vikas Rana. He first suspects Prof. Saxena (Zara's [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]]. guide), who tries to harass Zara. Then, Prof. Saxena is withdrawn as a suspect in Zara's murder case after finding out the truth. \n\nAfter seeking of new suspects in the murder case, he tries to find Sikander, Zara\u2019s stepbrother who happens to be part of a terrorist group in [[Kashmir]]. Keshav seeks help from Zara\u2019s father and checks her room for clues. He finds a locker with gunpowder, pregnancy kits, and selfies of Sikander with a gun along with Zara who happens to be smiling in the picture. Keshav goes through the clues one by one. He first tries to meet Sikander and asks him about his group called Tehreek. Sikander gets afraid and threatens them with a gun and runs away. They try to reach him out through his mother in Kashmir. Sikander meets them again and tries to explain that he is not the murderer. But with the proper clues, Keshav almost gets convinced that Sikander killed his sister in the fear that Tehreek might be known to the army. The next day Sikander kills himself, telling that his existence would harm Tehreek and convince everyone that he did not kill his sister. After the suicide of Sikander, Keshav realizes he made a mistake by doubting upon him.\n\nHe then finds out about the pregnancy kits Zara had in her [[safe]] and sees a picture of an army officer (\"Captain Faiz Khan\") in [[Kashmir]] with Zara, in her [[Instagram]]. After proper investigation, he finds out that the army officer has gifted Zara expensive jewelry and they raid his house in Delhi. They find the same pregnancy kits and check his internet history, which has search histories related to abortion and divorce. They also find gold blocks in his house and get convinced with the theory that he made Zara pregnant and killed her in guilt. They arrange a dinner party to announce the victim and arrest him unknowingly by inviting everyone Zara knew, after the 100th day of her death. Just before Keshav announces the killer, he goes on a little trip to [[Hyderabad]]. This is when he realizes that Raghu is the real killer. Raghu confesses to have killed Zara. He killed Zara because he found out she had an affair with her childhood friend, Captain Faiz, and was perhaps pregnant with his child; Faiz tells, however, that she wasn't. While they did have an affair, it ended because Faiz was married and Zara didn't want him to leave his wife and kids, and because Zara loved Raghu. Keshav learns that Raghu had sent the text messages to him on Zara's birthday, and that Zara was already dead. Raghu is arrested by Inspector Rana. The novel ends with Keshav visiting Zara's grave, and Keshav and Saurabh opening a detective agency.\n\n== References ==\n<br />{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.chetanbhagat.com/books/the-girl-in-room-105/ Official Website]\n{{Chetan Bhagat}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl in Room 105}}\n[[Category:2018 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Chetan Bhagat]]\n", "name_user": "Lsmeghwal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Girl_in_Room_105"}
{"title_page": "American Dream (shopping and entertainment complex)", "text_new": "{{About|the mall in New Jersey|proposed facilities of the same name|American Dream Mall (disambiguation){{!}}American Dream Mall}}\n{{short description|retail and entertainment complex in East Rutherford, NJ}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name = American Dream\n| logo = American Dream Meadowlands Logo.png\n| image = Indoor ski slope at American Dream in Meadowlands.jpg\n| image_width = 270px\n| caption = [[Big Snow American Dream]] ski slope\n| owner = [[Triple Five Group]]\n| location = [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]], [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States]]\n| opening_date = October 25, 2019, ([[Nickelodeon Universe]] and Ice Rink)<br>December 5, 2019, ([[Big Snow American Dream|Big Snow]]) ([[DreamWorks Water Park]])<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2020/02/27/american-dream-nj-water-park-some-retail-stores-open/4897595002/|title=Opening date for American Dream water park and some retail stores announced|website=North Jersey|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><br>September 2020, (retail stores and dining) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=2020-02-27|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> \n| number_of_stores = 450+\n| number_of_anchors = 6\n| floor_area = {{convert|3000000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| architect = \n| parking = 33,000 spaces<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison |date=December 2, 2018|url=https://expo.nj.com/news/erry-2018/12/8df3facb447815/waterslides-are-being-installe.html|title=Waterslides are being installed at the American Dream mega-mall and it is glorious|publisher=[[NJ.com]]|accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archivedate= |archiveurl= }}</ref>\n| publictransit = [[file:25_railtransportation.svg|11px|Railway Train]] {{rint|njt|60px}} [[Meadowlands station]] <br> {{bus icon|12px}} {{rint|njt|60px}} [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (1\u201399)|85]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (300\u2013399)|355]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (300\u2013399)|356]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (700\u2013799)|703]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (700\u2013799)|772]]\n| website = {{URL|www.americandream.com}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|48|36|N|74|04|03|W|region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''American Dream''' ('''AD''') is a retail and entertainment complex in the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], [[United States]], that will have over 450 stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/03/nyregion/dream-of-a-mall-starts-to-rise-out-of-a-meadowlands-nightmare.html?_r=0|title=Huge Mall Rising at Troubled Site in North Jersey|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 2, 2015|author=Bagli, Charles V. |accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> The first and second of four opening stages occurred on October 25, 2019, and on December 5, 2019.<ref name=\"NorthJersey7.3.19\">{{cite web|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=July 3, 2019|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/07/03/american-dream-open-oct-25-officials-say/1639522001/|title=It's finally happening: American Dream mall will open Oct. 25|newspaper=[[NorthJersey.com]]|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archivedate=July 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703201850/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/07/03/american-dream-open-oct-25-officials-say/1639522001/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/12/indoor-ski-slope-at-american-dream-is-open-heres-a-first-look-inside.html|title=Indoor ski slope at American Dream is open. Here\u2019s a first look inside.|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=December 5, 2019|website=nj|language=en|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The remaining opening stages was supposed to open on March 19, 2020. However, due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic (commonly known as COVID-19)]], the opening of the final stages was delayed once more until further notice. <ref name=NorthJersey7.3.19/><ref name=\"NJcom.9.20.19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/09/american-dream-reveals-plans-theme-park-will-open-before-water-park-ski-slope.html|title=American Dream\u2019s theme park to open in October. For other attractions, you'll have to wait.|last=Pries|first=Allison|date=September 20, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe project was first proposed in 2003 by the [[Mills Corporation]] as the ''Meadowlands Xanadu'', with construction beginning in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/arts-entertainment/inside-american-dream-mega-mall-new-jersey|title=Inside American Dream, The Mega-Mall New Jersey Maybe Didn't Need|last=Lampen|first=Claire|date=November 5, 2019|website=Gothamist|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> After the Mills Corporation's bankruptcy in 2007, the project was taken over by [[Colony Capital]]. In May 2009, construction stalled due to the [[bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers]]. [[Triple Five Group]] announced intent to take over the mall in May 2011, and on July 31, 2013, officially gained control of the mall and the surrounding site.<ref name=\"NorthJersey8.2.13\">Nicholaides, Kelly (August 2, 2013). [http://www.northjersey.com/news/217977711_American_Dream_Meadowlands_handed_over_former_Xanadu_project_in_East_Rutherford.html \"American Dream Meadowlands handed over former Xanadu project in East Rutherford\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref>\n\nAfter a series of ownership changes, financing issues, construction delays, and legal challenges, construction stopped again in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/03/03/american-dream-cranes-tell-sad-story/98688642/|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=March 3, 2017 |author=Brennan, John |title=American Dream cranes tell sad story}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |author=Bagli, Charles V. |title=After Many Missed Deadlines, New Jersey Megamall Is Again Taking Shape |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/13/nyregion/after-many-missed-deadlines-new-jersey-megamall-is-again-taking-shape.html |quote= |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 13, 2016 }}</ref> In late June 2017, construction had resumed, after new financing had been secured,<ref name=\"NorthJersey6.29.16\">{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/06/29/american-dream-meadowlands-finalizes-its-2-8-b-financing/440364001/ |title=American Dream Meadowlands finalizes $2.8B in construction financing; work resumes |author=Brennan, John |date=June 29, 2016 |publisher=North Jersey Media Group |accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first1=Sara |last1=Jerde |title=Construction reportedly resumes at Meadowlands megamall |url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2017/07/construction_reportedly_resumes_at_meadowlands_megamall.html |quote= |newspaper=[[The Star Ledger]]|date=July 11, 2017}}</ref> though the project would suffer a series of \"chronically delayed\" opening dates. Among the attractions that opened in 2019 were the [[Nickelodeon Universe#American Dream Meadowlands|Nickelodeon Universe]] theme park in October and the [[Big Snow American Dream]] ski slope in December; the [[DreamWorks Water Park]], scheduled to open in November, was supposed to open March 19, 2020. However, due to the coronavirus outbreak, the waterpark's opening date got delayed once again. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=February 27, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Meadowlands Mills (1994&ndash;2002)===\n[[File:Xanadu Indoor Ski.JPG|thumb|left|The exterior of the indoor ski slope in 2009]]\nThe [[Mills Corporation]] first began working on plans for a mall in the [[New Jersey Meadowlands]] in 1994. Meadowlands Mills, as it was called, would have been constructed on the Empire Tract, an area of {{convert|587|acre}} of wetlands in [[Carlstadt, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"MeadowlandsConservation\">{{cite web|url=http://meadowlandsconservationtrust.org/success-stories/richard-p-kane/|title=Richard P. Kane|publisher=Meadowlands Conservation Trust|language=en|location=[[Lyndhurst, New Jersey]]|accessdate=March 17, 2019|archivedate=January 25, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125130935/http://meadowlandsconservationtrust.org/success-stories/richard-p-kane/}}</ref> The tract was owned by Empire Ltd., a company which had purchased the land in 1961 and had been planning a major development since 1987.<ref>Hendry, Cheryl Ann. [https://scholarworks.montana.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1/12784/HendryC0517.pdf?sequence=4 \"Finding Nature in an Industrial Swamp: A Case Study of New Jersey's Hackensack Meadowlands\"], p. 196, [[Montana State University]], 2017.</ref> The commercial development would have consisted of {{convert|2.1|e6sqft|m2}} of retail space, a hotel, and {{convert|1|e6sqft|m2}} of office space on {{convert|206|acre}} of the tract. To mitigate the heavy environmental impact, the remainder of the tract would have been converted into stormwater [[retention basin]]s.<ref name=NYTimes2000/>\n\nAfter Empire and Mills announced their proposal in 1996, the project quickly became controversial and faced opposition from a variety of environmental and conservationist groups, as well as the tract's congressman, [[Steve Rothman]]. Opponents stated that the mall would have a devastating impact on the ecological health of the area, while the Mills Corporation defended its plans by arguing that the land was already devastated by [[pesticide]] usage and invasive [[Phragmites|common reeds]].<ref name=\"NYTimes2000\">Jacobs, Andrew (December 18, 2000). [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/18/nyregion/shops-vs-swamps-meadowlands-debate-over-huge-shopping-mall-marked-rival-claims.html \"Shops vs. Swamps In the Meadowlands; Debate Over a Huge Shopping Mall Marked by Rival Claims and Spin\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>[https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1998-04-15-1998105029-story.html \"Mall plan forces a look at future of Meadowlands; Developers argue that parts of N.J. wetland are not worth saving\"], ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', April 15, 1998.</ref>\n\nThe [[Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] opposed the project after studying its potential environmental impact. However, the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] conducted its own study which contradicted the EPA's findings and stated that the project was not a threat to the Meadowlands area.<ref name=NYTimes2000/> New Jersey governor [[Donald DiFrancesco]] announced plans to protect the area in 2001, encouraging the Mills Corporation to look at other potential sites in the region.<ref>Jacobs, Andrew (March 21, 2001). [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/21/nyregion/difrancesco-seeks-to-save-meadowlands.html \"DiFrancesco Seeks to Save Meadowlands\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref> His successor, [[Jim McGreevey]], informed Mills the following year that the state government would not provide permits for the mall, effectively ending the project as originally proposed.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080313164040/http://www.hackensackriverkeeper.org/Meadowlands_Xanadu.html \"The Facts Regarding the Conservation of the Empire Tract\"], Hackensack Riverkeeper, 2005.</ref> The Empire Tract was later permanently protected by the Meadowlands Conservation Trust, which purchased it in 2005 and renamed it the Richard P. Kane Natural Area after a noted New Jersey conservationist.<ref name=MeadowlandsConservation/>\n\n===Meadowlands Xanadu (2002&ndash;2010)===\nIn July 2002, the [[New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority]] (NJSEA) issued a [[request for proposal]] for a project in the area that was then the parking lot of the [[Continental Airlines Arena]]. The request was inspired by the Meadowlands Mills project as well as by plans to move the [[New Jersey Nets]] out of the arena, and involved significantly less environmental damage because it would be built on already developed land. The Mills Corporation retooled its earlier proposal for Meadowlands Mills to fit the new site, and partnered with [[Mack-Cali Realty Corporation]] to design Meadowlands Xanadu, a major multi-use development which would incorporate a renovated Continental Airlines Arena.<ref>[https://www.rst2.org/njheps/meadowlandsquest/teterboro/index.html \"Xanadu Project (Continental Airlines Arena Site Redevelopment)\"], ''Teterboro Online'', 2005.</ref> The name was taken from Mills Corporation's [[Madrid Xanad\u00fa]], a shopping mall in Spain which opened in 2003.\n\nNJSEA accepted several other proposals for developing the site. [[Westfield Group]] proposed Arena Place, an \"urban village\" and \"town square\" built around the arena. [[Hartz Mountain Industries]] and [[Forest City Realty Trust]] submitted plans for Expo Park at the Meadowlands, featuring an outlet mall, a convention center, an indoor racetrack, and three hotel buildings.<ref name=\"NorthJersey9.6.15\">{{cite news|last1=Brennan|first1=John|title=American Dream Meadowlands nears pivotal moment: the $1B bond sale|url=http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/12060/american-dream-meadowlands-nears-pivotal-moment-the-1b-bond-sale/|accessdate=September 16, 2015|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=September 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915071000/http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/12060/american-dream-meadowlands-nears-pivotal-moment-the-1b-bond-sale/|archive-date=September 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Triple Five Group]] proposed MeadowFest America, which planned an [[adaptive reuse]] of the arena to create a retail and entertainment complex.<ref name=\"nyt-sep2002\">Smothers, Ronald (September 20, 2002). [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/20/nyregion/new-ideas-unveiled-for-site-of-meadowlands-arena.html \"New Ideas Unveiled for Site of Meadowlands Arena\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com6.19.18\">Pries, Allison. [https://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2018/06/american_dream_how_did_a_swath_of_land_in_the_mead.html \"American Dream: The 16-year (and counting) journey of a mega-mall that might actually open kind of soon\"]. NJ.com. June 19, 2018. Retrieved January 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nOther proposals focused on the project's location in the Meadowlands Sports Complex. [[International Speedway Corporation]] envisioned plans for Sports City America, a development centered around the proposed Garden State International Speedway, a [[NASCAR]] racetrack seating 80,000. A consortium that included [[Paul Newman]], [[Carl Haas]], and [[Mario Andretti]] proposed Liberty Speedway and Family Theme Park, combining a racetrack with an amusement park and connecting the two with a monorail.<ref name=nyt-sep2002/><ref>[http://www.teterboro-online.com/xanadu/proposals/prop1.shtml \"Continental Airlines Arena site Redevelopment Proposals\"], ''Teterboro Online'', 2002.</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, the authority's board chose Mills Corporation and Mack-Cali's plan over the other two finalists, Westfield Group and Hartz Mountain Industries.<ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/> The project was billed by Mills chairman and executive officer Laurence E. Siegel as \"...a new standard for bringing lifestyle, recreation, sports and family entertainment offerings together in one location.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority Approves Meadowlands Xanadu Development Agreement |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20031203005654/en/Jersey-Sports-Exposition-Authority-Approves-Meadowlands-Xanadu|newspaper=Business Wire |date=December 3, 2003 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> Ground was broken on the complex on September 29, 2004,<ref>{{cite news |title=Meadowlands Xanadu Announces Official Groundbreaking Ceremony Date of September 29, 2004 |url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2004/Aug/1062449.htm |newspaper=Business Wire |date=August 3, 2004 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> and, at the time, was expected to open two years later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mills Corp. and Mack-Cali Sign Deal to Create 4.76m s/f Meadowlands Sport and Leisure Arena |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-112314739.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104034213/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-112314739.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |newspaper=Real Estate Weekly |date=December 17, 2003 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, [[Colony Capital]] purchased the project from Mills Corporation for $500 million and pushed the projected opening to 2008.<ref name=NYTimes/><ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/><ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/>\n\nBy 2008, the colorfully gaudy exterior of the building, which is visible from the [[New Jersey Turnpike]] and [[New Jersey Route 3]], began to draw criticism as an eyesore,<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> [[Richard Codey]], president of the New Jersey State Senate at the time, called the structure \"yucky-looking\".<ref name=\"NYTimes4.23.08\">{{cite news |title=Is a Giant Mall an Eyesore? Developer Urges Patience |first=Terry |last=Pristin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/23/realestate/commercial/23xanadu.html |newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 23, 2008 |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, then-Governor Chris Christie called it \"an offense to the eyes as you drive up the turnpike\" and \"by far the ugliest damn building in New Jersey, and maybe America.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Fix Xanadu? The Problem May Be Where to Begin|date=April 1, 2011|first=Richard|last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/02/nyregion/02xanadu.html?_r=0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/nj_ugliest_building_fix_vfSvwNyiWghUjFmPYWbSiN|title=NJ's 'ugliest-building' fix|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=March 25, 2011}}</ref> After acquiring the project, Triple Five indicated the exterior would be repainted in a different color scheme.<ref name=\"NorthJersey2.21.13\">Brennan, John (February 21, 2013). [http://www.northjersey.com/eastrutherford/american_dream_bergen_improvement_authority.html \"Work on American Dream complex set to resume in March, official says\"]. NorthJersey.com.</ref>\n\n[[File:Xanadumeadowlandslogo.jpg|thumb|The former logo of the complex]]\nIn May 2009, construction on Xanadu, which was nearly 80% complete<ref name=UCReporter>Sullivan, Al (August 25, 2013). \"A dream comes true?\" ''[[The Union City Reporter]]''. pp 5 and 12.</ref> (and whose common areas were about 88% complete), came to a halt after a subsidiary of bankrupt [[Lehman Brothers]] missed payments, causing other lenders to withdraw from the project, and lost $500&nbsp;million worth of construction funding. While developers stated the mall was 70% leased,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/20/realestate/commercial/20xanadu.html |title=At $2.3 Billion, This Mall Could Be Too Big to Fail |first=Terry |last=Pristin |newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 16, 2010}}</ref> it is unknown how many retailers stayed leased while the mall was delayed.\n\nIn March 2009, the retailer [[Cabela's]] announced that it did not plan to open its Meadowlands location for another year,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/cabelas_delays_opening_for_its.html |title=Cabela's delays opening for its Xanadu store|publisher=NJ.com |date=March 9, 2009 }}</ref> and subsequently gave \"late 2010\" as an estimated opening date.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/environment/specialreports/Cabelas_Xanadu_wont_open_until_late_2010.html |title=Key Xanadu tenant describes \"late 2010\" for Xanadu debut |first=John |last=Brennan |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=August 3, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100412170352/http://www.northjersey.com/news/environment/specialreports/Cabelas_Xanadu_wont_open_until_late_2010.html| archivedate=April 12, 2010 | url-status= dead}}</ref> It would later pull out of the project by November 2010, following the collapse of Lehman Brothers and a halt to construction.<ref>Bagli, Charles V. (November 26, 2010). [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/27/nyregion/27Xanadu.html \"A New Push to Rescue Xanadu Mall Project\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, [[Stephen M. Ross|Stephen Ross]], owner of [[The Related Companies]] in Manhattan, stated that he could finish the project by the end of 2010, possibly with a new name and look.<ref>{{cite news |title=Xanadu\u2019s $3B \u2018White Knight\u2019 knows how to get things done |first=Andrew |last=Tangel |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/83743942_Xanadu_s__3B__White_Knight__knows_how_to_get_things_done.html |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=February 7, 2010 |accessdate=February 9, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100210052343/http://www.northjersey.com/news/83743942_Xanadu_s__3B__White_Knight__knows_how_to_get_things_done.html| archivedate=February 10, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In May 2010, the NJSEA handed the project over to the Related Companies, and the \"Xanadu\" name had been dropped, changing the name to \"The Meadowlands\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross Taking over Xanadu, Dumping Name |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/051410_Ross_taking_over_Xanadu_dumping_name.html|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=May 15, 2010 |accessdate=June 11, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100517090338/http://www.northjersey.com/news/051410_Ross_taking_over_Xanadu_dumping_name.html| archivedate=May 17, 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, the project's name was shortened from \"Meadowlands Xanadu\" to simply \"Meadowlands.\"<ref>[https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/xanadu_entertainment_project_r.html \"Stalled Meadowlands Xanadu project gets new funding, shortens name to just 'Meadowlands'\"]. ''The Star-Ledger''/NJ.com. May 14, 2010. Retrieved January 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2010, Colony Capital surrendered control of the development of the mall to five lenders. Four parties were noted to be interested in redeveloping the project.<ref>{{cite news |title=Panel will advise Gov. Christie on four potential suitors in Xanadu redevelopment |first=Ted |last=Sherman |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/panel_will_advise_gov_christie.html |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=November 21, 2010 |accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> ''The Wall Street Journal'' on December 24, 2010, reported that [[Triple Five Group]] signed a letter of intent to invest in and finish the stalled mall.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704278404576037862549228004?mod=googlenews_wsj | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]| first1=Eliot | last1=Brown | first2=Lisa | last2=Fleisher | title=Deal Revives New Jersey's Xanadu | date=December 24, 2010}}</ref> Triple Five proposed that the mall be expanded to include indoor amusement and a water park. Developers cut a deal with [[Deutsche Bank]] to provide an approximately $700 million loan to finish the project.<ref name=UCReporter/>\n\n[[File:Xanadu.JPG|thumb|right|The complex seen from the Meadowlands [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts|Sheraton]] in 2009]]\nOn February 1, 2011, after a record-breaking month of snow for the area,<ref>[http://www.accuweather.com/blogs/news/story/44999/snowstorm-shatters-new-york-ci.asp \"Snowstorm Shatters New York City, Philadelphia Records\"]. AccuWeather.com. January 27, 2011.</ref> a 50- to 60-foot-long section of the eastern wall had buckled, and a horizontal crease was apparent on the complex's indoor ski slope. Two days later, on February 3, after workers were attempting to melt snow from the ski slope's roof, ice build-up caused the eastern wall to fail and suffer a partial collapse along an approximately {{convert|150|ft|-1|adj=on}} length of roof.<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite news|author=Thomas, Lauren |title=More than 17 years in the making, American Dream megamall\u2019s story was shaped by retail\u2019s upheaval |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html|publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=October 22, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|archivedate=October 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023063919/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html}}</ref> Michael Beckerman, a spokesman for the project's lending group stated, \"The Lender Group is aware of the damage to the roof caused by excessive snow and ice, but does not feel the damage affects the integrity of the structure. As such, the group has filed an insurance claim, and once the weather turns warmer, it will assess the damages and fix whatever is necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ice buildup causes wall to buckle at Xanadu's snow dome |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/020311_Ice_buildup_causes_wall_to_buckle_at_Xanadus_snow_dome.html|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=February 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===American Dream===\nOn April 29, 2011, the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority completed a deal with [[Triple Five Group]], the owners of two of North America's largest malls: [[West Edmonton Mall]] and the [[Mall of America]],<ref name=NYTimes/> who had previously proposed \"MeadowFest America\" for the New Jersey site in 2002, before the contract was awarded to Mills Corporation.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> Triple Five assumed ownership of the mall and renamed it \"American Dream Meadowlands\", announcing a tentative opening date of early 2014, to coincide with [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] at [[MetLife Stadium]]. The deal was officially announced on May 3, 2011. Among the changes to the project would an expansion to 3 million square feet, an 8.5-acre indoor glass-domed amusement park, water parks, and an ice skating rink.<ref name=\"NorthJersey11.12.18\">{{Cite news|author=Katzban, Nicholas|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2018/11/12/american-dreams-indoor-water-park-takes-shape-body-slide-now-visible-meadowlands-nj/1981791002/|title=See the progress on the American Dream water park, now taking shape|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=November 12, 2018|access-date=March 9, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"NJHerald\">{{cite web|author=Henry, Samantha|date=May 3, 2011|url=https://www.njherald.com/story/14566878/xanadu-mall-project-to-get-new-name-big-expansion?template=art_print#|title=Xanadu mall project to get new name, big expansion|newspaper=[[New Jersey Herald]]|archivedate=|accessdate=March 17, 2019|archiveurl=}}</ref> In July 2012 [[DreamWorks Animation]] CEO [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] announced that a [[DreamWorks Water Park]] would open at the mall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/dreamworks-shrek-theme-park-meadowlands-new-jersey-east-rutherford--162072095.html|title=DreamWorks Plans 'Shrek' Theme Park at Stalled NJ Mall|publisher=[[Associated Press]]/[[NBC New York]]|accessdate=March 18, 2019|date=July 11, 2012|archivedate=May 20, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78VvVk5oR}}</ref> \n\nBy May 2013, progress on the project was delayed further by financing, permitting, and a lawsuit filed by the [[New York Giants]] and [[New York Jets]] over traffic concerns.<ref>Sherman, Ted (May 17, 2013). [http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/sports_authority_approved_amer.html#incart_river_default#incart_hbx#incart_best-of \"Sports Authority approves expanded American Dream proposal\"]. NJ.com.</ref> Triple Five officially took ownership of the mall on July 31, 2013, with construction set to start in late August of that year, despite the lawsuit.<ref name=NorthJersey8.2.13/> Construction officially began in November and the developer estimated it would take approximately 24 months to complete the project.<ref name=\"NYPost\">{{cite news|title=Stalled Meadowlands mall project is back on|newspaper=New York Post |url=https://nypost.com/2014/03/13/stalled-meadowlands-mall-project-is-back-on/|accessdate=March 13, 2013}}</ref> In April 2014, Triple Five released a revised design for the mall's exterior and confirmed a tentative opening date in late 2016,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brennan|first1=John|title=American Dream developers unveil long-awaited makeover, target 2016 opening|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/american-dream-developers-unveil-long-awaited-makeover-target-2016-opening-1.1004344|accessdate=June 20, 2014 |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> though by December 2014, it was reported that this would only be a partial opening.<ref>{{cite web|author=Gurfein, Laura|date=December 8, 2014|url=https://ny.racked.com/2014/12/8/7565387/american-dream-mall-new-jersey|title=NJ Megamall Confirms Tenants, from Saks to FAO Schwarz|publisher=[[Racked]]|accessdate=March 18, 2019|archivedate=August 2, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802203829/https://ny.racked.com/2014/12/8/7565387/american-dream-mall-new-jersey}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the New Jersey Local Finance Board approved a tax-sharing plan between [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]] and Triple Five.  In August 2015, the [[New Jersey Economic Development Authority]] reauthorized a $390 million potential tax break for the project.  These steps were intended to set the stage for a sale of up to $1 billion in government bonds to raise money to complete the project in time for its new projected completion in the second half of 2017.<ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/>\n\nIn April 2016, a planned bond issue fell through.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/04/16/american-dreams-meadowlands-financing/ |title=More Delays For The Meadowlands \u2018American Dream\u2019 Entertainment Complex | date=April 16, 2016 | publisher=[[WCBS-TV|CBS New York]] }}</ref> In July 2016, construction appeared to have stopped, the developers were trying to obtain $1 billion in additional financing, and the projected completion date had slipped again, to 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nj1015.com/will-american-dream-at-meadowlands-ever-become-a-reality/ |title=Will \u2018American Dream\u2019 at Meadowlands ever become a reality? | author=Matthau, David | date=July 11, 2016 | publisher=Townsquare Entertainment News (as New Jersey 101.5 radio)}}</ref> In August 2016, the [[New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority]] announced an $800 million bond issue intended to finance further construction of the mall.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/nj-state-news/two-state-agencies-look-to-restart-stalled-meadowlands-project-1.1640548 |title=Two N.J. agencies look to restart stalled American Dream Meadowlands project | author=Brennan, John |author2=Moss, Linda | date=August 5, 2016 | publisher=NorthJersey.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Xanadu Hackensack River.JPG|thumb|right|upright=1.6|American Dream seen from across the [[Hackensack River]] in [[Secaucus, New Jersey]] in 2009]]\nIn September 2016, Triple Five Group announced that the indoor amusement park space would be occupied by [[Nickelodeon Universe]],<ref name=\"NorthJersey9.13.16\">{{cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2016/09/13/spongebob-ninja-turtles-sign-on-with-american-dream/93001992/|title=SpongeBob, Ninja Turtles sign on with American Dream |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=September 13, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> which would feature two world-record-holding roller coasters, the [[TMNT Shellraiser]], a [[Euro-Fighter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2017/12/world_record_roller_coasters_coming_to_american_dream_no_really.html|title=Meadowlands megamall to house pair of world record roller coasters|author=Jerde, Sara|date=December 5, 2017|publisher=NJ.com|archiveurl=|archivedate=|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Triple Five unveiled details on the proposed [[DreamWorks Waterpark]], which would feature the world's largest indoor wave pool and the world's second-tallest body slide.<ref name=NorthJersey11.12.18/> \n\n===Construction halts and resumes again===\nOn December 22, 2016, work on the project stopped again. Financing from the 2016 bond issue was delayed until 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2016/12/22/american-dream-quiet-2016-end-looms/95758664/ | title=American Dream Meadowlands quiet as 2016 end looms | author=Brennan, John | date=December 22, 2016 | publisher = North Jersey Media Group }}</ref> In May of that year, the developers secured $1.67 billion in construction financing from a syndicate led by [[JPMorgan Chase]],<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=May 19, 2017|last=Morris|first=Keiko|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/developer-of-meadowlands-complex-secures-construction-financing-1495244449|title=Developer of Meadowlands Complex Secures Construction Financing}}</ref> and by the following month, work had resumed.<ref name=NorthJersey6.29.16/>\n\nIn June 2018, the developer indicated that most of the complex was scheduled to open in early 2019, though the water park would open at the end of 2019.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> In August 2018, a Triple Five executive, Tony Amrlin, specified that the project was 68% complete and would open in April 2019.<ref name=\"HudReporter9.30.18\">{{cite news|url=https://hudsonreporter.com/2018/09/30/former-xanadu-project-to-open-in-april/|title=Former 'Xanadu' project to open in April|last1=Dia|first1=Hannington|date=September 30, 2018|work=The Hudson Reporter|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> That November, it was announced that September 2019 would be the water park's opening date.<ref name=NorthJersey11.12.18/>\n\nIn August 2018, Triple Five revealed that [[H&M]], [[Uniqlo]], and [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]] would open stores at the mall;<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave|date=August 24, 2018|publisher=[[94.5 PST]]|title=15 RETAILERS ANNOUNCED FOR NJ MEGA MALL|url=https://wpst.com/15-retailers-announced-for-nj-mega-mall/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=August 24, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824232138/https://wpst.com/15-retailers-announced-for-nj-mega-mall/}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com5.20.19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/05/american-dream-opening-delayed-again-but-now-there-will-be-birds-bunnies-and-instagram-moments.html|title=American Dream opening delayed -- again. But now there will be birds, bunnies and Instagram moments.|author=Pries, Allison|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520225259/https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/05/american-dream-opening-delayed-again-but-now-there-will-be-birds-bunnies-and-instagram-moments.html|archivedate=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> the three stores would be those companies' largest mall-based flagship locations.<ref name=\"NJFamily\">{{cite web|author=Pire, Taryn|date=November 27, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Family|title=The Latest Developments of American Dream Meadowlands Have Us Beyond Psyched|url=https://www.njfamily.com/the-latest-developments-of-american-dream-meadowlands-have-us-beyond-psyched/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XX9PcGD}}</ref> On September 25, 2018, the [[New Jersey Hall of Fame]] announced that they would be permanently moving to American Dream.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beckerman |first1=Jim |title=New Jersey Hall of Fame finally finds a permanent home \u2014 at American Dream |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2018/09/26/10-million-nj-hall-fame-breaks-ground-meadowlands-american-dream/1411326002/ |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |publisher=NJ.com|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> On March 12, 2019, [[Barneys New York]] announced that it would open a flagship store at the mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/east-rutherford/2019/03/12/barneys-new-york-open-flagship-american-dream-nj/3142912002/l|title=Barneys New York To Open At American Dream|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=March 12, 2019|publisher=NorthJersey.com|language=en|access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref> However, the firm announced in October 2019 that as part of its Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, it would close most of its stores, it was not announced till March 10 2020 that  Barney's New York  pulled out of American Dream due to the company going bankrupt .<ref>{{cite web|author=Ciment, Shoshy|date=October 17, 2019|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/barneys-new-york-struggling-edging-toward-bankruptcy-report-photos-2019-7|title=We went to Barneys' Manhattan flagship to see why it's the latest department store to reportedly consider bankruptcy|magazine=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate= November 22, 2019|quote=On October 16, bankruptcy filings revealed plans for a new $271 million deal in which Authentic Brands Group \u2014 owner of brands like Nine West, Nautica, and Volcom \u2014 and investment firm B. Riley Financial would buy the Barneys name and assets. All stores would close under the deal, though talks are ongoing for a few, including the massive Madison Avenue flagship, to stay open, a source told the Wall Street Journal.|archivedate=July 20, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720190934/https://www.businessinsider.com/barneys-new-york-struggling-edging-toward-bankruptcy-report-photos-2019-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glossy.co/fashion/delaying-a-grand-opening-makes-sense-coronavirus-threatens-american-dreams-retail-launch|title='Delaying a grand opening makes sense': Coronavirus threatens American Dream's retail launch|date=2020-03-10|website=Glossy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 [[Triple Five Group|Triple 5]] dropped Meadowlands from the name American Dream.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corkery|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/business/american-dream-meadowlands-mall.html|title=After 15 Years, Dream Mall Finally Becomes a Reality|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 28, 2020|last2=Maheshwari|first2=Sapna|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2019, Governor [[Phil Murphy]] indicated that the mall complex would open that June,<ref>{{Cite web|author=Pries, Allison|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-is-still-happening-but-not-as-soon-as-you-hoped.html|title=American Dream mega-mall is still happening, but not as soon as you hoped|publisher=NJ.com|date=March 8, 2019|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> but on March 25, Triple 5 Group announced that the project would open in August.<ref name=\"NJ.com3.25.19\">{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison Pries|date=March 25, 2019|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-officially-announces-a-late-summer-opening.html|title=American Dream mega-mall officially announces a 'late summer' opening|publisher=NJ.com|accessdate=May 8, 2019|archivedate=April 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403001946/https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-officially-announces-a-late-summer-opening.html}}</ref> On May 20, Triple Five announced that the mall's opening date had again been moved to later in the year,<ref>{{cite web|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=Associated Press/[[WABC-TV]]|title=Long-delayed Meadowlands megamall in New Jersey delayed yet again|url=https://abc7ny.com/business/long-delayed-nj-meadowlands-megamall-delayed-yet-again/5310003/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 201|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XYhiZM3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=[[NBC New York]]|title=Long-Delayed New Jersey Meadowlands Megamall Now Slated to Open in Fall|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Long-Delayed-Meadowlands-Megamall-Open-Fall-New-Jersey-510170371.html|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XYCGfET}}</ref> and that some retailers would not open until the 2019 holiday season or early 2020. It revealed that tenants would include [[Tiffany & Co.]], [[Watches of Switzerland]], [[Dolce & Gabbana]], [[Moncler]] and the experimental retailer Fourpost, which operates a store at Triple Five's other mall property, The Mall of America. Triple Five also revealed more of the complex's attractions and common areas, which are set to feature rotating art installations and attractions.<ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/><ref name=\"MSN\">{{cite web|author=Hubbard, Daniel|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=[[MSN]]|title=American Dream Meadowlands Pushes Opening Date Back \u2013 Again|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/lifestyle/lifestyle-buzz/american-dream-meadowlands-pushes-opening-date-back-\u2014-again/ar-AABDCaT#page=2|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XZolzO5}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 2019, officials from Triple Five announced that the opening date of the mall would be October 25.<ref name=NorthJersey7.3.19/> Later that month, ''[[Crain's New York Business]]'' reported that the Asian-American supermarket chain [[H Mart]] would open a {{convert|35000|sqft|adj=on}} store at American Dream, which would include a \"Market Eatery\" venue for top national and international food concepts and chefs, as well as live music and events.<ref name=\"CrainsNY\">{{cite web|author=Beltran, Lizeth|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/real-estate/h-mart-open-american-dream-megamall|title=H Mart to open at American Dream megamall|magazine=[[Crain's New York Business]]|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archivedate=July 18, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718162120/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/real-estate/h-mart-open-american-dream-megamall}}</ref>\n\n===Completion and opening===\nOn September 20, 2019, Triple Five announced that the mall would open in four stages it refers to as \"chapters\". In October 2019, the mall's much-criticized colorful exterior was repainted white. Triple Five also announced that the ski slope would be covered in a mural painted by a [[Canadian]] artist collective, set to be completed in Spring and Summer 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/09/06/american-dream-mega-mall-ski-slope-gets-makeover/2233417001/ |title=Eyesore no more: American Dream's ski slope gets much-anticipated face-lift |author=Anzidei, Melanie |work=North Jersey Media Group |date=September 6, 2019 |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> Much of the facade facing the Turnpike would be covered in dynamic [[LED displays]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://therealdeal.com/sna-displays-selected-to-provide-led-technology-for-american-dream-project/ |title=SNA Displays Selected to Provide LED Technology for American Dream Project |author=SNA Displays |work=The Real Deal |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2019, the mall opened its first chapter, an ice-skating rink and a Nickelodeon amusement park.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/business/american-dream-meadowlands-mall.html|title=After 15 Years, Dream Mall Finally Becomes a Reality|last=Corkery|first=Michael|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 18, 2019|last2=Maheshwari|first2=Sapna|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The theme park contains more than 35 rides and attractions, including three roller coasters that broke world records when they opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html|title=More than 17 years in the making, American Dream megamall's story was shaped by retail's upheaval|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=October 22, 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> The next chapter, the [[DreamWorks Water Park]], was set to open on November 27, 2019.<ref name=\"NJcom.9.20.19\" /><ref name=\"NJFamily\" /> However, on November 21, 2019, the company announced that they were postponing the water park opening until March 19, 2020.<ref name=NJ.com11.21.19>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison|title=DreamWorks Water Park at American Dream mall delays opening|publisher=NJ.com|date=November 21, 2019|url= https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/11/dreamworks-waterpark-at-american-dream-mall-delays-opening.html|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=NJ.com02.27.20>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|publisher=NJ.com|date=February 27, 2020|url= https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The next chapter, the Big Snow American Dream ski slope, opened on December 5, 2019 The mall's enclave of luxury stores called The Collections is planned to open in September 2020.<ref name=NJ.com02.27.20/>\n\nOn February 19, 2020, [[Sea Life]] announced it would open its location at American Dream on April 23, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/aquarium-at-american-dream-mega-mall-sets-opening-date.html|title=Aquarium at American Dream mega-mall sets opening date|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=February 19, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2020, Out of This World Blacklight Mini Golf opened its location at American Dream.\n\nOn  March 13, 2020, it was announced that [[Forever 21]] pulled out of American Dream, due to the company filing for bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2020/03/american-dream-stays-course-on-opening-despite-outbreak/|title=American Dream Stays Course on Opening Despite Outbreak|last=March 12|first=Chava Gourarie|last2=Pm|first2=2020 4:09|date=2020-03-12|website=Commercial Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus-caused temporarily close and rethink of retail, more entertainment===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n==Main attractions==\n[[File:Xanaduparking.jpg|thumb|right|One of the complex's parking garages in 2009]]\nAmerican Dream consists of 55 percent entertainment facilities and 45 percent retail locations.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n\n===General===\n* Six distinctive grand atriums flooded with natural light. One includes an extensive garden with bird-filled aviaries and rabbit fields; another will be an entertainment hub.<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=\"NorthJersey5.20.19\">{{cite web|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=NorthJersey.com|title=You'll have to wait longer still to visit American Dream, but now it'll have rabbit fields|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2019/05/20/american-dream-mall-opening-date-pushed-back-fall-more-stores-revealed/3741075002/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 20, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520190125/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2019/05/20/american-dream-mall-opening-date-pushed-back-fall-more-stores-revealed/3741075002/}}</ref>\n* Albero dei Sogni/Secret Garden \u2013 a tree-like sculpture consisting of more than 75,000 LED lights and 25,000 leaves that play music during intervals several times a day<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* A 60-foot fashion fountain that can be converted into a catwalk in seconds<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* One-of-a-kind, Instagram-worthy museums, where visitors can pay to spend an afternoon exploring themed rooms with extravagant props and backdrops<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/06/stalled-by-coronavirus-american-dream-rethinks-its-future.html|last=cnbc.com|first=Lauren Thomas {{!}} for CNBC, LLC.|date=April 6, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Instagram]] moments \u2013 areas designed specifically for social media photography<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/>\n* Museum-scale interiors displaying artwork by local and international artists<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/>\n* Trampoline park\n* Plans to construct several hotels with 3,500 hotel rooms, that will connect directly to the rest of the project via skybridges.\n\n===Shopping===\n* 450 retail shops like '''[[Abercrombie & Fitch|Abercombie Kids]], [[\u00c5land]], [[Aldo Group|Aldo]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] 4-Star, [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]], [[Arc'teryx]], [[Aritzia]], [[Asics]], [[Bath & Body Works]], [[Banana Republic]], [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]], [[Century 21 (department store)|Century 21]], [[Charlotte Russe]], [[Columbia Sportswear]], [[Dolce Gabbana]], [[Designer Brands|Designer Shoe Warehouse]], [[Eddie Bauer]], [[Express, Inc.|Express]], Evereve, [[Foot Locker]], [[H&M]], [[Hollister Co.|Hollister]], [[It'Sugar]], [[Levi's]], [[Lush (company)|Lush]], [[Mac Cosmetics]], [[Old Navy]], [[PacSun]], [[Primark]], [[Samsonite]], [[Sephora]], [[Sarah Jessica Parker|SJP by Sarah Jessica Parker]], [[Skechers]], [[Sunglass Hut]], [[Torrid (clothing retailer)|Torrid]], [[Tumi]], [[UGG (brand)|UGG]], [[Ulta Beauty]],  [[Uniqlo]], Urban Planet, [[Vans]], [[Victoria's Secret]]/[[Pink (Victoria's Secret)|Victoria's Secret Pink]], Yoyoso, [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]]''' and more.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/>\n* Six [[anchor retail tenants]] with more than {{convert|50,000|ft2}} each<!--Do not input store names, per [[WP:CRYSTAL]]--><ref name=\"NorthJersey8.11.15\">{{cite news|url=http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/11948/american-dream-meadowlands-by-the-numbers/|title=American Dream Meadowlands by the numbers|last=Brennan|first=John|date=August 11, 2015|publisher=NorthJersey.com|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207221924/http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/11948/american-dream-meadowlands-by-the-numbers/|archive-date=February 7, 2016|url-status=}}</ref>\n* 12 major retailers ({{convert|20,000|to|50,000|ft2|disp=sqbr}} each)<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* 339 smaller shops (up to {{convert|20,000|ft2|disp=sqbr}})<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* '''A 35,000 square foot [[H Mart]] Asian-American supermarket and restaurant''': The location will feature national and international Asian food concepts, an on-site bakery and a stage with live music, craft cocktails, entertainment and weekly events <ref name=CrainsNY/>\n* A 20,000 square foot Fourpost store: The new store will feature rotating selections of fresh brands and inventory, local eats, and interactive, family-friendly environments.\n*'''The Collections at American Dream''': The mall's enclave of luxury stores like [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] (anchor), [[Herm\u00e8s]], [[Tiffany & Co.]], [[Dolce Gabbana]], [[Moncler]], and [[Watches of Switzerland]].\n\n===Dining===\n* More than 100 eateries like '''Jarana''' (first location), '''Charley's Philly Steaks''', '''1st RND''', '''Likkle More Jerk''', '''[[Manchu Wok]]''', '''Pora Foods''' (first location), '''[[Thai Express]]''' and '''[[Wendy's]]'''.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/>\n* 21 full-service restaurants<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/><ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* 45 specialty food retailers<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* '''[[Coca-Cola]] Eats''': This branded dining destination will seat approximately 800 guests and offer a wide array of local and global cuisines. \n* '''Grisini''': The Grisini Hospitality Group which incorporates Grisini Coffee shop, Food Hall and Market concepts will be opening its first stores, two coffee shops and a European-style food hall at American Dream. Grisini by Chef Marc Murphy is expected to open in 2020 for lunch and dinner. In addition to the food hall, Grisini will also feature a coffee shop, and a marketplace providing retail products and packaged, prepared food for meals on-the-go.\n* '''Munchies by [[Vice Media|Vice]]''': The food hall will include 18 hot spots from the best local and regional food sources, a cooking studio, two revolving kitchens showcasing up-and-coming chefs, and more.\n* '''The Dining Terrance''': The Dining Terrace will feature more than 20 full-service restaurants complete with views of Manhattan and an upscale, alfresco-like setting.\n* '''Kosher Food Hall''': The first ever strictly kosher food market in a North American retail and entertainment destination.\n* '''[[Oreo]] TWISITD''': A new Oreo caf\u00e9 concept at the 3-floor It'Sugar candy department store.  TWISTiD will provide guests with a view of the DreamWorks Water Park and Nickelodeon Universe theme park.\n\n===Entertainment===\n[[File:Big Snow American Dream 01.jpg|thumb|The \"Switchback\" and \"Northern Lights\" trails at [[Big Snow American Dream]]]]\n* One of the six atriums is a 60-foot space that will serve as an entertainment hub for live events<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* The Rink: Indoor [[NHL]]-sized ice rink<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[Nickelodeon Universe#American Dream Meadowlands|Nickelodeon Universe]]: An indoor theme park<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[DreamWorks Water Park]]: A year-round indoor water park<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NorthJersey9.13.16/>\n* A 2,400\u20133,000 seat performing arts and concert venue<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/>\n* [[Big Snow American Dream]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/11/american-dreams-huge-indoor-ski-slope-is-hiring-300-workers.html|title=American Dream\u2019s huge indoor ski slope is hiring 300 workers|last=Pries|first=Allison|date=November 7, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newjersey.news12.com/story/41379853/three-trails-four-lifts-and-more-new-trail-map-released-for-big-snow-american-dream |title=Three trails, four lifts, and more! New trail map released for Big SNOW American Dream |last=|first=|date=November 27, 2019|publisher=news12.com|access-date=November 27, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/wyckoff/heres-trail-map-american-dreams-indoor-ski-park |title=Heres The Trail Map For American Dreams Indoor Ski Park |last=Redmond|first=Kemberly|date=November 26, 2019|publisher=patch.com|access-date=November 27, 2019|language=en}}</ref>   \u2013 an indoor ski slope<ref name=CNBC/>\n* Two miniature 18-hole golf courses, One is [[Angry Birds]] Not-So-Mini Golf Club, Another one is Out of It's World: Blacklight Mini Golf which opened it's location at March 7, 2020.<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref>Bagli, Charles V. (May 31, 2017). [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/nyregion/looking-for-another-1-1-billion-to-finish-an-amusement-mall.html?_r=0 \"Looking for (Another) $1.1 Billion to Finish an Amusement Mall\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://storage.googleapis.com/americandream-comingsoon-uploads/American-Dream-Angry-Birds-Mini-Golf_FINAL.pdf|title=ANGRY BIRDS INDOOR MINI GOLF TO OPEN AT AMERICAN DREAM|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[Cinemex|CMX]] [[Cobb Theatres|Cin\u00e9bistro]] premium dine-in cinema<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2015/10/luxury_movie_chain_to_open_at_american_dream_megam.html|title=Dine-in theater with private rooms and '4D' coming to American Dream megamall|publisher=NJ.com|access-date=September 15, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[KidZania]] family entertainment center<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref>{{cite |url = http://www.njbiz.com/article/20170404/NJBIZ01/170409956/american-dream-making-progress-kidzania-latest-to-lease-space | title=American Dream making progress: KidZania latest to lease space |first1=Mario |last1=Marroquin |publisher=NorthJersey.com| date= April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lucky Strike Lanes|Lucky Strike]]'s For the Win: The arcade-style gastropub will feature gaming, gastropub cuisine, craft beer, bowling, live music and more.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2016/06/meadowlands_megamall_announces_its_next_big_entertainment_venue.html |title=Meadowlands megamall announces its next big entertainment venue |publisher=NJ.com |date=June 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pennlive.com/life/2020/02/there-will-be-more-than-500-tenants-at-this-massive-shopping-center-in-nj-here-are-more-than-80-of-them.html |title=Around 450 stores, restaurants and places to play will (eventually) fill this massive N.J. mall: What are they? |publisher=pennlive.com |date=Feb 13, 2020 |accessdate=Feb 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Legoland Discovery Center]]<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=\"lego\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2015/10/aquarium_legoland_coming_to_meadowlands_complex.html |title=Aquarium, Legoland coming to Meadowlands complex |publisher=NJ.com| date=October 1, 2015 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Sea Life Aquarium]]<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=lego/>\n* Climbzone indoor rock climbing facility<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[Mirror Maze]] attraction<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n\n====Observation Wheel====\nAnnounced in February 2008, [[PepsiCo]] agreed to pay $100 million for a 10-year sponsorship of Pepsi Globe, a [[London Eye]]-style ferris wheel built facing the [[New Jersey Turnpike]] that would measure {{Convert|287|ft|abbr=on}}, and feature 26 glass enclosed, climate controlled gondolas that would take 20 people on 25-minute rides. Its planned opening was in 2009.<ref name=\"Record-Pepsi\">{{cite news|title=Pepsi Globe Delayed |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/business/Pepsi_Globe_delayed.html |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=May 14, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430020145/http://www.northjersey.com/business/Pepsi_Globe_delayed.html |archivedate=April 30, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com16YRJourney\">Pries, Allison (June 2018). [https://www.nj.com/bergen/2018/06/american_dream_how_did_a_swath_of_land_in_the_mead.html \"American Dream: The 16-year (and counting) journey of a mega-mall that might actually open kind of soon\"]. NJ.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> It would be the largest Ferris wheel in America,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newatlas.com/americas-largest-ferris-wheel/8859/|title=America\u2019s largest Ferris wheel|website=newatlas.com|language=en|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> but it drew much criticism<ref name=\"NJSpotlight\">Stainton, Lilo H. (September 22, 2015). [https://www.njspotlight.com/stories/15/09/21/explainer-is-meadowlands-american-dream-starting-to-come-true/ \"EXPLAINER: AMERICAN DREAM STARTING TO COME TRUE IN THE MEADOWLANDS?\"]. NJ Spotlight. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> from local residents and politicians who viewed it as an [[eyesore]],<ref name=NJ.com16YRJourney/> and who voiced concerns about both safety and its obstruction of views of Manhattan's skyline across the Hudson River, which they feared would hurt property values and damage the image of the local communities.<ref>Gruen, Mary (March 6, 2008). [https://www.nj.com/business/2008/03/xanadu_ferris_wheel_spoils_vie.html \"Bergen properties hit by Xanadu ferris wheel\"]. NJ.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> PepsiCo eventually withdrew their sponsorship of the ferris wheel, which would no longer be branded with that company's name or logo.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> By 2015, the ferris wheel was still being planned, but had been rechristened the \"Observation Wheel,\"<ref name=NJSpotlight/><ref>Brennan, John (May 4, 2017). [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/05/02/long-and-winding-road-has-been-american-dream-meadowlands/100670280/ \"The long and winding road that has been American Dream Meadowlands\"]. NorthJersey.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> and would be only {{Convert|235|ft|abbr=on}} feet in diameter, though it would retain the same number of gondolas.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/>\n\n==Transportation and parking==\n\n=== Public transport ===\nPublic transportation to American Dream Meadowland's on-site bus hub and train station<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/> is provided by [[NJ Transit]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander, Dan|title=NJ Transit bus service to American Dream mega mall at Meadowlands|url=https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/|publisher=[[New Jersey 101.5]] |date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 4, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904000036/https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/}}</ref> Direct local and express bus service to American Dreams includes the following [[NJ Transit Bus Operations|NJ Transit Bus]] lines:<ref name=\"NJTransit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njtransit.com/var/var_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=AmericanDreamTo|title=American Dream|publisher=New Jersey Transit|location=Newark|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 22, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922013254/https://www.njtransit.com/var/var_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=AmericanDreamTo}}</ref>\n* 85 Hoboken/Union City&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 355 New York&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 356 Secaucus Junction&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 703 Paterson/Passaic&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 772 Hackensack&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n\nFor travel there by rail, the [[Meadowlands station]] is the western terminus for the [[Meadowlands Rail Line]] located at the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] next to American Dream.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=Project077To |title=Meadowlands Rail Station |publisher=[[New Jersey Transit]]|location=[[Newark, New Jersey]]|date=January 2008 |accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 4, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904000036/https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/}}</ref> However, that line is not being operated daily for American Dream, but solely during events at the stadium. NJ Transit stated that daily rail service could be added \"once the rail system is resilient enough that doing so won\u2019t adversely affect NJ Transit commuters.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/|title=NJ Transit bus service to American Dream mega mall at Meadowlands|last=Alex|first=Dan|last2=er|website=New Jersey 101.5|language=en|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMulti-modal service is provided by [[NY Waterway]], which provides a package service consisting of ferry service from Manhattan to [[Weehawken Port Imperial]] in [[Weehawken, New Jersey|Weehawken]], followed by a bus for the remaining 6.5 miles to the mall. Passengers can also take the bus without a ferry connection.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wilson, Colleen|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2019/10/09/ferry-bus-service-announced-american-dream-october-25/3919480002/|title=American Dream ferry-bus service from Manhattan will start on mega mall's opening day|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=October 9, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=October 12, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012175507/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2019/10/09/ferry-bus-service-announced-american-dream-october-25/3919480002/}}</ref>\n\n=== Private transport ===\nMotorists traveling to the location are accommodated with a 33,000-space parking lot.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/> American Dream initially announced plans to charge for daily parking, but plans to charge for parking were cancelled; American Dream will only charge for parking when events are occurring at MetLife Stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/5695363/|title=Visitors now allowed to park for free at American Dream mall in New Jersey|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[WABC-TV]]|location= New York|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019|archivedate=November 15, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115135702/https://abc7ny.com/5695363/}}</ref> The parking garage is set to incorporate a smart IT interface developed by [[Atos]], which would place sensors and [[Bluetooth]]-enabled beacons to help customers locate empty parking spots near the stores and attractions that want to visit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/ridgewood/visiting-american-dream-theres-app |title=Tech To Help Park, Navigate American Dream |author=Redmond, Kimberley |work=Patch.com |date=November 19, 2019 |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Dream will run a fleet of several helicopters to offer luxury transportation for wealthy international tourists and residents from the roof of the mall's [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] store.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fickenscher, Lisa|title=Long-delayed NJ mall featuring helicopter transport from NYC seeking luxury tenants|url=https://nypost.com/2019/04/07/long-delayed-nj-mall-featuring-helicopter-transport-from-nyc-seeking-luxury-tenants/|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|location=New York|date=April 7, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=April 8, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408030308/https://nypost.com/2019/04/07/long-delayed-nj-mall-featuring-helicopter-transport-from-nyc-seeking-luxury-tenants/}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[File:MeadowlandsXanaduFromPlane2.jpg|thumb|left|The mall under construction, with [[MetLife Stadium]] under construction as well, as seen from an airplane on April 19, 2008]]\nOpposition to the idea of building a permanent shopping center within the Meadowlands Sports Complex centered on traffic and environmental concerns. The project is being built on state-owned land, as the NJSEA is a state agency, and $81.3 million was spent on transportation improvements such as new off and on ramps and a train station at the Sports Complex.<ref name=NYTimes4.23.08/> Some have also called the mall a \"colossal real estate nightmare\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Giants Stadium demolition \u2013 can they take down Xanadu next? |first=Brian |last=Donohue |url=http://www.nj.com/ledgerlive/index.ssf/2010/02/giants_stadium_demolition.html |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=February 4, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://archive.today/20100208215548/http://www.nj.com/ledgerlive/index.ssf/2010/02/giants_stadium_demolition.html| archivedate=February 8, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and \"perhaps the worst retail failure ever\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible Second Life for Stalled Xanadu Project? Consider Trip to 'Jersey Shore'|first=Peter |last=Applebome |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/25/nyregion/25towns.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=January 24, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128072251/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/25/nyregion/25towns.html |archivedate=January 28, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe project was also criticized by environmentalists who issued a complaint on July 10, 2012 that draft permits approved by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] would allow five more acres of wetlands to be destroyed for the project, which had already filled in more than seven. Jeff Tittel, director of the New Jersey chapter of the [[Sierra Club]], stated, \"This project will increase traffic and flooding while taking business away from existing stores. This project is the Super Bowl of Sprawl and the American Dream is a commuter\u2019s nightmare.\"<ref name=NJ.com7.10.12/>\n\nIn May 2006, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) announced it was formally investigating the Mills Corporation, the original developer of the property, after it announced that it was restating four years of earnings due to executive misconduct and accounting errors. Later in the year, an analyst at [[Bank of America Securities]] pushed Mills Corporation to drop the project, citing the signs of cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Analyst tells Mills to drop Xanadu |first=Prashant |last=Gopal |first2=John |last2=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/page.php?qstr=eXJpcnk3ZjczN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXkzJmZnYmVsN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXk2OTc0MzAxJnlyaXJ5N2Y3MTdmN3ZxZWVFRXl5Mg==|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=August 12, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] expressed concerns about the height of the Ferris wheel, which at the time was planned to be {{Convert|287|ft|abbr=on}}, which the FAA feared would affect local air traffic to and from [[Teterboro Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FAA seeks shorter Ferris wheel at Xanadu |first=Nick |last=Clunn |url=http://www.northjersey.com/page.php?qstr=eXJpcnk3ZjczN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXkzJmZnYmVsN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXk3MjA5ODMzJnlyaXJ5N2Y3MTdmN3ZxZWVFRXl5Mg== |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=October 19, 2007 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the [[New York Giants]] and the [[New York Jets]] filed a lawsuit against Triple Five, seeking to halt construction. The lawsuit claimed that the addition of amusement and water parks at the site would adversely affect traffic at MetLife stadium on days when home games were played there,<ref name=\"NJ.com7.10.12\">{{cite news|author=Sherman, Ted|title=Developers of American Dream mall seek to sack Giants and Jets lawsuit|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2012/07/developers_of_the_american_dre.html|publisher=The Associated Press/NJ.com|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y1OiKDz}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com3.12.14\">{{cite news |title=Jets, Giants agree to drop American Dream lawsuit|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2014/03/jets_giants_agree_to_drop_american_dream_lawsuit.html|publisher=The Associated Press/NJ.com|date=March 12, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y14nCvH}}</ref> specifically 16 Sundays out of the year, the day of the week that [[Bergen County]]'s [[Blue Law]] prohibits shopping, though not amusement parks.<ref name=\"WallStreetJournal\">{{cite news|author=Haddon, Heather|title=Jets, Giants Sue Over Mall Near Stadium|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323728204578515673045639386|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=September 11, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911074317/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323728204578515673045639386}}</ref> The teams contended that while the mall would be closed on Sundays, the amusement park would not, which would create traffic jams on game days when up to 25,000 vehicles would park at the complex. Traffic studies conducted by the team estimated that 7,700 spots would be added by the project; the developers countered that the amusement parks would add only 63 more cars, claiming that local residents would be wise enough to avoid visiting on a game day, and most tourists would take the rail link rather than drive.<ref>{{cite news|author=Porter, David|title=Dueling Meadowlands mall traffic studies offered|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100157070|publisher=CNBC|date=November 11, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y6ZKD1e}}</ref><ref>Brennan, John (December 7, 2012). [http://www.northjersey.com/news/182489961_Small_step_forward_for_American_Dream_parks.html \"Small step forward for American Dream parks\"]. NorthJersey.com.</ref> In July 2012 Triple Five countersued for what it called an improper campaign by the teams to preserve their monopoly at the site while dissuading potential lenders from investing.<ref name=NJ.com7.10.12/><ref name=NJ.com3.12.14/> On March 12, 2014 the parties reached a tentative settlement, agreeing to drop their lawsuits, which allowed the project to move forward.<ref name=NJ.com3.12.14/> \n\nIn February 2015, U.S. federal prosecutors accused [[Joe Ferriero]], former chairman of the Bergen County Democratic Organization and New Jersey political power broker, of bribery, fraud, and racketeering charges.<ref>Sampson, Peter (February 27, 2015) [http://www.northjersey.com/news/hard-work-or-abuse-of-power-joseph-ferriero-corruption-trial-opens-with-widely-varying-portrayals-1.1279161 \"Hard work or abuse of power? Joseph Ferriero corruption trial opens with widely varying portrayals\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref> The charges included an allegation that Mills Corporation paid Ferriero $1.7 million over the course of several years as a bribe or extortion to maintain Ferriero's political support for their development bid on the Xanadu project against rivals Hartz Mountain Industries. James Dausch, a former Mills Corporation employee testified that the $1.7 million was paid for Ferriero's consulting, not as a bribe. Dausch's testimony detailed much of the development bid process, including paid lobbyists positioning Mills with Governor [[Jim McGreevey]], then Governor [[Richard Codey]], as well as with Senator [[Robert Menendez]].<ref>Sampson, Peter (March 10, 2015 [http://www.northjersey.com/news/developer-testifying-in-ferriero-trial-says-1-7m-wasn-t-a-bribe-1.1286191 \"Developer testifying in Ferriero trial says $1.7M wasn't a bribe\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref> In April 2015, Ferriero was found guilty on five counts, but not on the Mills Corporation racketeering charges.<ref>Sampson, Peter (April 16, 2015) [http://www.northjersey.com/news/ferriero-found-guilty-on-racketeering-wire-fraud-and-bribery-related-charges-1.1310961 \"Ferriero convicted on racketeering count; ex-Democratic chief used political clout for profit\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref>\n\nThe State of New Jersey, through the New Jersey Sports and Exhibition Authority, issued $1.15 billion in tax-free bonds to support the project. These unrated bonds yielded 6.625% when first issued. They were part of a suite of tax concessions negotiated with the state and the City of Hackensack.<ref name=\"nj170621\">{{cite news |first1=John |last1=Brennan |title=American Dream Meadowlands bonds interest rate set as revival looms |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/06/21/american-dream-meadowlands-bonds-interest-rate-set-revival-looms/395607001/ |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=June 21, 2017|accessdate =July 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Patriot Place]]\n* [[Titletown District]]\n* [[List of largest shopping malls in the world|List of the world's largest shopping malls]]\n* [[List of largest shopping malls in the United States]]\n* [[American Dream Miami]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|American Dream Meadowlands}}\n* {{official website|www.americandream.com}}\n* Lyne, Jack (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20060314180611/http://www.conway.com/ssinsider/snapshot/sf030804.htm $1.3B, 4.8MSF Xanadu Project Will Transform 'Swamps of Jersey']. Site Selection.\n* Douglass, David (October 5, 2004). [https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20041005005704/en/Meadowlands-Xanadu-Unveils-Wave-Major-Tenants-Consumer \"Meadowlands Xanadu Unveils First Wave of Major Tenants, Consumer Brands and Entertainment Experiences\"]. [[Business Wire]]\n* Ma, Myles (June 19, 2012). [http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2012/06/american_dream_mall_may_not_be_open_for_meadowlands_super_bowl.html \"American Dream Meadowlands shopping center may not be open for 2014 Super Bowl in New Jersey\"]. NJ.com.\n{{Meadowlands Sports Complex|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Shopping malls in New Jersey}}\n{{New York City Malls}}\n\n[[Category:Meadowlands Sports Complex]]\n[[Category:East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the mall in New Jersey|proposed facilities of the same name|American Dream Mall (disambiguation){{!}}American Dream Mall}}\n{{short description|retail and entertainment complex in East Rutherford, NJ}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name = American Dream\n| logo = American Dream Meadowlands Logo.png\n| image = Indoor ski slope at American Dream in Meadowlands.jpg\n| image_width = 270px\n| caption = [[Big Snow American Dream]] ski slope\n| owner = [[Triple Five Group]]\n| location = [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]], [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States]]\n| opening_date = October 25, 2019, ([[Nickelodeon Universe]] and Ice Rink)<br>December 5, 2019, ([[Big Snow American Dream|Big Snow]]) ([[DreamWorks Water Park]])<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2020/02/27/american-dream-nj-water-park-some-retail-stores-open/4897595002/|title=Opening date for American Dream water park and some retail stores announced|website=North Jersey|language=en|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><br>September 2020, (retail stores and dining) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=2020-02-27|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> \n| number_of_stores = 450+\n| number_of_anchors = 6\n| floor_area = {{convert|3000000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| architect = \n| parking = 33,000 spaces<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison |date=December 2, 2018|url=https://expo.nj.com/news/erry-2018/12/8df3facb447815/waterslides-are-being-installe.html|title=Waterslides are being installed at the American Dream mega-mall and it is glorious|publisher=[[NJ.com]]|accessdate=March 17, 2019 |archivedate= |archiveurl= }}</ref>\n| publictransit = [[file:25_railtransportation.svg|11px|Railway Train]] {{rint|njt|60px}} [[Meadowlands station]] <br> {{bus icon|12px}} {{rint|njt|60px}} [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (1\u201399)|85]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (300\u2013399)|355]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (300\u2013399)|356]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (700\u2013799)|703]], [[List of NJ Transit bus routes (700\u2013799)|772]]\n| website = {{URL|www.americandream.com}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|48|36|N|74|04|03|W|region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''American Dream''' ('''AD''') is a retail and entertainment complex in the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], [[United States]], that will have over 450 stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/03/nyregion/dream-of-a-mall-starts-to-rise-out-of-a-meadowlands-nightmare.html?_r=0|title=Huge Mall Rising at Troubled Site in North Jersey|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 2, 2015|author=Bagli, Charles V. |accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> The first and second of four opening stages occurred on October 25, 2019, and on December 5, 2019.<ref name=\"NorthJersey7.3.19\">{{cite web|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=July 3, 2019|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/07/03/american-dream-open-oct-25-officials-say/1639522001/|title=It's finally happening: American Dream mall will open Oct. 25|newspaper=[[NorthJersey.com]]|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archivedate=July 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703201850/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/07/03/american-dream-open-oct-25-officials-say/1639522001/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/12/indoor-ski-slope-at-american-dream-is-open-heres-a-first-look-inside.html|title=Indoor ski slope at American Dream is open. Here\u2019s a first look inside.|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=December 5, 2019|website=nj|language=en|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The remaining opening stages was supposed to open on March 19, 2020. However, due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic (commonly known as COVID-19)]], the opening of the final stages was delayed once more until further notice. <ref name=NorthJersey7.3.19/><ref name=\"NJcom.9.20.19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/09/american-dream-reveals-plans-theme-park-will-open-before-water-park-ski-slope.html|title=American Dream\u2019s theme park to open in October. For other attractions, you'll have to wait.|last=Pries|first=Allison|date=September 20, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe project was first proposed in 2003 by the [[Mills Corporation]] as the ''Meadowlands Xanadu'', with construction beginning in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/arts-entertainment/inside-american-dream-mega-mall-new-jersey|title=Inside American Dream, The Mega-Mall New Jersey Maybe Didn't Need|last=Lampen|first=Claire|date=November 5, 2019|website=Gothamist|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> After the Mills Corporation's bankruptcy in 2007, the project was taken over by [[Colony Capital]]. In May 2009, construction stalled due to the [[bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers]]. [[Triple Five Group]] announced intent to take over the mall in May 2011, and on July 31, 2013, officially gained control of the mall and the surrounding site.<ref name=\"NorthJersey8.2.13\">Nicholaides, Kelly (August 2, 2013). [http://www.northjersey.com/news/217977711_American_Dream_Meadowlands_handed_over_former_Xanadu_project_in_East_Rutherford.html \"American Dream Meadowlands handed over former Xanadu project in East Rutherford\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref>\n\nAfter a series of ownership changes, financing issues, construction delays, and legal challenges, construction stopped again in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/03/03/american-dream-cranes-tell-sad-story/98688642/|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=March 3, 2017 |author=Brennan, John |title=American Dream cranes tell sad story}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |author=Bagli, Charles V. |title=After Many Missed Deadlines, New Jersey Megamall Is Again Taking Shape |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/13/nyregion/after-many-missed-deadlines-new-jersey-megamall-is-again-taking-shape.html |quote= |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 13, 2016 }}</ref> In late June 2017, construction had resumed, after new financing had been secured,<ref name=\"NorthJersey6.29.16\">{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/06/29/american-dream-meadowlands-finalizes-its-2-8-b-financing/440364001/ |title=American Dream Meadowlands finalizes $2.8B in construction financing; work resumes |author=Brennan, John |date=June 29, 2016 |publisher=North Jersey Media Group |accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first1=Sara |last1=Jerde |title=Construction reportedly resumes at Meadowlands megamall |url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2017/07/construction_reportedly_resumes_at_meadowlands_megamall.html |quote= |newspaper=[[The Star Ledger]]|date=July 11, 2017}}</ref> though the project would suffer a series of \"chronically delayed\" opening dates. Among the attractions that opened in 2019 were the [[Nickelodeon Universe#American Dream Meadowlands|Nickelodeon Universe]] theme park in October and the [[Big Snow American Dream]] ski slope in December; the [[DreamWorks Water Park]], scheduled to open in November, was supposed to open March 19, 2020. However, due to the coronavirus outbreak, the waterpark's opening date got delayed once again. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=February 27, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Meadowlands Mills (1994&ndash;2002)===\n[[File:Xanadu Indoor Ski.JPG|thumb|left|The exterior of the indoor ski slope in 2009]]\nThe [[Mills Corporation]] first began working on plans for a mall in the [[New Jersey Meadowlands]] in 1994. Meadowlands Mills, as it was called, would have been constructed on the Empire Tract, an area of {{convert|587|acre}} of wetlands in [[Carlstadt, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"MeadowlandsConservation\">{{cite web|url=http://meadowlandsconservationtrust.org/success-stories/richard-p-kane/|title=Richard P. Kane|publisher=Meadowlands Conservation Trust|language=en|location=[[Lyndhurst, New Jersey]]|accessdate=March 17, 2019|archivedate=January 25, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125130935/http://meadowlandsconservationtrust.org/success-stories/richard-p-kane/}}</ref> The tract was owned by Empire Ltd., a company which had purchased the land in 1961 and had been planning a major development since 1987.<ref>Hendry, Cheryl Ann. [https://scholarworks.montana.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1/12784/HendryC0517.pdf?sequence=4 \"Finding Nature in an Industrial Swamp: A Case Study of New Jersey's Hackensack Meadowlands\"], p. 196, [[Montana State University]], 2017.</ref> The commercial development would have consisted of {{convert|2.1|e6sqft|m2}} of retail space, a hotel, and {{convert|1|e6sqft|m2}} of office space on {{convert|206|acre}} of the tract. To mitigate the heavy environmental impact, the remainder of the tract would have been converted into stormwater [[retention basin]]s.<ref name=NYTimes2000/>\n\nAfter Empire and Mills announced their proposal in 1996, the project quickly became controversial and faced opposition from a variety of environmental and conservationist groups, as well as the tract's congressman, [[Steve Rothman]]. Opponents stated that the mall would have a devastating impact on the ecological health of the area, while the Mills Corporation defended its plans by arguing that the land was already devastated by [[pesticide]] usage and invasive [[Phragmites|common reeds]].<ref name=\"NYTimes2000\">Jacobs, Andrew (December 18, 2000). [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/18/nyregion/shops-vs-swamps-meadowlands-debate-over-huge-shopping-mall-marked-rival-claims.html \"Shops vs. Swamps In the Meadowlands; Debate Over a Huge Shopping Mall Marked by Rival Claims and Spin\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>[https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1998-04-15-1998105029-story.html \"Mall plan forces a look at future of Meadowlands; Developers argue that parts of N.J. wetland are not worth saving\"], ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', April 15, 1998.</ref>\n\nThe [[Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] opposed the project after studying its potential environmental impact. However, the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] conducted its own study which contradicted the EPA's findings and stated that the project was not a threat to the Meadowlands area.<ref name=NYTimes2000/> New Jersey governor [[Donald DiFrancesco]] announced plans to protect the area in 2001, encouraging the Mills Corporation to look at other potential sites in the region.<ref>Jacobs, Andrew (March 21, 2001). [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/21/nyregion/difrancesco-seeks-to-save-meadowlands.html \"DiFrancesco Seeks to Save Meadowlands\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref> His successor, [[Jim McGreevey]], informed Mills the following year that the state government would not provide permits for the mall, effectively ending the project as originally proposed.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080313164040/http://www.hackensackriverkeeper.org/Meadowlands_Xanadu.html \"The Facts Regarding the Conservation of the Empire Tract\"], Hackensack Riverkeeper, 2005.</ref> The Empire Tract was later permanently protected by the Meadowlands Conservation Trust, which purchased it in 2005 and renamed it the Richard P. Kane Natural Area after a noted New Jersey conservationist.<ref name=MeadowlandsConservation/>\n\n===Meadowlands Xanadu (2002&ndash;2010)===\nIn July 2002, the [[New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority]] (NJSEA) issued a [[request for proposal]] for a project in the area that was then the parking lot of the [[Continental Airlines Arena]]. The request was inspired by the Meadowlands Mills project as well as by plans to move the [[New Jersey Nets]] out of the arena, and involved significantly less environmental damage because it would be built on already developed land. The Mills Corporation retooled its earlier proposal for Meadowlands Mills to fit the new site, and partnered with [[Mack-Cali Realty Corporation]] to design Meadowlands Xanadu, a major multi-use development which would incorporate a renovated Continental Airlines Arena.<ref>[https://www.rst2.org/njheps/meadowlandsquest/teterboro/index.html \"Xanadu Project (Continental Airlines Arena Site Redevelopment)\"], ''Teterboro Online'', 2005.</ref> The name was taken from Mills Corporation's [[Madrid Xanad\u00fa]], a shopping mall in Spain which opened in 2003.\n\nNJSEA accepted several other proposals for developing the site. [[Westfield Group]] proposed Arena Place, an \"urban village\" and \"town square\" built around the arena. [[Hartz Mountain Industries]] and [[Forest City Realty Trust]] submitted plans for Expo Park at the Meadowlands, featuring an outlet mall, a convention center, an indoor racetrack, and three hotel buildings.<ref name=\"NorthJersey9.6.15\">{{cite news|last1=Brennan|first1=John|title=American Dream Meadowlands nears pivotal moment: the $1B bond sale|url=http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/12060/american-dream-meadowlands-nears-pivotal-moment-the-1b-bond-sale/|accessdate=September 16, 2015|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=September 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915071000/http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/12060/american-dream-meadowlands-nears-pivotal-moment-the-1b-bond-sale/|archive-date=September 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Triple Five Group]] proposed MeadowFest America, which planned an [[adaptive reuse]] of the arena to create a retail and entertainment complex.<ref name=\"nyt-sep2002\">Smothers, Ronald (September 20, 2002). [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/20/nyregion/new-ideas-unveiled-for-site-of-meadowlands-arena.html \"New Ideas Unveiled for Site of Meadowlands Arena\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com6.19.18\">Pries, Allison. [https://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2018/06/american_dream_how_did_a_swath_of_land_in_the_mead.html \"American Dream: The 16-year (and counting) journey of a mega-mall that might actually open kind of soon\"]. NJ.com. June 19, 2018. Retrieved January 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nOther proposals focused on the project's location in the Meadowlands Sports Complex. [[International Speedway Corporation]] envisioned plans for Sports City America, a development centered around the proposed Garden State International Speedway, a [[NASCAR]] racetrack seating 80,000. A consortium that included [[Paul Newman]], [[Carl Haas]], and [[Mario Andretti]] proposed Liberty Speedway and Family Theme Park, combining a racetrack with an amusement park and connecting the two with a monorail.<ref name=nyt-sep2002/><ref>[http://www.teterboro-online.com/xanadu/proposals/prop1.shtml \"Continental Airlines Arena site Redevelopment Proposals\"], ''Teterboro Online'', 2002.</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, the authority's board chose Mills Corporation and Mack-Cali's plan over the other two finalists, Westfield Group and Hartz Mountain Industries.<ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/> The project was billed by Mills chairman and executive officer Laurence E. Siegel as \"...a new standard for bringing lifestyle, recreation, sports and family entertainment offerings together in one location.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority Approves Meadowlands Xanadu Development Agreement |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20031203005654/en/Jersey-Sports-Exposition-Authority-Approves-Meadowlands-Xanadu|newspaper=Business Wire |date=December 3, 2003 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> Ground was broken on the complex on September 29, 2004,<ref>{{cite news |title=Meadowlands Xanadu Announces Official Groundbreaking Ceremony Date of September 29, 2004 |url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2004/Aug/1062449.htm |newspaper=Business Wire |date=August 3, 2004 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> and, at the time, was expected to open two years later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mills Corp. and Mack-Cali Sign Deal to Create 4.76m s/f Meadowlands Sport and Leisure Arena |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-112314739.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104034213/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-112314739.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 4, 2012 |newspaper=Real Estate Weekly |date=December 17, 2003 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, [[Colony Capital]] purchased the project from Mills Corporation for $500 million and pushed the projected opening to 2008.<ref name=NYTimes/><ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/><ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/>\n\nBy 2008, the colorfully gaudy exterior of the building, which is visible from the [[New Jersey Turnpike]] and [[New Jersey Route 3]], began to draw criticism as an eyesore,<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> [[Richard Codey]], president of the New Jersey State Senate at the time, called the structure \"yucky-looking\".<ref name=\"NYTimes4.23.08\">{{cite news |title=Is a Giant Mall an Eyesore? Developer Urges Patience |first=Terry |last=Pristin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/23/realestate/commercial/23xanadu.html |newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 23, 2008 |accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, then-Governor Chris Christie called it \"an offense to the eyes as you drive up the turnpike\" and \"by far the ugliest damn building in New Jersey, and maybe America.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Fix Xanadu? The Problem May Be Where to Begin|date=April 1, 2011|first=Richard|last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/02/nyregion/02xanadu.html?_r=0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/nj_ugliest_building_fix_vfSvwNyiWghUjFmPYWbSiN|title=NJ's 'ugliest-building' fix|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=March 25, 2011}}</ref> After acquiring the project, Triple Five indicated the exterior would be repainted in a different color scheme.<ref name=\"NorthJersey2.21.13\">Brennan, John (February 21, 2013). [http://www.northjersey.com/eastrutherford/american_dream_bergen_improvement_authority.html \"Work on American Dream complex set to resume in March, official says\"]. NorthJersey.com.</ref>\n\n[[File:Xanadumeadowlandslogo.jpg|thumb|The former logo of the complex]]\nIn May 2009, construction on Xanadu, which was nearly 80% complete<ref name=UCReporter>Sullivan, Al (August 25, 2013). \"A dream comes true?\" ''[[The Union City Reporter]]''. pp 5 and 12.</ref> (and whose common areas were about 88% complete), came to a halt after a subsidiary of bankrupt [[Lehman Brothers]] missed payments, causing other lenders to withdraw from the project, and lost $500&nbsp;million worth of construction funding. While developers stated the mall was 70% leased,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/20/realestate/commercial/20xanadu.html |title=At $2.3 Billion, This Mall Could Be Too Big to Fail |first=Terry |last=Pristin |newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 16, 2010}}</ref> it is unknown how many retailers stayed leased while the mall was delayed.\n\nIn March 2009, the retailer [[Cabela's]] announced that it did not plan to open its Meadowlands location for another year,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2009/03/cabelas_delays_opening_for_its.html |title=Cabela's delays opening for its Xanadu store|publisher=NJ.com |date=March 9, 2009 }}</ref> and subsequently gave \"late 2010\" as an estimated opening date.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/environment/specialreports/Cabelas_Xanadu_wont_open_until_late_2010.html |title=Key Xanadu tenant describes \"late 2010\" for Xanadu debut |first=John |last=Brennan |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=August 3, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100412170352/http://www.northjersey.com/news/environment/specialreports/Cabelas_Xanadu_wont_open_until_late_2010.html| archivedate=April 12, 2010 | url-status= dead}}</ref> It would later pull out of the project by November 2010, following the collapse of Lehman Brothers and a halt to construction.<ref>Bagli, Charles V. (November 26, 2010). [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/27/nyregion/27Xanadu.html \"A New Push to Rescue Xanadu Mall Project\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, [[Stephen M. Ross|Stephen Ross]], owner of [[The Related Companies]] in Manhattan, stated that he could finish the project by the end of 2010, possibly with a new name and look.<ref>{{cite news |title=Xanadu\u2019s $3B \u2018White Knight\u2019 knows how to get things done |first=Andrew |last=Tangel |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/83743942_Xanadu_s__3B__White_Knight__knows_how_to_get_things_done.html |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=February 7, 2010 |accessdate=February 9, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100210052343/http://www.northjersey.com/news/83743942_Xanadu_s__3B__White_Knight__knows_how_to_get_things_done.html| archivedate=February 10, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In May 2010, the NJSEA handed the project over to the Related Companies, and the \"Xanadu\" name had been dropped, changing the name to \"The Meadowlands\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ross Taking over Xanadu, Dumping Name |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/051410_Ross_taking_over_Xanadu_dumping_name.html|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=May 15, 2010 |accessdate=June 11, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100517090338/http://www.northjersey.com/news/051410_Ross_taking_over_Xanadu_dumping_name.html| archivedate=May 17, 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, the project's name was shortened from \"Meadowlands Xanadu\" to simply \"Meadowlands.\"<ref>[https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/xanadu_entertainment_project_r.html \"Stalled Meadowlands Xanadu project gets new funding, shortens name to just 'Meadowlands'\"]. ''The Star-Ledger''/NJ.com. May 14, 2010. Retrieved January 2, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2010, Colony Capital surrendered control of the development of the mall to five lenders. Four parties were noted to be interested in redeveloping the project.<ref>{{cite news |title=Panel will advise Gov. Christie on four potential suitors in Xanadu redevelopment |first=Ted |last=Sherman |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/panel_will_advise_gov_christie.html |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=November 21, 2010 |accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> ''The Wall Street Journal'' on December 24, 2010, reported that [[Triple Five Group]] signed a letter of intent to invest in and finish the stalled mall.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704278404576037862549228004?mod=googlenews_wsj | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]| first1=Eliot | last1=Brown | first2=Lisa | last2=Fleisher | title=Deal Revives New Jersey's Xanadu | date=December 24, 2010}}</ref> Triple Five proposed that the mall be expanded to include indoor amusement and a water park. Developers cut a deal with [[Deutsche Bank]] to provide an approximately $700 million loan to finish the project.<ref name=UCReporter/>\n\n[[File:Xanadu.JPG|thumb|right|The complex seen from the Meadowlands [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts|Sheraton]] in 2009]]\nOn February 1, 2011, after a record-breaking month of snow for the area,<ref>[http://www.accuweather.com/blogs/news/story/44999/snowstorm-shatters-new-york-ci.asp \"Snowstorm Shatters New York City, Philadelphia Records\"]. AccuWeather.com. January 27, 2011.</ref> a 50- to 60-foot-long section of the eastern wall had buckled, and a horizontal crease was apparent on the complex's indoor ski slope. Two days later, on February 3, after workers were attempting to melt snow from the ski slope's roof, ice build-up caused the eastern wall to fail and suffer a partial collapse along an approximately {{convert|150|ft|-1|adj=on}} length of roof.<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite news|author=Thomas, Lauren |title=More than 17 years in the making, American Dream megamall\u2019s story was shaped by retail\u2019s upheaval |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html|publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=October 22, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|archivedate=October 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023063919/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html}}</ref> Michael Beckerman, a spokesman for the project's lending group stated, \"The Lender Group is aware of the damage to the roof caused by excessive snow and ice, but does not feel the damage affects the integrity of the structure. As such, the group has filed an insurance claim, and once the weather turns warmer, it will assess the damages and fix whatever is necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ice buildup causes wall to buckle at Xanadu's snow dome |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/020311_Ice_buildup_causes_wall_to_buckle_at_Xanadus_snow_dome.html|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=February 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===American Dream===\nOn April 29, 2011, the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority completed a deal with [[Triple Five Group]], the owners of two of North America's largest malls: [[West Edmonton Mall]] and the [[Mall of America]],<ref name=NYTimes/> who had previously proposed \"MeadowFest America\" for the New Jersey site in 2002, before the contract was awarded to Mills Corporation.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> Triple Five assumed ownership of the mall and renamed it \"American Dream Meadowlands\", announcing a tentative opening date of early 2014, to coincide with [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] at [[MetLife Stadium]]. The deal was officially announced on May 3, 2011. Among the changes to the project would an expansion to 3 million square feet, an 8.5-acre indoor glass-domed amusement park, water parks, and an ice skating rink.<ref name=\"NorthJersey11.12.18\">{{Cite news|author=Katzban, Nicholas|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2018/11/12/american-dreams-indoor-water-park-takes-shape-body-slide-now-visible-meadowlands-nj/1981791002/|title=See the progress on the American Dream water park, now taking shape|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=November 12, 2018|access-date=March 9, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"NJHerald\">{{cite web|author=Henry, Samantha|date=May 3, 2011|url=https://www.njherald.com/story/14566878/xanadu-mall-project-to-get-new-name-big-expansion?template=art_print#|title=Xanadu mall project to get new name, big expansion|newspaper=[[New Jersey Herald]]|archivedate=|accessdate=March 17, 2019|archiveurl=}}</ref> In July 2012 [[DreamWorks Animation]] CEO [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] announced that a [[DreamWorks Water Park]] would open at the mall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/dreamworks-shrek-theme-park-meadowlands-new-jersey-east-rutherford--162072095.html|title=DreamWorks Plans 'Shrek' Theme Park at Stalled NJ Mall|publisher=[[Associated Press]]/[[NBC New York]]|accessdate=March 18, 2019|date=July 11, 2012|archivedate=May 20, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78VvVk5oR}}</ref> \n\nBy May 2013, progress on the project was delayed further by financing, permitting, and a lawsuit filed by the [[New York Giants]] and [[New York Jets]] over traffic concerns.<ref>Sherman, Ted (May 17, 2013). [http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/sports_authority_approved_amer.html#incart_river_default#incart_hbx#incart_best-of \"Sports Authority approves expanded American Dream proposal\"]. NJ.com.</ref> Triple Five officially took ownership of the mall on July 31, 2013, with construction set to start in late August of that year, despite the lawsuit.<ref name=NorthJersey8.2.13/> Construction officially began in November and the developer estimated it would take approximately 24 months to complete the project.<ref name=\"NYPost\">{{cite news|title=Stalled Meadowlands mall project is back on|newspaper=New York Post |url=https://nypost.com/2014/03/13/stalled-meadowlands-mall-project-is-back-on/|accessdate=March 13, 2013}}</ref> In April 2014, Triple Five released a revised design for the mall's exterior and confirmed a tentative opening date in late 2016,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brennan|first1=John|title=American Dream developers unveil long-awaited makeover, target 2016 opening|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/american-dream-developers-unveil-long-awaited-makeover-target-2016-opening-1.1004344|accessdate=June 20, 2014 |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> though by December 2014, it was reported that this would only be a partial opening.<ref>{{cite web|author=Gurfein, Laura|date=December 8, 2014|url=https://ny.racked.com/2014/12/8/7565387/american-dream-mall-new-jersey|title=NJ Megamall Confirms Tenants, from Saks to FAO Schwarz|publisher=[[Racked]]|accessdate=March 18, 2019|archivedate=August 2, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802203829/https://ny.racked.com/2014/12/8/7565387/american-dream-mall-new-jersey}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the New Jersey Local Finance Board approved a tax-sharing plan between [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]] and Triple Five.  In August 2015, the [[New Jersey Economic Development Authority]] reauthorized a $390 million potential tax break for the project.  These steps were intended to set the stage for a sale of up to $1 billion in government bonds to raise money to complete the project in time for its new projected completion in the second half of 2017.<ref name=NorthJersey9.6.15/>\n\nIn April 2016, a planned bond issue fell through.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/04/16/american-dreams-meadowlands-financing/ |title=More Delays For The Meadowlands \u2018American Dream\u2019 Entertainment Complex | date=April 16, 2016 | publisher=[[WCBS-TV|CBS New York]] }}</ref> In July 2016, construction appeared to have stopped, the developers were trying to obtain $1 billion in additional financing, and the projected completion date had slipped again, to 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nj1015.com/will-american-dream-at-meadowlands-ever-become-a-reality/ |title=Will \u2018American Dream\u2019 at Meadowlands ever become a reality? | author=Matthau, David | date=July 11, 2016 | publisher=Townsquare Entertainment News (as New Jersey 101.5 radio)}}</ref> In August 2016, the [[New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority]] announced an $800 million bond issue intended to finance further construction of the mall.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/nj-state-news/two-state-agencies-look-to-restart-stalled-meadowlands-project-1.1640548 |title=Two N.J. agencies look to restart stalled American Dream Meadowlands project | author=Brennan, John |author2=Moss, Linda | date=August 5, 2016 | publisher=NorthJersey.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Xanadu Hackensack River.JPG|thumb|right|upright=1.6|American Dream seen from across the [[Hackensack River]] in [[Secaucus, New Jersey]] in 2009]]\nIn September 2016, Triple Five Group announced that the indoor amusement park space would be occupied by [[Nickelodeon Universe]],<ref name=\"NorthJersey9.13.16\">{{cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2016/09/13/spongebob-ninja-turtles-sign-on-with-american-dream/93001992/|title=SpongeBob, Ninja Turtles sign on with American Dream |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=September 13, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> which would feature two world-record-holding roller coasters, the [[TMNT Shellraiser]], a [[Euro-Fighter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2017/12/world_record_roller_coasters_coming_to_american_dream_no_really.html|title=Meadowlands megamall to house pair of world record roller coasters|author=Jerde, Sara|date=December 5, 2017|publisher=NJ.com|archiveurl=|archivedate=|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Triple Five unveiled details on the proposed [[DreamWorks Waterpark]], which would feature the world's largest indoor wave pool and the world's second-tallest body slide.<ref name=NorthJersey11.12.18/> \n\n===Construction halts and resumes again===\nOn December 22, 2016, work on the project stopped again. Financing from the 2016 bond issue was delayed until 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2016/12/22/american-dream-quiet-2016-end-looms/95758664/ | title=American Dream Meadowlands quiet as 2016 end looms | author=Brennan, John | date=December 22, 2016 | publisher = North Jersey Media Group }}</ref> In May of that year, the developers secured $1.67 billion in construction financing from a syndicate led by [[JPMorgan Chase]],<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=May 19, 2017|last=Morris|first=Keiko|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/developer-of-meadowlands-complex-secures-construction-financing-1495244449|title=Developer of Meadowlands Complex Secures Construction Financing}}</ref> and by the following month, work had resumed.<ref name=NorthJersey6.29.16/>\n\nIn June 2018, the developer indicated that most of the complex was scheduled to open in early 2019, though the water park would open at the end of 2019.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> In August 2018, a Triple Five executive, Tony Amrlin, specified that the project was 68% complete and would open in April 2019.<ref name=\"HudReporter9.30.18\">{{cite news|url=https://hudsonreporter.com/2018/09/30/former-xanadu-project-to-open-in-april/|title=Former 'Xanadu' project to open in April|last1=Dia|first1=Hannington|date=September 30, 2018|work=The Hudson Reporter|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> That November, it was announced that September 2019 would be the water park's opening date.<ref name=NorthJersey11.12.18/>\n\nIn August 2018, Triple Five revealed that [[H&M]], [[Uniqlo]], and [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]] would open stores at the mall;<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave|date=August 24, 2018|publisher=[[94.5 PST]]|title=15 RETAILERS ANNOUNCED FOR NJ MEGA MALL|url=https://wpst.com/15-retailers-announced-for-nj-mega-mall/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=August 24, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824232138/https://wpst.com/15-retailers-announced-for-nj-mega-mall/}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com5.20.19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/05/american-dream-opening-delayed-again-but-now-there-will-be-birds-bunnies-and-instagram-moments.html|title=American Dream opening delayed -- again. But now there will be birds, bunnies and Instagram moments.|author=Pries, Allison|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520225259/https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/05/american-dream-opening-delayed-again-but-now-there-will-be-birds-bunnies-and-instagram-moments.html|archivedate=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> the three stores would be those companies' largest mall-based flagship locations.<ref name=\"NJFamily\">{{cite web|author=Pire, Taryn|date=November 27, 2018 |publisher=New Jersey Family|title=The Latest Developments of American Dream Meadowlands Have Us Beyond Psyched|url=https://www.njfamily.com/the-latest-developments-of-american-dream-meadowlands-have-us-beyond-psyched/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XX9PcGD}}</ref> On September 25, 2018, the [[New Jersey Hall of Fame]] announced that they would be permanently moving to American Dream.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beckerman |first1=Jim |title=New Jersey Hall of Fame finally finds a permanent home \u2014 at American Dream |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2018/09/26/10-million-nj-hall-fame-breaks-ground-meadowlands-american-dream/1411326002/ |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |publisher=NJ.com|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> On March 12, 2019, [[Barneys New York]] announced that it would open a flagship store at the mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/east-rutherford/2019/03/12/barneys-new-york-open-flagship-american-dream-nj/3142912002/l|title=Barneys New York To Open At American Dream|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=March 12, 2019|publisher=NorthJersey.com|language=en|access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref> However, the firm announced in October 2019 that as part of its Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, it would close most of its stores, it was not announced till March 10 2020 that  Barney's New York  pulled out of American Dream due to the company going bankrupt .<ref>{{cite web|author=Ciment, Shoshy|date=October 17, 2019|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/barneys-new-york-struggling-edging-toward-bankruptcy-report-photos-2019-7|title=We went to Barneys' Manhattan flagship to see why it's the latest department store to reportedly consider bankruptcy|magazine=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate= November 22, 2019|quote=On October 16, bankruptcy filings revealed plans for a new $271 million deal in which Authentic Brands Group \u2014 owner of brands like Nine West, Nautica, and Volcom \u2014 and investment firm B. Riley Financial would buy the Barneys name and assets. All stores would close under the deal, though talks are ongoing for a few, including the massive Madison Avenue flagship, to stay open, a source told the Wall Street Journal.|archivedate=July 20, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720190934/https://www.businessinsider.com/barneys-new-york-struggling-edging-toward-bankruptcy-report-photos-2019-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glossy.co/fashion/delaying-a-grand-opening-makes-sense-coronavirus-threatens-american-dreams-retail-launch|title='Delaying a grand opening makes sense': Coronavirus threatens American Dream's retail launch|date=2020-03-10|website=Glossy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 [[Triple Five Group|Triple 5]] dropped Meadowlands from the name American Dream.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corkery|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/business/american-dream-meadowlands-mall.html|title=After 15 Years, Dream Mall Finally Becomes a Reality|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 28, 2020|last2=Maheshwari|first2=Sapna|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2019, Governor [[Phil Murphy]] indicated that the mall complex would open that June,<ref>{{Cite web|author=Pries, Allison|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-is-still-happening-but-not-as-soon-as-you-hoped.html|title=American Dream mega-mall is still happening, but not as soon as you hoped|publisher=NJ.com|date=March 8, 2019|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> but on March 25, Triple 5 Group announced that the project would open in August.<ref name=\"NJ.com3.25.19\">{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison Pries|date=March 25, 2019|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-officially-announces-a-late-summer-opening.html|title=American Dream mega-mall officially announces a 'late summer' opening|publisher=NJ.com|accessdate=May 8, 2019|archivedate=April 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403001946/https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/03/american-dream-mega-mall-officially-announces-a-late-summer-opening.html}}</ref> On May 20, Triple Five announced that the mall's opening date had again been moved to later in the year,<ref>{{cite web|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=Associated Press/[[WABC-TV]]|title=Long-delayed Meadowlands megamall in New Jersey delayed yet again|url=https://abc7ny.com/business/long-delayed-nj-meadowlands-megamall-delayed-yet-again/5310003/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 201|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XYhiZM3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=[[NBC New York]]|title=Long-Delayed New Jersey Meadowlands Megamall Now Slated to Open in Fall|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Long-Delayed-Meadowlands-Megamall-Open-Fall-New-Jersey-510170371.html|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XYCGfET}}</ref> and that some retailers would not open until the 2019 holiday season or early 2020. It revealed that tenants would include [[Tiffany & Co.]], [[Watches of Switzerland]], [[Dolce & Gabbana]], [[Moncler]] and the experimental retailer Fourpost, which operates a store at Triple Five's other mall property, The Mall of America. Triple Five also revealed more of the complex's attractions and common areas, which are set to feature rotating art installations and attractions.<ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/><ref name=\"MSN\">{{cite web|author=Hubbard, Daniel|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=[[MSN]]|title=American Dream Meadowlands Pushes Opening Date Back \u2013 Again|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/lifestyle/lifestyle-buzz/american-dream-meadowlands-pushes-opening-date-back-\u2014-again/ar-AABDCaT#page=2|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78XZolzO5}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 2019, officials from Triple Five announced that the opening date of the mall would be October 25.<ref name=NorthJersey7.3.19/> Later that month, ''[[Crain's New York Business]]'' reported that the Asian-American supermarket chain [[H Mart]] would open a {{convert|35000|sqft|adj=on}} store at American Dream, which would include a \"Market Eatery\" venue for top national and international food concepts and chefs, as well as live music and events.<ref name=\"CrainsNY\">{{cite web|author=Beltran, Lizeth|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/real-estate/h-mart-open-american-dream-megamall|title=H Mart to open at American Dream megamall|magazine=[[Crain's New York Business]]|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019|archivedate=July 18, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718162120/https://www.crainsnewyork.com/real-estate/h-mart-open-american-dream-megamall}}</ref>\n\n===Completion and opening===\nOn September 20, 2019, Triple Five announced that the mall would open in four stages it refers to as \"chapters\". In October 2019, the mall's much-criticized colorful exterior was repainted white. Triple Five also announced that the ski slope would be covered in a mural painted by a [[Canadian]] artist collective, set to be completed in Spring and Summer 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2019/09/06/american-dream-mega-mall-ski-slope-gets-makeover/2233417001/ |title=Eyesore no more: American Dream's ski slope gets much-anticipated face-lift |author=Anzidei, Melanie |work=North Jersey Media Group |date=September 6, 2019 |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> Much of the facade facing the Turnpike would be covered in dynamic [[LED displays]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://therealdeal.com/sna-displays-selected-to-provide-led-technology-for-american-dream-project/ |title=SNA Displays Selected to Provide LED Technology for American Dream Project |author=SNA Displays |work=The Real Deal |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2019, the mall opened its first chapter, an ice-skating rink and a Nickelodeon amusement park.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/business/american-dream-meadowlands-mall.html|title=After 15 Years, Dream Mall Finally Becomes a Reality|last=Corkery|first=Michael|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 18, 2019|last2=Maheshwari|first2=Sapna|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The theme park contains more than 35 rides and attractions, including three roller coasters that broke world records when they opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/22/timeline-of-new-jerseys-american-dream-megamall-and-how-it-got-built.html|title=More than 17 years in the making, American Dream megamall's story was shaped by retail's upheaval|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=October 22, 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> The next chapter, the [[DreamWorks Water Park]], was set to open on November 27, 2019.<ref name=\"NJcom.9.20.19\" /><ref name=\"NJFamily\" /> However, on November 21, 2019, the company announced that they were postponing the water park opening until March 19, 2020.<ref name=NJ.com11.21.19>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison|title=DreamWorks Water Park at American Dream mall delays opening|publisher=NJ.com|date=November 21, 2019|url= https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/11/dreamworks-waterpark-at-american-dream-mall-delays-opening.html|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=NJ.com02.27.20>{{cite web|author=Pries, Allison|title=Water park, some stores at American Dream mall announce openings|publisher=NJ.com|date=February 27, 2020|url= https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/water-park-some-stores-at-american-dream-mall-announce-openings.html|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> The next chapter, the Big Snow American Dream ski slope, opened on December 5, 2019 The mall's enclave of luxury stores called The Collections is planned to open in September 2020.<ref name=NJ.com02.27.20/>\n\nOn February 19, 2020, [[Sea Life]] announced it would open its location at American Dream on April 23, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2020/02/aquarium-at-american-dream-mega-mall-sets-opening-date.html|title=Aquarium at American Dream mega-mall sets opening date|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=February 19, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2020, Out of This World Blacklight Mini Golf opened its location at American Dream.\n\nOn  March 13, 2020, it was announced that [[Forever 21]] pulled out of American Dream, due to the company filing for bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2020/03/american-dream-stays-course-on-opening-despite-outbreak/|title=American Dream Stays Course on Opening Despite Outbreak|last=March 12|first=Chava Gourarie|last2=Pm|first2=2020 4:09|date=2020-03-12|website=Commercial Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus-caused temporarily close and rethink of retail, more entertainment===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n==Main attractions==\n[[File:Xanaduparking.jpg|thumb|right|One of the complex's parking garages in 2009]]\nAmerican Dream consists of 55 percent entertainment facilities and 45 percent retail locations.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n\n===General===\n* Six distinctive grand atriums flooded with natural light. One includes an extensive garden with bird-filled aviaries and rabbit fields; another will be an entertainment hub.<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=\"NorthJersey5.20.19\">{{cite web|author=Anzidei, Melanie|date=May 20, 2019|publisher=NorthJersey.com|title=You'll have to wait longer still to visit American Dream, but now it'll have rabbit fields|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2019/05/20/american-dream-mall-opening-date-pushed-back-fall-more-stores-revealed/3741075002/|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 20, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520190125/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2019/05/20/american-dream-mall-opening-date-pushed-back-fall-more-stores-revealed/3741075002/}}</ref>\n* Albero dei Sogni/Secret Garden \u2013 a tree-like sculpture consisting of more than 75,000 LED lights and 25,000 leaves that play music during intervals several times a day<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* A 60-foot fashion fountain that can be converted into a catwalk in seconds<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* One-of-a-kind, Instagram-worthy museums, where visitors can pay to spend an afternoon exploring themed rooms with extravagant props and backdrops<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/06/stalled-by-coronavirus-american-dream-rethinks-its-future.html|last=cnbc.com|first=Lauren Thomas {{!}} for CNBC, LLC.|date=April 6, 2020|website=nj|language=en|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Instagram]] moments \u2013 areas designed specifically for social media photography<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/>\n* Museum-scale interiors displaying artwork by local and international artists<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=NorthJersey5.20.19/>\n* Trampoline park\n* Plans to construct several hotels with 3,500 hotel rooms, that will connect directly to the rest of the project via skybridges.\n\n===Shopping===\n* 450 retail shops like '''[[Abercrombie & Fitch|Abercombie Kids]], [[\u00c5land]], [[Aldo]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] 4-Star, [[American Eagle Outfitters|American Eagle]], [[Arc'teryx]], [[Aritzia]], [[Asics]], [[Bath & Body Works]], [[Banana Republic]], [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]], [[Century 21 (department store)|Century 21]], [[Charlotte Russe]], [[Columbia Sportswear]], [[Dolce Gabbana]], [[Designer Brands|Designer Shoe Warehouse]], [[Eddie Bauer]], [[Express, Inc.|Express]], Evereve, [[Foot Locker]], [[H&M]], [[Hollister Co.|Hollister]], [[It'Sugar]], [[Levi's]], [[Lush (company)|Lush]], [[Mac Cosmetics]], [[Old Navy]], [[PacSun]], [[Primark]], [[Samsonite]], [[Sephora]], [[Sarah Jessica Parker|SJP by Sarah Jessica Parker]], [[Skechers]], [[Sunglass Hut]], [[Torrid]], [[Tumi]], [[UGG (brand)|UGG]], [[Ulta Beauty]],  [[Uniqlo]], Urban Planet, [[Vans]], [[Victoria's Secret]]/[[Pink (Victoria's Secret)|Victoria's Secret Pink]], Yoyoso, [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]]''' and more.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/>\n* Six [[anchor retail tenants]] with more than {{convert|50,000|ft2}} each<!--Do not input store names, per [[WP:CRYSTAL]]--><ref name=\"NorthJersey8.11.15\">{{cite news|url=http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/11948/american-dream-meadowlands-by-the-numbers/|title=American Dream Meadowlands by the numbers|last=Brennan|first=John|date=August 11, 2015|publisher=NorthJersey.com|accessdate=August 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207221924/http://blog.northjersey.com/meadowlandsmatters/11948/american-dream-meadowlands-by-the-numbers/|archive-date=February 7, 2016|url-status=}}</ref>\n* 12 major retailers ({{convert|20,000|to|50,000|ft2|disp=sqbr}} each)<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* 339 smaller shops (up to {{convert|20,000|ft2|disp=sqbr}})<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* '''A 35,000 square foot [[H Mart]] Asian-American supermarket and restaurant''': The location will feature national and international Asian food concepts, an on-site bakery and a stage with live music, craft cocktails, entertainment and weekly events <ref name=CrainsNY/>\n* A 20,000 square foot Fourpost store: The new store will feature rotating selections of fresh brands and inventory, local eats, and interactive, family-friendly environments.\n*'''The Collections at American Dream''': The mall's enclave of luxury stores like [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] (anchor), [[Herm\u00e8s]], [[Tiffany & Co.]], [[Dolce Gabbana]], [[Moncler]], and [[Watches of Switzerland]].\n\n===Dining===\n* More than 100 eateries like '''Jarana''' (first location), '''Charley's Philly Steaks''', '''1st RND''', '''Likkle More Jerk''', '''[[Manchu Wok]]''', '''Pora Foods''' (first location), '''[[Thai Express]]''' and '''[[Wendy's]]'''.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/>\n* 21 full-service restaurants<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/><ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* 45 specialty food retailers<ref name=NorthJersey8.11.15/>\n* '''[[Coca-Cola]] Eats''': This branded dining destination will seat approximately 800 guests and offer a wide array of local and global cuisines. \n* '''Grisini''': The Grisini Hospitality Group which incorporates Grisini Coffee shop, Food Hall and Market concepts will be opening its first stores, two coffee shops and a European-style food hall at American Dream. Grisini by Chef Marc Murphy is expected to open in 2020 for lunch and dinner. In addition to the food hall, Grisini will also feature a coffee shop, and a marketplace providing retail products and packaged, prepared food for meals on-the-go.\n* '''Munchies by [[Vice Media|Vice]]''': The food hall will include 18 hot spots from the best local and regional food sources, a cooking studio, two revolving kitchens showcasing up-and-coming chefs, and more.\n* '''The Dining Terrance''': The Dining Terrace will feature more than 20 full-service restaurants complete with views of Manhattan and an upscale, alfresco-like setting.\n* '''Kosher Food Hall''': The first ever strictly kosher food market in a North American retail and entertainment destination.\n* '''[[Oreo]] TWISITD''': A new Oreo caf\u00e9 concept at the 3-floor It'Sugar candy department store.  TWISTiD will provide guests with a view of the DreamWorks Water Park and Nickelodeon Universe theme park.\n\n===Entertainment===\n[[File:Big Snow American Dream 01.jpg|thumb|The \"Switchback\" and \"Northern Lights\" trails at [[Big Snow American Dream]]]]\n* One of the six atriums is a 60-foot space that will serve as an entertainment hub for live events<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* The Rink: Indoor [[NHL]]-sized ice rink<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[Nickelodeon Universe#American Dream Meadowlands|Nickelodeon Universe]]: An indoor theme park<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[DreamWorks Water Park]]: A year-round indoor water park<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/><ref name=NorthJersey9.13.16/>\n* A 2,400\u20133,000 seat performing arts and concert venue<ref name=NorthJersey2.21.13/>\n* [[Big Snow American Dream]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/11/american-dreams-huge-indoor-ski-slope-is-hiring-300-workers.html|title=American Dream\u2019s huge indoor ski slope is hiring 300 workers|last=Pries|first=Allison|date=November 7, 2019|publisher=NJ.com|access-date=November 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newjersey.news12.com/story/41379853/three-trails-four-lifts-and-more-new-trail-map-released-for-big-snow-american-dream |title=Three trails, four lifts, and more! New trail map released for Big SNOW American Dream |last=|first=|date=November 27, 2019|publisher=news12.com|access-date=November 27, 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/wyckoff/heres-trail-map-american-dreams-indoor-ski-park |title=Heres The Trail Map For American Dreams Indoor Ski Park |last=Redmond|first=Kemberly|date=November 26, 2019|publisher=patch.com|access-date=November 27, 2019|language=en}}</ref>   \u2013 an indoor ski slope<ref name=CNBC/>\n* Two miniature 18-hole golf courses, One is [[Angry Birds]] Not-So-Mini Golf Club, Another one is Out of It's World: Blacklight Mini Golf which opened it's location at March 7, 2020.<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref>Bagli, Charles V. (May 31, 2017). [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/31/nyregion/looking-for-another-1-1-billion-to-finish-an-amusement-mall.html?_r=0 \"Looking for (Another) $1.1 Billion to Finish an Amusement Mall\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://storage.googleapis.com/americandream-comingsoon-uploads/American-Dream-Angry-Birds-Mini-Golf_FINAL.pdf|title=ANGRY BIRDS INDOOR MINI GOLF TO OPEN AT AMERICAN DREAM|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[Cinemex|CMX]] [[Cobb Theatres|Cin\u00e9bistro]] premium dine-in cinema<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2015/10/luxury_movie_chain_to_open_at_american_dream_megam.html|title=Dine-in theater with private rooms and '4D' coming to American Dream megamall|publisher=NJ.com|access-date=September 15, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* [[KidZania]] family entertainment center<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref>{{cite |url = http://www.njbiz.com/article/20170404/NJBIZ01/170409956/american-dream-making-progress-kidzania-latest-to-lease-space | title=American Dream making progress: KidZania latest to lease space |first1=Mario |last1=Marroquin |publisher=NorthJersey.com| date= April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lucky Strike Lanes|Lucky Strike]]'s For the Win: The arcade-style gastropub will feature gaming, gastropub cuisine, craft beer, bowling, live music and more.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2016/06/meadowlands_megamall_announces_its_next_big_entertainment_venue.html |title=Meadowlands megamall announces its next big entertainment venue |publisher=NJ.com |date=June 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pennlive.com/life/2020/02/there-will-be-more-than-500-tenants-at-this-massive-shopping-center-in-nj-here-are-more-than-80-of-them.html |title=Around 450 stores, restaurants and places to play will (eventually) fill this massive N.J. mall: What are they? |publisher=pennlive.com |date=Feb 13, 2020 |accessdate=Feb 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Legoland Discovery Center]]<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=\"lego\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2015/10/aquarium_legoland_coming_to_meadowlands_complex.html |title=Aquarium, Legoland coming to Meadowlands complex |publisher=NJ.com| date=October 1, 2015 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Sea Life Aquarium]]<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/><ref name=lego/>\n* Climbzone indoor rock climbing facility<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n* [[Mirror Maze]] attraction<ref name=NJ.com5.20.19/>\n\n====Observation Wheel====\nAnnounced in February 2008, [[PepsiCo]] agreed to pay $100 million for a 10-year sponsorship of Pepsi Globe, a [[London Eye]]-style ferris wheel built facing the [[New Jersey Turnpike]] that would measure {{Convert|287|ft|abbr=on}}, and feature 26 glass enclosed, climate controlled gondolas that would take 20 people on 25-minute rides. Its planned opening was in 2009.<ref name=\"Record-Pepsi\">{{cite news|title=Pepsi Globe Delayed |first=John |last=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/business/Pepsi_Globe_delayed.html |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=May 14, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430020145/http://www.northjersey.com/business/Pepsi_Globe_delayed.html |archivedate=April 30, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com16YRJourney\">Pries, Allison (June 2018). [https://www.nj.com/bergen/2018/06/american_dream_how_did_a_swath_of_land_in_the_mead.html \"American Dream: The 16-year (and counting) journey of a mega-mall that might actually open kind of soon\"]. NJ.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> It would be the largest Ferris wheel in America,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newatlas.com/americas-largest-ferris-wheel/8859/|title=America\u2019s largest Ferris wheel|website=newatlas.com|language=en|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> but it drew much criticism<ref name=\"NJSpotlight\">Stainton, Lilo H. (September 22, 2015). [https://www.njspotlight.com/stories/15/09/21/explainer-is-meadowlands-american-dream-starting-to-come-true/ \"EXPLAINER: AMERICAN DREAM STARTING TO COME TRUE IN THE MEADOWLANDS?\"]. NJ Spotlight. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> from local residents and politicians who viewed it as an [[eyesore]],<ref name=NJ.com16YRJourney/> and who voiced concerns about both safety and its obstruction of views of Manhattan's skyline across the Hudson River, which they feared would hurt property values and damage the image of the local communities.<ref>Gruen, Mary (March 6, 2008). [https://www.nj.com/business/2008/03/xanadu_ferris_wheel_spoils_vie.html \"Bergen properties hit by Xanadu ferris wheel\"]. NJ.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> PepsiCo eventually withdrew their sponsorship of the ferris wheel, which would no longer be branded with that company's name or logo.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/> By 2015, the ferris wheel was still being planned, but had been rechristened the \"Observation Wheel,\"<ref name=NJSpotlight/><ref>Brennan, John (May 4, 2017). [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/05/02/long-and-winding-road-has-been-american-dream-meadowlands/100670280/ \"The long and winding road that has been American Dream Meadowlands\"]. NorthJersey.com. Retrieved March 14, 2019.</ref> and would be only {{Convert|235|ft|abbr=on}} feet in diameter, though it would retain the same number of gondolas.<ref name=NJ.com6.19.18/>\n\n==Transportation and parking==\n\n=== Public transport ===\nPublic transportation to American Dream Meadowland's on-site bus hub and train station<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/> is provided by [[NJ Transit]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander, Dan|title=NJ Transit bus service to American Dream mega mall at Meadowlands|url=https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/|publisher=[[New Jersey 101.5]] |date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 4, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904000036/https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/}}</ref> Direct local and express bus service to American Dreams includes the following [[NJ Transit Bus Operations|NJ Transit Bus]] lines:<ref name=\"NJTransit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.njtransit.com/var/var_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=AmericanDreamTo|title=American Dream|publisher=New Jersey Transit|location=Newark|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 22, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922013254/https://www.njtransit.com/var/var_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=AmericanDreamTo}}</ref>\n* 85 Hoboken/Union City&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 355 New York&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 356 Secaucus Junction&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 703 Paterson/Passaic&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n* 772 Hackensack&nbsp;\u2013American Dream\n\nFor travel there by rail, the [[Meadowlands station]] is the western terminus for the [[Meadowlands Rail Line]] located at the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] next to American Dream.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.njtransit.com/tm/tm_servlet.srv?hdnPageAction=Project077To |title=Meadowlands Rail Station |publisher=[[New Jersey Transit]]|location=[[Newark, New Jersey]]|date=January 2008 |accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=September 4, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904000036/https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/}}</ref> However, that line is not being operated daily for American Dream, but solely during events at the stadium. NJ Transit stated that daily rail service could be added \"once the rail system is resilient enough that doing so won\u2019t adversely affect NJ Transit commuters.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nj1015.com/nj-transit-bus-service-to-american-dream-mega-mall-at-meadowlands/|title=NJ Transit bus service to American Dream mega mall at Meadowlands|last=Alex|first=Dan|last2=er|website=New Jersey 101.5|language=en|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMulti-modal service is provided by [[NY Waterway]], which provides a package service consisting of ferry service from Manhattan to [[Weehawken Port Imperial]] in [[Weehawken, New Jersey|Weehawken]], followed by a bus for the remaining 6.5 miles to the mall. Passengers can also take the bus without a ferry connection.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wilson, Colleen|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2019/10/09/ferry-bus-service-announced-american-dream-october-25/3919480002/|title=American Dream ferry-bus service from Manhattan will start on mega mall's opening day|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=October 9, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=October 12, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012175507/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/transportation/2019/10/09/ferry-bus-service-announced-american-dream-october-25/3919480002/}}</ref>\n\n=== Private transport ===\nMotorists traveling to the location are accommodated with a 33,000-space parking lot.<ref name=NJ.com12.2.18/> American Dream initially announced plans to charge for daily parking, but plans to charge for parking were cancelled; American Dream will only charge for parking when events are occurring at MetLife Stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/5695363/|title=Visitors now allowed to park for free at American Dream mall in New Jersey|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[WABC-TV]]|location= New York|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019|archivedate=November 15, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115135702/https://abc7ny.com/5695363/}}</ref> The parking garage is set to incorporate a smart IT interface developed by [[Atos]], which would place sensors and [[Bluetooth]]-enabled beacons to help customers locate empty parking spots near the stores and attractions that want to visit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/ridgewood/visiting-american-dream-theres-app |title=Tech To Help Park, Navigate American Dream |author=Redmond, Kimberley |work=Patch.com |date=November 19, 2019 |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Dream will run a fleet of several helicopters to offer luxury transportation for wealthy international tourists and residents from the roof of the mall's [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] store.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fickenscher, Lisa|title=Long-delayed NJ mall featuring helicopter transport from NYC seeking luxury tenants|url=https://nypost.com/2019/04/07/long-delayed-nj-mall-featuring-helicopter-transport-from-nyc-seeking-luxury-tenants/|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|location=New York|date=April 7, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019|archivedate=April 8, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190408030308/https://nypost.com/2019/04/07/long-delayed-nj-mall-featuring-helicopter-transport-from-nyc-seeking-luxury-tenants/}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[File:MeadowlandsXanaduFromPlane2.jpg|thumb|left|The mall under construction, with [[MetLife Stadium]] under construction as well, as seen from an airplane on April 19, 2008]]\nOpposition to the idea of building a permanent shopping center within the Meadowlands Sports Complex centered on traffic and environmental concerns. The project is being built on state-owned land, as the NJSEA is a state agency, and $81.3 million was spent on transportation improvements such as new off and on ramps and a train station at the Sports Complex.<ref name=NYTimes4.23.08/> Some have also called the mall a \"colossal real estate nightmare\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Giants Stadium demolition \u2013 can they take down Xanadu next? |first=Brian |last=Donohue |url=http://www.nj.com/ledgerlive/index.ssf/2010/02/giants_stadium_demolition.html |newspaper=The Star-Ledger |date=February 4, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://archive.today/20100208215548/http://www.nj.com/ledgerlive/index.ssf/2010/02/giants_stadium_demolition.html| archivedate=February 8, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and \"perhaps the worst retail failure ever\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible Second Life for Stalled Xanadu Project? Consider Trip to 'Jersey Shore'|first=Peter |last=Applebome |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/25/nyregion/25towns.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=January 24, 2010 |accessdate=February 21, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128072251/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/25/nyregion/25towns.html |archivedate=January 28, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe project was also criticized by environmentalists who issued a complaint on July 10, 2012 that draft permits approved by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] would allow five more acres of wetlands to be destroyed for the project, which had already filled in more than seven. Jeff Tittel, director of the New Jersey chapter of the [[Sierra Club]], stated, \"This project will increase traffic and flooding while taking business away from existing stores. This project is the Super Bowl of Sprawl and the American Dream is a commuter\u2019s nightmare.\"<ref name=NJ.com7.10.12/>\n\nIn May 2006, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) announced it was formally investigating the Mills Corporation, the original developer of the property, after it announced that it was restating four years of earnings due to executive misconduct and accounting errors. Later in the year, an analyst at [[Bank of America Securities]] pushed Mills Corporation to drop the project, citing the signs of cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Analyst tells Mills to drop Xanadu |first=Prashant |last=Gopal |first2=John |last2=Brennan |url=http://www.northjersey.com/page.php?qstr=eXJpcnk3ZjczN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXkzJmZnYmVsN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXk2OTc0MzAxJnlyaXJ5N2Y3MTdmN3ZxZWVFRXl5Mg==|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=August 12, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] expressed concerns about the height of the Ferris wheel, which at the time was planned to be {{Convert|287|ft|abbr=on}}, which the FAA feared would affect local air traffic to and from [[Teterboro Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FAA seeks shorter Ferris wheel at Xanadu |first=Nick |last=Clunn |url=http://www.northjersey.com/page.php?qstr=eXJpcnk3ZjczN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXkzJmZnYmVsN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXk3MjA5ODMzJnlyaXJ5N2Y3MTdmN3ZxZWVFRXl5Mg== |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=October 19, 2007 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the [[New York Giants]] and the [[New York Jets]] filed a lawsuit against Triple Five, seeking to halt construction. The lawsuit claimed that the addition of amusement and water parks at the site would adversely affect traffic at MetLife stadium on days when home games were played there,<ref name=\"NJ.com7.10.12\">{{cite news|author=Sherman, Ted|title=Developers of American Dream mall seek to sack Giants and Jets lawsuit|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2012/07/developers_of_the_american_dre.html|publisher=The Associated Press/NJ.com|date=July 10, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y1OiKDz}}</ref><ref name=\"NJ.com3.12.14\">{{cite news |title=Jets, Giants agree to drop American Dream lawsuit|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2014/03/jets_giants_agree_to_drop_american_dream_lawsuit.html|publisher=The Associated Press/NJ.com|date=March 12, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y14nCvH}}</ref> specifically 16 Sundays out of the year, the day of the week that [[Bergen County]]'s [[Blue Law]] prohibits shopping, though not amusement parks.<ref name=\"WallStreetJournal\">{{cite news|author=Haddon, Heather|title=Jets, Giants Sue Over Mall Near Stadium|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323728204578515673045639386|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=September 11, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911074317/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323728204578515673045639386}}</ref> The teams contended that while the mall would be closed on Sundays, the amusement park would not, which would create traffic jams on game days when up to 25,000 vehicles would park at the complex. Traffic studies conducted by the team estimated that 7,700 spots would be added by the project; the developers countered that the amusement parks would add only 63 more cars, claiming that local residents would be wise enough to avoid visiting on a game day, and most tourists would take the rail link rather than drive.<ref>{{cite news|author=Porter, David|title=Dueling Meadowlands mall traffic studies offered|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100157070|publisher=CNBC|date=November 11, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2019|archivedate=May 21, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78Y6ZKD1e}}</ref><ref>Brennan, John (December 7, 2012). [http://www.northjersey.com/news/182489961_Small_step_forward_for_American_Dream_parks.html \"Small step forward for American Dream parks\"]. NorthJersey.com.</ref> In July 2012 Triple Five countersued for what it called an improper campaign by the teams to preserve their monopoly at the site while dissuading potential lenders from investing.<ref name=NJ.com7.10.12/><ref name=NJ.com3.12.14/> On March 12, 2014 the parties reached a tentative settlement, agreeing to drop their lawsuits, which allowed the project to move forward.<ref name=NJ.com3.12.14/> \n\nIn February 2015, U.S. federal prosecutors accused [[Joe Ferriero]], former chairman of the Bergen County Democratic Organization and New Jersey political power broker, of bribery, fraud, and racketeering charges.<ref>Sampson, Peter (February 27, 2015) [http://www.northjersey.com/news/hard-work-or-abuse-of-power-joseph-ferriero-corruption-trial-opens-with-widely-varying-portrayals-1.1279161 \"Hard work or abuse of power? Joseph Ferriero corruption trial opens with widely varying portrayals\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref> The charges included an allegation that Mills Corporation paid Ferriero $1.7 million over the course of several years as a bribe or extortion to maintain Ferriero's political support for their development bid on the Xanadu project against rivals Hartz Mountain Industries. James Dausch, a former Mills Corporation employee testified that the $1.7 million was paid for Ferriero's consulting, not as a bribe. Dausch's testimony detailed much of the development bid process, including paid lobbyists positioning Mills with Governor [[Jim McGreevey]], then Governor [[Richard Codey]], as well as with Senator [[Robert Menendez]].<ref>Sampson, Peter (March 10, 2015 [http://www.northjersey.com/news/developer-testifying-in-ferriero-trial-says-1-7m-wasn-t-a-bribe-1.1286191 \"Developer testifying in Ferriero trial says $1.7M wasn't a bribe\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref> In April 2015, Ferriero was found guilty on five counts, but not on the Mills Corporation racketeering charges.<ref>Sampson, Peter (April 16, 2015) [http://www.northjersey.com/news/ferriero-found-guilty-on-racketeering-wire-fraud-and-bribery-related-charges-1.1310961 \"Ferriero convicted on racketeering count; ex-Democratic chief used political clout for profit\"]. NorthJersey.com</ref>\n\nThe State of New Jersey, through the New Jersey Sports and Exhibition Authority, issued $1.15 billion in tax-free bonds to support the project. These unrated bonds yielded 6.625% when first issued. They were part of a suite of tax concessions negotiated with the state and the City of Hackensack.<ref name=\"nj170621\">{{cite news |first1=John |last1=Brennan |title=American Dream Meadowlands bonds interest rate set as revival looms |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/business/meadowlands-matters/2017/06/21/american-dream-meadowlands-bonds-interest-rate-set-revival-looms/395607001/ |publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=June 21, 2017|accessdate =July 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Patriot Place]]\n* [[Titletown District]]\n* [[List of largest shopping malls in the world|List of the world's largest shopping malls]]\n* [[List of largest shopping malls in the United States]]\n* [[American Dream Miami]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|American Dream Meadowlands}}\n* {{official website|www.americandream.com}}\n* Lyne, Jack (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20060314180611/http://www.conway.com/ssinsider/snapshot/sf030804.htm $1.3B, 4.8MSF Xanadu Project Will Transform 'Swamps of Jersey']. Site Selection.\n* Douglass, David (October 5, 2004). [https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20041005005704/en/Meadowlands-Xanadu-Unveils-Wave-Major-Tenants-Consumer \"Meadowlands Xanadu Unveils First Wave of Major Tenants, Consumer Brands and Entertainment Experiences\"]. [[Business Wire]]\n* Ma, Myles (June 19, 2012). [http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2012/06/american_dream_mall_may_not_be_open_for_meadowlands_super_bowl.html \"American Dream Meadowlands shopping center may not be open for 2014 Super Bowl in New Jersey\"]. NJ.com.\n{{Meadowlands Sports Complex|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Shopping malls in New Jersey}}\n{{New York City Malls}}\n\n[[Category:Meadowlands Sports Complex]]\n[[Category:East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Aldo\u2192Aldo Group,Torrid\u2192Torrid (clothing retailer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Dream_(shopping_and_entertainment_complex)"}
{"title_page": "Flag of Scotland", "text_new": "{{Redirect|The Saltire||Saltire}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use Scottish English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox flag\n|Name = Scotland\n|Article =\n|Nickname = St Andrew's Cross<br>The Saltire\n|Image = Flag of Scotland.svg\n|Use = [[Civil flag|Civil]] and [[state flag]]\n|Symbol ={{FIAV|normal}}\n|Proportion = 3:5\n|Adoption = 16th century\n|Design =  A blue field with a white diagonal cross that extends to the corners of the flag. In [[Blazon]], ''[[Azure (heraldry)|Azure]], a [[saltire]] [[Argent]]''.\n|Type = National\n}}\nThe '''flag of Scotland''' ({{lang-gd|bratach na h-Alba}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AthelsatnefordlanguageLfts.pdf |format=PDF |title=Visit Athelstaneford. Birthplace of Scotland's Flag |accessdate=2010-03-12 |date=n.d. |publisher=Scottish Flag Trust |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716021436/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AthelsatnefordlanguageLfts.pdf |archivedate=16 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> {{lang-sco|Banner o Scotland}}, also known as '''St Andrew's Cross''' or '''the Saltire''')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04474.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618161731/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04474.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 June 2009 |format=PDF |title=The Union Flag and Flags of the United Kingdom |accessdate=2010-02-10 |date=2008-06-03 |work=SN/PC/04447 |first=Kevin |last=Williams |last2=Walpole |first2=Jennifer |publisher=House of Commons Library |df=dmy-all }}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-00-113-368-C |title=Scotland's National Flag, the Saltire or St Andrews Cross |accessdate=2009-12-09 |last=Gardiner |first=James |work=Scran |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland }}</ref> consists of a white [[saltire]] [[Defacement (flag)|defacing]] a blue field. The Saltire, rather than the [[Royal Standard of Scotland]], is the correct flag for all private individuals and corporate bodies to fly.<ref name='lyon'>{{cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/236.html |title=The Saltire |accessdate=2009-12-09 |publisher=The Court of the Lord Lyon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425205459/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/236.html |archive-date=25 April 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is also, where possible, flown from [[Scottish Government]] buildings every day from 8:00 am until sunset, with certain exceptions.<ref name='Govt'>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial/flag-guidance |title=Flag Flying Guidance |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2009-01-01 |work=Issue No. 13 (Valid from January 2009) |publisher=The Government of Scotland }}</ref>\n\nUse of the flag is first recorded with the illustration of a heraldic flag in [[David Lyndsay|Sir David Lyndsay of the Mount]]'s ''Register of Scottish Arms,'' circa 1542.<ref name='SCRAN'>{{cite web|url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-000-578-942-C&scache=2u90s101bf&searchdb=scran |title=Plate from the Lindsay Armorial |accessdate=2009-12-09 |author=National Library of Scotland |year=1542 |work=Scran |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland }}</ref> It is possible that this is based on a precedent of the late 15th century, the use of a white saltire in the canton of a blue flag reputedly made by [[Margaret of Denmark, Queen of Scotland|Queen Margaret]], wife of [[James III of Scotland|James III]] (1451\u20131488).<ref>{{cite book|title=British Flags & Emblems|publisher=Tuckwell Press|isbn=1-86232-297-X|last=Bartram|first=Graham|year=2004|quote=The blue background dates back to at least the 15th century.|page=10 }} [http://www.flaginstitute.org/images/page10_large.gif www.flaginstitute.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109055700/http://www.flaginstitute.org/images/page10_large.gif |date=9 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Flag of Scotland (traditional).svg|right|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} Saltire with ''sky blue'' field.]]\n[[File:Flag of Scotland (navy blue).svg|right|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} Saltire with ''navy blue'' field.]]\nThe [[heraldry|heraldic]] term for an X-shaped cross is a 'saltire', from the [[old French]] word ''saultoir'' or ''salteur'' (itself derived from the Latin ''saltatorium''), a word for both a type of stile constructed from two cross pieces and a type of cross-shaped stirrup-cord.<ref>''Oxford English Dictionary'', Second edition, 1989</ref> In [[heraldry|heraldic]] language, it may be [[blazon]]ed ''[[Azure (heraldry)|azure]]'', a saltire ''[[argent]]''. The [[Tincture (heraldry)|tincture]] of the Saltire can appear as either silver (''argent'') or white. However, the term ''azure'' does not refer to a particular shade of blue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/Faq.htm |title=Frequently Asked Questions |accessdate=2009-12-09 |publisher=College of Arms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413213138/http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/Faq.htm |archive-date=13 April 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThroughout the history of fabric production [[natural dye]]s have been used to apply a form of colour,<ref>{{cite book|title=All about fabrics: an introduction to needlecraft|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-832755-2|last=Holland|first=Stephanie|year=1987|quote=Throughout the history of fabric production, natural dyes have been used. They came from plant and animal sources, usually relating to the area in which the fabric was produced.|page=[https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31 31]|url=https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31}} [https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31 <!-- quote=\"what dyes were available\". --> Internet Archive] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426212033/https://books.google.com/books?id=Fgoy0G0_T4oC&pg=PA31&dq=%22what+dyes+were+available%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22what%20dyes%20were%20available%22&f=false |date=26 April 2016 }}</ref> with dyes from plants, including [[indigo dye|indigo]] from [[woad]], having dozens of compounds whose proportions may vary according to soil type and climate; therefore giving rise to variations in shade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wildcolours.co.uk/html/natural_dyes_comparison.html |title=Natural Dyes vs. synthetic dyes|accessdate=2010-09-28 |date=October 2006 |work=Natural Dyes|publisher=WildColours}}</ref> In the case of the Saltire, variations in shades of blue have resulted in the background of the flag ranging from [[sky blue]] to [[navy blue]]. When incorporated as part of the [[Union Flag]] during the 17th century, the dark blue applied to Union Flags destined for maritime use was possibly selected on the basis of the durability of darker dyes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb.html#col |title=Colour of the flag| accessdate=2009-12-12 |publisher=Flags of the World }}</ref> with this dark blue shade eventually becoming standard on Union Flags both at sea and on land. Some flag manufacturers selected the same navy blue colour trend of the Union Flag for the Saltire itself, leading to a variety of shades of blue being depicted on the flag of Scotland.<ref>{{cite news | first=Hamish | last=Macdonell |authorlink= | title=Parliament to set standard colour for Saltire | date=2003-02-19 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url =http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/standrewscross/Parliament-to-set-standard-colour.2403689.jp | work =The Scotsman | accessdate = 2009-12-09 }}</ref>\n\nThese variations in shade eventually led to calls to standardise the colour of Scotland's national flag,<ref>{{cite news | first=Hamish | last=Macdonell | title=MSPs are feeling blue over shady Saltire business | date=2002-06-03 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url =http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/standrewscross/MSPs-are-feeling-blue-over.2332166.jp | work=The Scotsman | accessdate = 2009-11-28 }}</ref> and in 2003 a [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|committee]] of the [[Scottish Parliament]] met to examine a petition that the [[Scottish Executive]] adopt the [[Pantone]] 300 colour as a standard. (Note that this blue is of a lighter shade than the Pantone 280 of the Union Flag). Having taken advice from a number of sources, including the office of the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], the committee recommended that the optimum shade of blue for the Saltire be Pantone 300.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hector |last=MacQueen |last2=Wortley |first2=Scott |authorlink= |title=(208)  Pantone 300 and the Saltire |date=2000-07-29 |publisher=The University of Edinburgh, School of Law. |url=http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/sln/blogentry.aspx?blogentryref=7261 |work=Scots Law News |pages= |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513070521/http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/sln/blogentry.aspx?blogentryref=7261 |archivedate=13 May 2012 }}</ref> Recent versions of the Saltire have therefore largely converged on this official recommendation. (Pantone 300 is #005EB8 as hexadecimal [[web colours]].)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pantone.com/pages/pantone/colorfinder.aspx |title=Pantone 300 Coated |accessdate=2009-12-09 |work=Find a PANTONE color |publisher=Pantone LLC }}</ref><ref name=\"BBCAzureThing\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2778189.stm |title=Flag colour is azure thing: Politicians have finally nailed their colours to the mast by specifying the precise shade of blue in Scotland's national flag |date=19 February 2003 |location=United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland |work=BBC News |author=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=1 November 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031101170046/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2778189.stm |archivedate=1 November 2003 }}</ref><ref name=\"PE512\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/petitions/public/petit-child/PE512.htm |title=Petition PE512 |date=2003 |accessdate=6 May 2004 |work=Public Petitions Committee \u2013 Petition PE512 Detail Page |publisher=The Scottish Parliament |location=Scotland, United Kingdom |quote=Tuesday, February 18, 2003: The Education, Culture and Sport Committee considered a petition from Mr George Reid on the Saltire flag. The Committee agreed that the colour of the Saltire flag should be colour reference Pantone 300. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040506123227/http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/petitions/public/petit-child/PE512.htm |archivedate=6 May 2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe flag proportions are not fixed, but 3:5 is most commonly used, as with other flags of the countries of the United Kingdom. (Flag manufacturers themselves may adopt alternative ratios, including 1:2 or 2:3).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flyingcolours.org/product-detail.php?ID=8 |title=Scotland \u2013 St Andrews Saltire) |accessdate=2010-09-20 |work=UK Flags |publisher=Flying Colours Flagmakers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726061622/http://www.flyingcolours.org/product-detail.php?ID=8 |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lord Lyon King of Arms states that 5:4 is suitable.<ref name=\"lyon\" /> The ratio of the width of the bars of the saltire in relation to the width of the [[field (heraldry)|field]] is specified in heraldry in relation to [[escutcheon (heraldry)|shield]] width rather than flag width. However, this ratio, though not rigid, is specified as one-third to one-fifth of the width of the field.<ref>{{cite book|title=Discovering Heraldry|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=0-7478-0660-8|last=Fearn|first=Jacqueline|year=2008|quote=The proportions of the ordinaries and diminutives to the shield have been defined but are not rigid and are secondary to good heraldic design. Thus the chief, fess and pale occupy up to one third of the shield, as do the bend, saltire and cross, unless uncharged, when they occupy one fifth, together with the bar and chevron.|page=21}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=GzDDnhcuOoIC&pg=PA21&dq=saltire+one-third+one-fifth+width+charged+uncharged&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=saltire%20one-third%20one-fifth%20width%20charged%20uncharged&f=false Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504145712/https://books.google.com/books?id=GzDDnhcuOoIC&pg=PA21&dq=saltire+one-third+one-fifth+width+charged+uncharged&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=saltire%20one-third%20one-fifth%20width%20charged%20uncharged&f=false |date=4 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!--[[File:Pennon of James Douglas, Earl of Moray from Otterburn 001.jpg|thumb|Pennon of James Douglas, Earl of Moray ([[Walter Scott]], ''Border Antiquities'',  1814)]]-->\n[[File:Model of the 'Great Michael'.jpg|thumb|Model of the ''Great Michael'']]\n[[File:Unicorn and Thistle, heraldic panel of King James V at the gatehouse of Holyrood Palace, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|upright|Arms of [[James V of Scotland|King James V]] (r. 1513\u20131542)<ref>A unicorn, holding the saltire (over the centre of which is a crown) supporting an escutcheon bearing a lion rampant, to either side and below are thistles, at the bottom in painted gold raised letters the inscription I R 5. Public Monuments and Sculpture Association  [https://canmore.org.uk/event/613230 (PMSA Work Ref.: EDIN0720)]</ref>]] The tradition of [[Saint Andrew]] being the [[patron saint]] of Scotland develops in the 13th to 14th centuries. The 1320 [[Declaration of Arbroath]] cites Scotland's conversion to Christianity by Andrew, \"the first to be an Apostle\". Depiction of the saint being crucified on a decussate cross, an iconographic tradition that had become current by the late 12th century, is used on a seal of the [[Guardians of Scotland]], dated 1286.<ref name='NAS'>{{cite web |url=http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp |title=Feature: Saint Andrew seals Scotland's independence |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2007-11-28 |publisher=The National Archives of Scotland |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916085046/http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp |archivedate=16 September 2013 |df=dmy }}{{unreliable source?|date=March 2019}}</ref> Bishop [[William de Lamberton]] (r. 1297\u20131328) also used the crucified figure of the saint in his seal.<ref>Henry Laing, ''Descriptive Catalogue of Impressions from Ancient Scottish Seals'' (1850), [https://books.google.ch/books?id=hlQJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA145 no. 865]</ref>\n\n<!--The [[Clan Maxwell|Maxwell family]] used a heraldic saltire as their emblem from at least the 1340s.<ref>Henry Laing, ''Descriptive Catalogue of Impressions from Ancient Scottish Seals'' (1850), [https://books.google.ch/books?id=hlQJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA98#v=onepage&q&f=false no. 573]</ref>\n-->\nThe [[saltire]] (decussate cross, diagonal cross) was used as a [[field sign]] in the medieval period without any connection to Saint Andrew. The connection between the field sign and the legendary mode of crucifixion of the saint may originate in Scotland, in the late 14th century. The [[Parliament of Scotland]] decreed [[English invasion of Scotland (1385)|in 1385]] that every Scottish and French soldier (fighting against the English under [[Richard II of England|Richard II]]) \"shall have  a sign before and behind, namely a white St. Andrew's Cross\".<ref>The Records of the Parliaments of Scotland to 1707, K.M. Brown et al. (eds.), St Andrews (2007\u20132019), [http://www.rps.ac.uk/mss/1385/6/4 1385/6/4]  \"ordinance made in council concerning the French army\": ''Item, que tout homme, Francois et Escot, ait un signe devant et derrere cest assavoir une croiz blanche Saint Andrieu et se son jacque soit blanc ou sa cote blanche il portera la dicte croiz blanche en une piece de drap noir ronde ou quarree.''</ref>\n\n[[James Douglas, 2nd Earl of Douglas]] at the [[Battle of Otterburn]] (1388) reportedly used a pennon with a saltire at the hoist. Similarly, a white saltire was shown in the canton of the  \"''Blue Blanket of the Trades of [[Edinburgh]]''\", reputedly made by [[Margaret of Denmark, Queen of Scotland|Queen Margaret]], wife of [[James III of Scotland|James III]] (1451\u20131488).<ref name='Bartram'>{{Cite conference| first=Graham | last=Bartram| contribution=The Story of Scotland's Flags| title=Proceedings of the XIX International Congress of Vexillology| publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale des associations vexillologiques| place=York, United Kingdom| pages=167\u2013172| year=2001 | contribution-url=http://www.flaginstitute.org/pdfs/Graham%20Bartram.pdf| chapter-format=PDF}}</ref> This is the flag of the [[Incorporated Trades of Edinburgh]], and the focal point of the Riding of the Marches ceremony held in the city each year.\n \nUse of the white \"Sanct Androis cors\" on blue as a naval flag is recorded for 1507, for the [[carrack]] ''[[Michael (ship)|Great Michael]]''.<ref name=\"Treas\">Balfour Paul, Sir James (1902). ''Accounts of the Lord High Treasurer of Scotland. Vol. iv. A.D. 1507\u20131513.'' H.M. General Register House, Edinburgh. p. 477. {{cite web|url= https://archive.org/stream/accountslordhig01offigoog#page/n573/mode/2up |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160403173248/https://archive.org/stream/accountslordhig01offigoog |archivedate=3 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> As a heraldic flag, the white saltire in a blue field is first shown in a 1542, in the armorial of [[David Lyndsay]]. Here, the [[Royal Arms of Scotland|royal arms]] are supported by two unicorns, each holding the saltire banner.<ref name=\"SCRAN\"  />\n\n[[Walter Bower]] in his ''[[Scotichronicon]]'' (1440s) supplies a legend according to which Saint Andrew appears to king  [[\u00d3engus II of the Picts|\u00d3engus II]] in 832, on the eve of a battle against the [[Angles]]. The saint advises the king to watch for the \"sign of the Cross of Christ in the air\". The \"Cross of Christ\" in this legend is later turned into the Saint Andrew's Cross or Saltire, in the account of [[George Buchanan]] (1506\u20131582), where \"a miraculous white saltire appeared in the blue sky\" during the battle.{{failed verification|date=March 2019}}<ref name=\"Bartram\"  />\n\n==Protocol==\n===Use by the Scottish Government===\n[[File:Scottish Government Logo.svg|250px|thumb|right|[[Scottish Government]] logo]]\nThe [[Scottish Government]] has ruled that the Saltire should, where possible, fly on all its buildings every day from 8am until sunset.<ref name=\"Govt\" /> An exception is made for [[United Kingdom]] \"national days\", when on buildings where only one flagpole is present the Saltire shall be lowered and replaced with the [[Union Flag]].<ref name='ukflagdates'>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/dates.html |title=Dates for Hoisting Flags on UK Government Buildings 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-14 |date=2008-12-16 |work=Flying the Flag on UK Government Buildings |publisher=Department for Culture, Media and Sport |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316062848/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/dates.html |archivedate=16 March 2009 }}</ref> Such [[Flag of the United Kingdom#Flag days|flag days]] are standard throughout the United Kingdom, with the exception of Merchant Navy Day, (3 September), which is a specific flag day in Scotland during which the [[Red Ensign]] of the [[Merchant Navy]] may be flown on land in place of either the Saltire or Union Flag.<ref name=\"Govt\" />\n\nA further Scottish distinction from the UK flag days is that on [[Saint Andrew's Day]], (30 November), the Union Flag will only be flown where a building has more than one flagpole; the Saltire will not be lowered to make way for the Union Flag where a single flagpole is present.<ref name=\"Govt\" /> If there are two or more flagpoles present, the Saltire may be flown in addition to the Union Flag but not in a superior position.<ref name='ukflagdates'/> This distinction arose after [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|Members of the Scottish Parliament]] complained that Scotland was the only country in the world where the potential existed for the citizens of a country to be unable to fly their national flag on their country's national day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ministers agree flag day review |date=2002-05-20 |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1997980.stm |accessdate=2009-11-30 }}</ref> In recent years, embassies of the United Kingdom have also flown the Saltire to mark St Andrew's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2006/11/07155736 |title=St Andrews Day celebrations |accessdate=2009-12-01 |date=2006-11-07 |publisher=The Scottish Executive}}</ref> Many bodies of the Scottish Government use the flag as a design basis for their logo; for example, Safer Scotland's emblem depicts a lighthouse shining beams in a saltire shape onto a blue sky.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Justice/public-safety/17141/practitioners |title=Community Safety in Scotland \u2013 Information for Practitioners |accessdate=2009-12-01 |work=Law, Order & Public Safety |publisher=The Government of Scotland}}</ref> Other Scottish bodies, both private and public, have also used the saltire in similar ways.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/FactTheFlag.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020224/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/FactTheFlag.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-16 |title=The Flag of Scotland |accessdate=2009-12-18 |work=FactTheFlag |publisher=The Scottish Flag Trust |format=PDF }}</ref>\n\n===Use by military institutions on land===\n[[File:Challenger Desert Storm 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Challenger 1]] [[Main Battle Tank|tank]] of the [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]] flying a Saltire from the whip antenna.]][[File:050625-Kiel-x82-600.jpg|thumb|right|[[Royal Navy]] [[Westland Sea King|Sea King Mk5]] of [[HMS Gannet SAR Flight|HMS ''Gannet'']].]]\nThe seven [[British Army Infantry]] [[battalion]]s of the [[Scottish Division]], plus the [[Scots Guards]] and [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]] [[regiment]]s, use the Saltire in a variety of forms. Combat and transport vehicles of these Army units may be adorned with a small, (130x80mm approx.), representation of the Saltire; such [[decal]]s being displayed on the front and/or rear of the vehicle. (On tanks these may also be displayed on the vehicle turret).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/bw_prep_turret_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716124551/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/bw_prep_turret_hr.jpg |archivedate=16 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In [[Iraq]], during both [[Operation Granby]] and the subsequent [[Operation Telic]], the Saltire was seen to be flown from the communications [[whip antenna]] of vehicles belonging to these units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/land/rsdg_flag_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050514041537/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/land/rsdg_flag_hr.jpg |archivedate=14 May 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/shaibah_saltire_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610061522/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/shaibah_saltire_hr.jpg |archivedate=10 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Funerals, conducted with full [[military honours]], of casualties of these operations in Iraq, (plus those killed in operations in [[Afghanistan]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img147.imageshack.us/img147/5817/610xxe.jpg |title=The coffin of Black Watch soldier Kevin Elliot is carried from St Mary's Church on September 15, 2009 in Dundee, Scotland. |accessdate=2012-01-09 |publisher=trackpads.com }}</ref> have also been seen to include the Saltire; the flag being draped over the coffin of the deceased on such occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/home/article/13250061 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714222416/http://news.sky.com/home/article/13250061 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-14 |title=Funeral Of Black Watch Bomb Victim |accessdate=2012-01-09 |publisher=sky.com }}</ref>\n\nIn the battle for \"hearts and minds\" in Iraq, the Saltire was again used by the British Army as a means of distinguishing troops belonging to Scottish regiments from other coalition forces, in the hope of fostering better relations with the civilian population in the area south west of [[Baghdad]]. Leaflets were distributed to Iraqi civilians, by members of the [[Black Watch]], depicting troops and vehicles set against a backdrop of the Saltire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psywarrior.com/OpnIraqiFreedomcont3.html |title=Operation Iraqi Freedom |accessdate=2009-05-31 |publisher=Psywarrior.com }}</ref>\n\nImmediately prior to, and following, the merger in March 2006 of Scotland's historic infantry regiments to form a single [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], a multi-million-pound advertising campaign was launched in Scotland in an attempt to attract recruits to join the reorganised and simultaneously rebranded \"Scottish Infantry\". The recruitment campaign employed the Saltire in the form of a logo; the words \"Scottish Infantry. Forward As One.\" being placed next to a stylised image of the Saltire. For the duration of the campaign, this logo was used in conjunction with the traditional Army recruiting logo; the words \"Army. Be The Best.\" being placed beneath a stylised representation of the Union Flag.{{cn|date=November 2019}} Despite this multi-media campaign having had mixed results in terms of overall success,<ref>{{cite news | first=Ian | last=Bruce | title=Recruits down 15% as Army severs local links | date=2007-09-19 | publisher=Herald & Times Group | url =http://www.heraldscotland.com/recruits-down-15-as-army-severs-local-links-1.865513 | work=The Herald | accessdate = 2009-06-01 }}</ref> the Saltire continues to appear on a variety of Army recruiting media used in Scotland.\n\nOther uses of the Saltire by the Army include the cap badge design of the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], which consists of a (silver) Saltire, surmounted by a (gilt) [[lion rampant]] and ensigned with a representation of the [[Crown of Scotland]]. (This same design, save for the Crown, is used on both the Regimental flag and [[tactical recognition flash]] of the Royal Regiment of Scotland).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/593DD958-A1EE-4EE1-B1BB-F054822C0810/0/BlackWatch2.JPG |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806102825/http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/593DD958-A1EE-4EE1-B1BB-F054822C0810/0/BlackWatch2.JPG |archivedate=6 August 2009 }}</ref> The badge of the [[No. 679 (The Duke of Connaught's) Squadron AAC|No. 679 (The Duke of Connaught's) Squadron]] [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] bears a Saltire between two wreaths ensigned 'Scottish Horse'; an honour they received in 1971 which originated through their links with the Royal Artillery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/aviation/22432.aspx |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-05-03 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126025101/http://army.mod.uk/aviation/22432.aspx |archivedate=26 November 2011 }}</ref> The [[Officer Training Corps]] units attached to universities in Edinburgh and Glasgow, plus the Tayforth University OTC, all feature the Saltire in their cap badge designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/UOTC/5487.aspx |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903133135/http://www.army.mod.uk/UOTC/5487.aspx |archivedate=3 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fleet Air Arm]] of the [[Royal Navy]] adorned three of their aircraft with the Saltire. Specifically, the [[Westland Sea King]] Mk5 aircraft of [[HMS Gannet|HMS ''Gannet'']], operating in the [[Search and Rescue]] (SAR) role from [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport|Royal Naval Air Station Prestwick]], [[Ayrshire]], displayed a Saltire decal on the nose of each aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/operations-and-support/fleet-air-arm/sar-operations/hms-gannet/about-us/ |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027174415/http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/operations-and-support/fleet-air-arm/sar-operations/hms-gannet/about-us/ |archivedate=27 October 2010 }}</ref> (The SAR function was transferred from the Royal Navy to [[Bristow Helicopters]], acting on behalf of [[HM Coastguard]], part of the UK's [[Maritime and Coastguard Agency]], with effect from 1 January 2016.)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35205477|title=Civilian team replaces HMS Gannet search and rescue at Prestwick |accessdate=2016-01-01 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not represented in the form of a flag, the [[No. 602 Squadron RAF|No. 602 (City of Glasgow) Squadron]] of the [[Royal Auxiliary Air Force]] uses the Saltire surmounted by a lion rampant as the device shown on the squadron crest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bshistorian.files.wordpress.com/2009/02/602sqn1.jpg |title=602sqn image |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=The BS Historian }}</ref> The station crest of the former [[RAF Leuchars]], [[Fife]], also showed the Saltire, in this case surmounted by a sword. The crest of the former [[RAF East Fortune]], [[East Lothian]], also showed a sword surmounting the Saltire, however unlike Leuchars this sword was shown inverted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-E.htm | title=RAF Stations \u2013 E | accessdate=2010-12-01 |publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation }}</ref> and the station crest of the former [[RAF Turnhouse]], [[Edinburgh]], showed a Saltire surmounted by an eagle's head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-T.htm | title=RAF Stations \u2013 T | accessdate=2010-12-01 |publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation }}</ref> The [[East of Scotland Universities Air Squadron]] crest features a Saltire surmounted by an open book; the book itself being supported by red lions rampant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/eastofscotlanduas/ |title=East of Scotland Universities Air Sqn |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012070303/http://www.raf.mod.uk/eastofscotlanduas/ |archive-date=12 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===General use===\nIn Scotland, the Saltire can be flown at any time by any individual, company, local authority, hospital or school without obtaining express consent.<ref name=\"lyon\" /><ref name=\"Govt\"/> Many local authorities in Scotland fly the Saltire from Council Buildings.  However, in 2007 [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]] Council approved a proposal to replace the Saltire on Council Buildings with a new Angus flag, based on the council's coat of arms. This move led to public outcry across Scotland with more than 7,000 people signing a petition opposing the council's move, leading to a compromise whereby the Angus flag would not replace but be flown alongside the Saltire on council buildings.<ref>{{cite news | first=Philip | last=Murray | title=Saltire and new Angus Flag will be pole buddies | date=2007-11-12 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url=http://www.forfardispatch.co.uk/local/SALTIRE-AND-NEW-ANGUS-FLAG.3479868.jp | archive-url=https://archive.today/20120530080023/http://www.forfardispatch.co.uk/local/SALTIRE-AND-NEW-ANGUS-FLAG.3479868.jp | url-status=dead | archive-date=2012-05-30 | work=Forfar Dispatch | accessdate=2009-12-02 }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, owners of vehicles registered in [[Great Britain]] have the option of displaying the Saltire on the [[Vehicle registration plates of the United Kingdom|vehicle registration plate]], in conjunction with the letters \"SCO\" or alternatively the word \"Scotland\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_067666.pdf |title=Section 9: National Flags on number plates |accessdate=2009-12-03 |date=2009-04-27 |work=(PDF), INF104: Vehicle registration numbers and number plates |publisher=DVLA }}</ref> In 1999, the [[Royal Mail]] issued a series of [[Country definitives#Pictorial issues|pictorial stamps for Scotland]], with the '2nd' value stamp depicting the Flag of Scotland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanley Gibbons Great Britain Concise Stamp Catalogue|publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd|isbn=978-0-85259-808-5|year=2011|first=Hugh|last=Jeffries}}</ref> In [[Northern Ireland]], sections of the [[Protestant]] community routinely employ the Saltire as a means of demonstrating and celebrating their [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster-Scots]] heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/images/symbols/flags.htm |title=Symbols in Northern Ireland \u2013 Flags Used in the Region |accessdate=2009-12-01 |work=CAIN Web Service | publisher=University of Ulster }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Scottish Red Ensign.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} [[Royal Scots Navy]] red [[ensign]].]] Use of the Saltire at sea as a ''[[Maritime flags#Jacks|Jack]]'' or ''[[courtesy flag]]'' has been observed, including as a ''Jack'' on the Scottish Government's Marine Patrol Vessel (MPV) ''Jura''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/marine/Compliance |title=Marine and Fisheries \u2013 Compliance |accessdate=2011-09-28 |publisher=Scottish Government }}</ref>  The ferry operator [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] routinely flies the Saltire as a ''Jack'' on vessels which have a bow staff, including when such vessels are underway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calmac.co.uk/getimage.aspx.ID-146922 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613205238/http://www.calmac.co.uk/getimage.aspx.ID-146922 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-13 |title=CalMac image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=CalMac }}</ref> This practice has also been observed on the [[PS Waverley|Paddle Steamer Waverley]] when operating in and around the [[Firth of Clyde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waverleyexcursions.co.uk/pictures/25.jpg |title=Waverley Excursions image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=Waverley Excursions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608124506/http://www.waverleyexcursions.co.uk/pictures/25.jpg |archivedate=8 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The practice of maritime vessels adopting the Saltire, for use as a ''jack'' or ''courtesy flag'', may lead to possible confusion in that the Saltire closely resembles the maritime [[signal flag]] '''M''', ''\"MIKE\"'', which is used to indicate \"''My vessel is stopped; making no way.''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/navy_legacy_hr.asp?id=273 |title=US Navy Signal Flags |accessdate=2009-12-18 |date=2009-08-17 |publisher=United States Navy}}</ref> For the benefit of Scottish [[seafarers]] wishing to display a Scottish flag other than the Saltire, thereby avoiding confusion and a possible fine, a campaign was launched in November 2007 seeking official recognition for the historic Scottish [[Red Ensign]].<ref name=\"ensign\">{{cite news | first=Kurt | last=Bayer | authorlink= | title=Article: Why sailors want to fly the (red) flag for Scotland; FLYING THE FLAG: James Ross wants recognition for the Scottish Red Ensign. | date=2007-11-25 | publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd | url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-171756260 | work=The Mail On Sunday | pages= | accessdate=2008-07-25 |url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia Online Library]] }}</ref> Despite having last been used officially by the pre-[[Acts of Union 1707|Union]] [[Royal Scots Navy]] and merchant marine fleets in the 18th century,<ref>{{cite book|title=Flags at sea: a guide to the flags flown at sea by British and some foreign ...|publisher=HMSO|isbn=0-11-290389-4 |year=1986|first=Timothy|last=Wilson|author2=National Maritime Museum (Great Britain)|quote=Scottish red ensign 17th-18th century|page=66}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=0mUTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&dq=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&lr=&as_brr=0&client=firefox-a&cd=6 Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424193959/https://books.google.com/books?id=0mUTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&dq=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&lr=&as_brr=0&client=firefox-a&cd=6 |date=24 April 2016 }}</ref> the flag continues to be produced by flag manufacturers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.duncanyacht.co.uk/showpartnumber.asp?CategoryID=2558&PartNumberID=302707 |title=1yd Scottish Ensign |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=www.duncanyacht.co.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402124540/http://www.duncanyacht.co.uk/showpartnumber.asp?CategoryID=2558&PartNumberID=302707 |archivedate=2 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AboutFlagssheet.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020145/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AboutFlagssheet.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-16 |title=Supply of Flags |accessdate=2009-12-19 |date=n.d. |work=PDF, Proper use of the Saltire |publisher=The Scottish Flag Trust}}</ref> and its unofficial use by private citizens on water has been observed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsindependent.org/features/orgs/images/red_ensign.jpg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121115618/http://www.scotsindependent.org/features/orgs/images/red_ensign.jpg |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-21 |title=The Scottish Flag Trust: \"Scottish Red Ensign\" (.jpg image) |accessdate=2009-12-18 |publisher=Scots Independent Newspaper }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the [[Unicode Consortium]] approved [[emoji]] support for the Flag of Scotland<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/01/27/emoji-england-scotland-wales-flags-released-year/|title=Emoji for England, Scotland and Wales flags to be released this year|last=Titcomb|first=James|date=2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> following a proposal from [[Jeremy Burge]] of [[Emojipedia]] and Owen Williams of [[BBC Cymru Wales|BBC Wales]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-40032325|title=Wales flag emoji arrives on Twitter|date=2017-05-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-36985749|title=Wales flag emoji decision awaited|last=Thomas|first=Huw|date=2016-08-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> This was added to major smartphone platforms alongside the flags of [[Flag of England|England]] and [[Flag of Wales|Wales]] in the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-41839176|title=Wales flag emoji arrives on iPhone|date=2017-11-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> Prior to this update, The Telegraph reported that users had \"been able to send emojis of the Union Flag, but not of the individual nations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/11/flags-england-wales-scotland-given-thumbs-emoji-chiefs/|title=Flags of England, Wales and Scotland given thumbs up by emoji chiefs|last=Reporters|first=Telegraph|date=2016-12-11|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Incorporation into the Union Flag==\n{{Main|Union Flag}} {{See also|Flag of England}}\n[[File:BeaumontScottishUnionFlag.png|thumb|right|alt=White saltire clearly visible over white-bordered red cross on blue background.| Scottish Union Flag depicted in the 1704 edition of ''The Present State of the Universe.'']]The Saltire is one of the key components of the [[Union Flag]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotshistoryonline.co.uk/saltire/saltire.html |title=Saint Andrew and his flag |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Scots History Online}}</ref> which, since its creation in 1606, has appeared in various forms<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Symbols of the Monarchy: Union Jack |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Royal Website |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref> following the Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of England]] first being merged to mark the [[Union of the Crowns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flaginstitute.org/index.php?location=7 |title=British flags |accessdate=2009-12-14 |last=Bartram |first=Graham |date=2008-10-18 |publisher=The Flag Institute}}</ref> (The Union of the Crowns having occurred three years earlier, in 1603, when [[James I of England|James VI, King of Scots]], acceded to the thrones of both [[Kingdom of England|England]] and [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]] upon the death of [[Elizabeth I of England]]). The [[proclamation]] by King James, made on 12 April 1606, which led to the creation of the Union Flag states:\n\n{{quote|By the King: Whereas, some differences hath arisen between Our subjects of South and North Britaine travelling by Seas, about the bearing of their Flagges: For the avoiding of all contentions hereafter. We have, with the advice of our Council, ordered: That from henceforth all our Subjects of this Isle and Kingdome of Great Britaine, and all our members thereof, shall beare in their main-toppe the [[Flag of England|Red Crosse]], commonly called [[St. George's Cross|St. George\u2019s Crosse]], and the White Crosse, commonly called [[Saltire|St. Andrew\u2019s Crosse]], joyned together according to the forme made by our [[herald]]s, and sent by Us to our Admerall to be published to our Subjects: and in their fore-toppe our Subjects of South Britaine shall weare the Red Crosse onely as they were wont, and our Subjects of North Britaine in their fore-toppe the White Crosse onely as they were accustomed. \u2013 1606.|sign=Proclamation of James VI, King of Scots: Orders in Council \u2013 12 April 1606.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fox-Davies|first=Arthur Charles|authorlink=Arthur Charles Fox-Davies|title=The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory|editor-link=The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory|publisher=Bloomsbury Books|location=London|year=1904 |origyear=1986|page=399|isbn=0-906223-34-2}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, in objecting strongly to the form and pattern of Union Flag designed by the [[College of Arms]] and approved by King James, whereby the cross of [[Saint George]] surmounted that of Saint Andrew, (regarded in Scotland as a slight upon the Scottish nation), a great number of [[shipmaster]]s and [[ship-owner]]s in Scotland took up the matter with [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|John Erskine, 19th Earl of Mar]], and encouraged him to send a letter of complaint, dated 7 August 1606, to James VI, via the [[Privy Council of Scotland]], stating:\n\n{{quote|Most sacred Soverayne. A greate nomber of the maisteris and awnaris of the schippis of this your Majesteis kingdome hes verie havelie compleint to your Majesteis Counsell that the form and patrone of the flaggis of schippis, send doun heir and commandit to be ressavit and used be the subjectis of boith kingdomes, is very prejudiciall to the fredome and dignitie of this Estate and will gif occasioun of reprotche to this natioun quhairevir the said flage sal happin to be worne beyond sea becaus, as your sacred majestie may persave, the Scottis Croce, callit Sanctandrois Croce is twyse divydit, and the Inglishe Croce, callit Sanct George, haldin haill and drawne through the Scottis Croce, whiche is thairby obscurit and no takin nor merk to be seen of the Scottis Armes. This will breid some heit and miscontentment betwix your Majesteis subjectis, and it is to be ferit that some inconvenientis sall fall out betwix thame, for oure seyfairing men cannot be inducit to ressave that flag as it is set doun. They haif drawne two new drauchtis and patronis as most indifferent for boith kingdomes which they present to the Counsell, and craved our approbatioun of the same; bot we haif reserved that to you Majesteis princelie determination.|sign=Letter from the Privy Council of Scotland to James VI, King of Scots \u2013 7 August 1606.<ref>{{cite book |last=Perrin |first=William G|title=British Flags; Their Early History and their Development at Sea, with an Account of the Origin of the Flag as a National Device |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.169115 |year=1922 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.169115/page/n247 207]}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=mtc8AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0# Google Books]</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Edinburgh Castle John Slezer.jpg|thumb|alt=Engraving of a castle on top of a steep hill, above the title \"The North East View of Edinburgh Castle\". On the castle flies a large Union Flag with Scottish saltire part of flag most visible.|[[John Slezer|Slezer's]] [[Edinburgh Castle]] c.1693 showing the Scottish Union Flag being flown above the Royal apartments.<ref>[http://www.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 National Library of Scotland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225215448/http://www.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 |date=25 February 2009 }}, Slezer's Scotland. Accessed 04 July 2010</ref>]]Despite the drawings described in this letter as showing drafts of the two new patterns, together with any royal response to the complaint which may have accompanied them, having been lost, (possibly in the 1834 [[Burning of Parliament]]), other evidence exists, at least on paper, of a Scottish variant whereby the Scottish cross appears uppermost. Whilst, in the absence of evidence to the contrary, this design is considered by most [[Vexillology|vexillologists]] to have been ''unofficial'', there is reason to believe that such flags were employed during the 17th century for use on Scottish vessels at sea.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartram |first=Graham |title=British Flags & Emblems |year=2005 |publisher=Flag Institute/Tuckwell |page=122}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=TD1mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&dq=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&pgis=1 Google books: ''\"Unofficial 1606 Scottish Union Flag\"''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822143725/https://books.google.com/books?id=TD1mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&dq=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&pgis=1 |date=22 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Crampton |first=William |title=Flags of the World |year=1992}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 1973\">{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Whitney |title=The Flag Bulletin |year=1973 |publisher=Flag Research Center}}</ref> This flag's design is also described in the 1704 edition of ''The Present State of the Universe'' by John Beaumont, Junior, which contains as an appendix ''The Ensigns, Colours or Flags of the Ships at Sea: Belonging to The several Princes and States in the World''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beaumont |first=John |title=The Present State of the Universe: Or an Account of I. The Rise, Births, Names, ... of All the Present Chief Princes of the World. ... |year=1704 |orig-year=First published 1701) |publisher=Benj. Motte, and are to be sold by John Nutt, 1704 |page=164}}</ref>\n\nOn land, evidence suggesting use of this flag appears in the depiction of [[Edinburgh Castle]] by [[John Slezer]], in his series of [[engraving]]s entitled ''Theatrum Scotiae'', c. 1693. Appearing in later editions of ''Theatrum Scotiae'', the ''North East View of Edinburgh Castle'' engraving depicts the ''[[Scotch (adjective)|Scotch]]'' (to use the appropriate adjective of that period) version of the Union Flag flying from the Castle Clock Tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=John Slezer, Robert Sibbald and Abel Swall |title=Theatrum Scotiae: Containing the prospects of their Majesties castles and palaces: together with those of the most considerable towns and colleges; the ruins of many ancient abbeys, churches, monasteries and convents, within the said kingdom. All curiously engraven on copper plates. With a short ... |year=1693 |publisher=John Leake |page=114}}</ref> A reduced view of this engraving, with the flag similarly detailed, also appears on the ''Plan of Edenburgh, Exactly Done''.<ref name='Slezer - Edenburgh, Exactly Done'>{{cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=70 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref> However, on the engraving entitled ''North Prospect of the City of Edenburgh'' the detail of the flag, when compared to the aforementioned engravings, appears indistinct and lacks any element resembling a saltire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maps.nls.uk/slezer/view/?sl=58 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref> (The reduced version of the ''North Prospect ...'', as shown on the ''Plan of Edenburgh, Exactly Done'', does however display the undivided arm of a saltire and is thereby suggestive of the Scottish variant).<ref name=\"Slezer - Edenburgh, Exactly Done\"/>\n|{{FIAV|historical}} \n[[File:Union Jack 1606 Scotland.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|alternate}} ''\"Scots union flag as said to be used by the Scots.\"''<ref name=\"de Burton\"/>]]\nOn 17 April 1707, just two weeks prior to the [[Acts of Union 1707|Acts of Union]] coming into effect, Sir Henry St George, [[Garter King of Arms]], presented several designs to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] and her [[Privy Council]] for consideration as the flag of the soon to be unified [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]. At the request of the Scots representatives, the designs for consideration included that version of Union Flag showing the Cross of Saint Andrew uppermost; identified as being the \"''Scots union flagg as said to be used by the Scots''\".<ref name='de Burton'>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=de Burton|title=How Scots lost battle of the standard |date=1999-11-09 |publisher=Johnston Press plc |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-18715263.html|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2009-06-30}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} ''Partial view at [http://www.encyclopedia.com/ Encyclopedia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108025215/http://www.encyclopedia.com/ |date=8 November 2016 }}''</ref> However, Queen Anne and her Privy Council approved Sir Henry's original effort, (pattern \"one\"), showing the Cross of Saint George uppermost.<ref name=\"de Burton\"/>\n\nFrom 1801, in order to symbolise the union of the Kingdom of Great Britain with the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] a new design, which included the [[St Patrick's Cross]], was adopted for the flag of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb-hist.html |title=United Kingdom \u2013 History of the Flag |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Flags of the World}}</ref> A manuscript compiled from 1785 by William Fox, and in possession of the [[Flag Research Center]], includes a full plate showing \"''the scoth {{sic}} union''\" flag with the addition of the cross of St. Patrick. This could imply that there was still some insistence on a Scottish variant after 1801.<ref>{{cite book|last=Smith |first=Whitney |title=The Flag Bulletin |year=1973 |publisher=Flag Research Center}}</ref>\n\nDespite its unofficial and historic status the Scottish Union Flag continues to be produced by flag manufacturers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyingcolours.org/gallery-items.php?galleryID=32 |title=Unofficial Scottish Union 1606 Flag |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=Flying Colours Flagmakers}}</ref> and its unofficial use by private citizens on land has been observed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/30178831@N02/3589637303/ |title=Scottish Union (.jpg image) |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=boonjiepam (Flickr)}}</ref> In 2006 historian [[David R. Ross]] called for Scotland to once again adopt this design in order to \"reflect separate national identities across the UK\",<ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Mair|title=Let's have a Scottish version of Union flag, says historian|date=2006-06-21 |url=http://news.scotsman.com/standrewscross/Lets-have-a-Scottish-version.2785666.jp |work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> however the 1801 design of Union Flag remains the [[Flag of the United Kingdom|official flag]] of the entire [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Union Jack |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=The official website of the British Monarchy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Scottish Union Flag - detail.JPG|[[Union Flag#Scottish Union Flag|Scottish Union Flag]]. An unofficial variant used in the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] during the 17th century, following the [[Union of the Crowns]].\nFile:Ch\u00e2t\u00e9 L\u00eezab\u00e9 Couleu d'la Grande Br\u00e9tangne c (reverse).jpg|Union Flag used in the [[Kingdom of England]] from 1606 and, following the [[Acts of Union 1707|Acts of Union]], the flag of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] from 1707\u20131800.\nFile:Union flag.jpg|Union Flag since 1801, including the [[Cross of Saint Patrick]], following the [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union]] between the Kingdom of Great Britain and [[Kingdom of Ireland]].\nFile:Union Flag and St Georges Cross.jpg|[[Flag of the United Kingdom]], (''Union Flag since 1801''), flying alongside the [[Flag of England]]; the [[St George's Cross|Cross of Saint George]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Related flags==\nSeveral flags outside of the United Kingdom are based on the Scottish saltire. In [[Canada]], an inverse representation of the flag (i.e. a blue saltire on a white field), combined with the shield from the [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland|royal arms of the Kingdom of Scotland]], forms the modern [[Flag of Nova Scotia|flag of the province of Nova Scotia]]. Nova Scotia (Latin for \"New Scotland\") was the first [[Scottish colonization of the Americas|colonial venture of the Kingdom of Scotland]] in the Americas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ns.ca/cmns/flagspublic.asp |title=Public Flag, Tartan Images |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2007-05-29 |publisher=Communications Nova Scotia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202225111/http://www.gov.ns.ca/cmns/flagspublic.asp |archivedate=2 December 2009 }}</ref> By contrast, the saltire logo of [[St. Andrew's First Aid]] is red on white rather than white on blue, in  alteration of the [[Emblems of the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].\n\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] municipality of [[Sint-Oedenrode]], named after the Scottish princess [[Saint Oda]], uses a version of the flag of Scotland, defaced with a gold castle having on both sides a battlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sint-oedenrode.nl/sint-oedenrode.aspx |title=Gemeentevlag |accessdate=2009-12-11 |publisher=Gemeente Sint-Oedenrode |language=Dutch }} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Australian Scottish-heritage flag.svg|Flag of the [[Scottish Australian]] Heritage Council, [[Australia]]\nFile:Royal Regiment of Scotland Flag.PNG|Regimental flag of the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]]\nFile:Flag of Nova Scotia.svg|[[Flag of Nova Scotia|Provincial flag of Nova Scotia]], Canada\nFile:Sint-Oedenrode vlag.svg|Flag of [[Sint-Oedenrode]], Netherlands\n</gallery>\n\n==Royal Standard of Scotland==\n{{Main|Royal Standard of Scotland}}\n{{See also|Royal Standard of the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:Lionrampant.svg|thumb|The [[Royal Standard of Scotland]]]]\n\nThe ''Royal Standard of Scotland'', also known as the ''Banner of the King of Scots''<ref>{{cite book |last=Innes of Learney |first=Sir Thomas |title=Scots heraldry: a practical handbook on the historical principles and modern application of the art and science |year=1934 |publisher=Oliver and Boyd |page=186}} [https://books.google.com/books?cd=1&id=-7UrAAAAIAAJ&dq=Scots+heraldry%3A+a+practical+handbook&q=Banner+of+the+king+of+scots#search_anchor ''Google Books''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511193431/https://books.google.com/books?cd=1&id=-7UrAAAAIAAJ&dq=Scots+heraldry%3A+a+practical+handbook&q=Banner+of+the+king+of+scots#search_anchor |date=11 May 2016 }}</ref> or more commonly the ''Lion Rampant of Scotland'',<ref>{{cite book |last =[[Patrick Fraser Tytler|Tytler, Patrick F]] |first= |title=History of Scotland Volume 2, 1149\u20131603 |year=1845 |publisher=William Tait |page=433}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=RtJJAAAAMAAJ&q=Lion+Rampant+of+Scotland#v=snippet&q=Lion%20Rampant&f=false Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528172442/https://books.google.com/books?id=RtJJAAAAMAAJ&q=Lion+Rampant+of+Scotland#v=snippet&q=Lion%20Rampant&f=false |date=28 May 2016 }}</ref> is the Scottish Royal Banner of Arms.<ref name=\"lyon2\" /> Used historically by the [[King of Scotland|King of Scots]], the Royal Standard of Scotland differs from Scotland's national flag, the Saltire, in that its correct use is restricted by an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of Scotland]] to only a few [[Great Officer of State|Great Officers of State]] who officially represent [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|The Sovereign]] in [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"lyon2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/237.html |title=The \"Lion Rampant\" Flag |accessdate=2008-10-10 |publisher=The Court of the Lord Lyon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605030445/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/237.html |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} pointing at the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/aosp/1672/47/paragraph/p1 Lyon King of Arms Act 1672, c. 47] and the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/30-31/17 Lyon King of Arms Act 1867, 30 & 31 Vict. cap. 17]</ref> However, a 1934 [[Royal warrant (document)|Royal Warrant]] for [[George V]]'s [[silver jubilee]] which authorised waving of hand-held versions continues to be relied upon by fans at sports events and other public occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.djmcgeachie.co.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?t=60&sid=8a73745574828ff4e1edcebf28785078 |title=The Lion Rampant & Heraldry |accessdate=28 August 2009 |publisher=The McGeachie Surname Forum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301181901/http://www.djmcgeachie.co.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?t=60&sid=8a73745574828ff4e1edcebf28785078 |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is also used in an official capacity at [[List of British royal residences|Royal residences]] in Scotland when the Sovereign is not present.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Union Jack |accessdate=2009-08-28 |publisher=The Royal Household |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag of Scotland.jpg|The Saltire, the national flag of [[Scotland]]: A white (''[[argent]]'') [[saltire]] on a blue (''[[Azure (heraldry)|azure]]'') field.\nFile:Flags outside Parliament.jpg|The [[Flag of the United Kingdom]], Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of Europe]] at the [[Scottish Parliament Building]].\nFile:Slag om Grolle 2008-1 - Linie van Staatse troepen vuurt.jpg|The Scottish Red Ensign at a [[historical reenactment]] of the [[Slag om Grolle|Battle for Grolle]].\nFile:The Saltire - geograph.org.uk - 718800.jpg|A variety of Saltires at [[Murrayfield Stadium]]; the national stadium of [[Rugby Union in Scotland]].\nFile:Welcome to Scotland - geograph.org.uk - 931197.jpg|The Flag(s) of Scotland marking the [[Anglo-Scottish Border]].\nFile:Highland Games-Opening ceremonies in Canmore.jpg|The Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of Canada]] at the [[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]] [[Highland Games]].\nFile:Hampden_Park_WP_EN.JPG|The Flag of Scotland seating design at [[Hampden Park|Hampden Park Stadium]]; the national stadium of [[Football in Scotland]].\nFile:Replica Covenanter flag, National Museum of Scotland.JPG|A replica 17th-century [[Covenanter|Covenanters']] flag.\nFile:The flag at North Berwick Golf Course - geograph.org.uk - 1523656.jpg|A [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] Saltire belonging to the [[Bass Rock]] [[golf]] club, [[North Berwick]].\nFile:Carrying the Royal Burgh Flag on Peat Hill - geograph.org.uk - 1354482.jpg|The defaced Saltire of the [[Royal Burgh]] of [[Selkirk, Scottish Borders|Selkirk]] leading the [[Common Riding]].\nFile:Scottish Flag.jpg|The Flag of Scotland; Proportions: 2:3.\nFile:Saltire.jpg|The Flag of Scotland; Proportions: 1:2.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Heraldry|Scotland}}\n* [[Bearer of the National Flag of Scotland]]\n* [[Flags of Europe]]\n* [[List of British flags]]\n* [[List of Scottish flags]]\n* [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of Scotland}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605020055/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/CCC_FirstPage.jsp The Court of the Lord Lyon website]\n* [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial/flag-guidance The Scottish Government \u2013 Flag Flying Guidance website]\n* [http://www.royal.gov.uk/ The British Monarchy \u2013 Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050914144924/http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/petitions/docs/PE512.htm Petition Number 512 ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130916085046/http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp Saint Andrew in the National Archives of Scotland]\n* [http://www.visitscotland.com/about/arts-culture/uniquely-scottish/saltire The Saltire \u2013 Scotland's national flag]{{cbignore}} at ''VisitScotland''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{UKFlags}}\n{{Flag of Europe}}\n{{Nationalflags}}\n{{Scotland topics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of Scotland}}\n[[Category:Flags of Scotland| ]]\n[[Category:Flags of saints]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Saltire flags]]\n[[Category:National flags|Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|The Saltire||Saltire}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use Scottish English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox flag\n|Name = Scotland\n|Article =\n|Nickname = St Andrew's Cross<br>The Saltire\n|Image = Flag of Scotland.svg\n|Use = [[Civil flag|Civil]] and [[state flag]]\n|Symbol ={{FIAV|normal}}\n|Proportion = 3:5\n|Adoption = 16th century\n|Design =  A blue field with a white diagonal cross that extends to the corners of the flag. In [[Blazon]], ''[[Azure (heraldry)|Azure]], a [[saltire]] [[Argent]]''.\n|Type = National\n}}\nThe '''flag of Scotland''' ({{lang-gd|bratach na h-Alba}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AthelsatnefordlanguageLfts.pdf |format=PDF |title=Visit Athelstaneford. Birthplace of Scotland's Flag |accessdate=2010-03-12 |date=n.d. |publisher=Scottish Flag Trust |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716021436/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AthelsatnefordlanguageLfts.pdf |archivedate=16 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> {{lang-sco|Banner o Scotland}}, also known as '''St Andrew's Cross''' or '''the Saltire''')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04474.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618161731/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04474.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 June 2009 |format=PDF |title=The Union Flag and Flags of the United Kingdom |accessdate=2010-02-10 |date=2008-06-03 |work=SN/PC/04447 |first=Kevin |last=Williams |last2=Walpole |first2=Jennifer |publisher=House of Commons Library |df=dmy-all }}\n{{cite web|url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-00-113-368-C |title=Scotland's National Flag, the Saltire or St Andrews Cross |accessdate=2009-12-09 |last=Gardiner |first=James |work=Scran |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland }}</ref> consists of a white [[saltire]] [[Defacement (flag)|defacing]] a blue field. The Saltire, rather than the [[Royal Standard of Scotland]], is the correct flag for all private individuals and corporate bodies to fly.<ref name='lyon'>{{cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/236.html |title=The Saltire |accessdate=2009-12-09 |publisher=The Court of the Lord Lyon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425205459/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/236.html |archive-date=25 April 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is also, where possible, flown from [[Scottish Government]] buildings every day from 8:00 am until sunset, with certain exceptions.<ref name='Govt'>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial/flag-guidance |title=Flag Flying Guidance |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2009-01-01 |work=Issue No. 13 (Valid from January 2009) |publisher=The Government of Scotland }}</ref>\n\nUse of the flag is first recorded with the illustration of a heraldic flag in [[David Lyndsay|Sir David Lyndsay of the Mount]]'s ''Register of Scottish Arms,'' circa 1542.<ref name='SCRAN'>{{cite web|url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-000-578-942-C&scache=2u90s101bf&searchdb=scran |title=Plate from the Lindsay Armorial |accessdate=2009-12-09 |author=National Library of Scotland |year=1542 |work=Scran |publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland }}</ref> It is possible that this is based on a precedent of the late 15th century, the use of a white saltire in the canton of a blue flag reputedly made by [[Margaret of Denmark, Queen of Scotland|Queen Margaret]], wife of [[James III of Scotland|James III]] (1451\u20131488).<ref>{{cite book|title=British Flags & Emblems|publisher=Tuckwell Press|isbn=1-86232-297-X|last=Bartram|first=Graham|year=2004|quote=The blue background dates back to at least the 15th century.|page=10 }} [http://www.flaginstitute.org/images/page10_large.gif www.flaginstitute.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109055700/http://www.flaginstitute.org/images/page10_large.gif |date=9 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Flag of Scotland (traditional).svg|right|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} Saltire with ''sky blue'' field.]]\n[[File:Flag of Scotland (navy blue).svg|right|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} Saltire with ''navy blue'' field.]]\nThe [[heraldry|heraldic]] term for an X-shaped cross is a 'saltire', from the [[old French]] word ''saultoir'' or ''salteur'' (itself derived from the Latin ''saltatorium''), a word for both a type of stile constructed from two cross pieces and a type of cross-shaped stirrup-cord.<ref>''Oxford English Dictionary'', Second edition, 1989</ref> In [[heraldry|heraldic]] language, it may be [[blazon]]ed ''[[Azure (heraldry)|azure]]'', a saltire ''[[argent]]''. The [[Tincture (heraldry)|tincture]] of the Saltire can appear as either silver (''argent'') or white. However, the term ''azure'' does not refer to a particular shade of blue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/Faq.htm |title=Frequently Asked Questions |accessdate=2009-12-09 |publisher=College of Arms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413213138/http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/Faq.htm |archive-date=13 April 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThroughout the history of fabric production [[natural dye]]s have been used to apply a form of colour,<ref>{{cite book|title=All about fabrics: an introduction to needlecraft|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-832755-2|last=Holland|first=Stephanie|year=1987|quote=Throughout the history of fabric production, natural dyes have been used. They came from plant and animal sources, usually relating to the area in which the fabric was produced.|page=[https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31 31]|url=https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31}} [https://archive.org/details/allaboutfabricsi0000holl/page/31 <!-- quote=\"what dyes were available\". --> Internet Archive] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426212033/https://books.google.com/books?id=Fgoy0G0_T4oC&pg=PA31&dq=%22what+dyes+were+available%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22what%20dyes%20were%20available%22&f=false |date=26 April 2016 }}</ref> with dyes from plants, including [[indigo dye|indigo]] from [[woad]], having dozens of compounds whose proportions may vary according to soil type and climate; therefore giving rise to variations in shade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wildcolours.co.uk/html/natural_dyes_comparison.html |title=Natural Dyes vs. synthetic dyes|accessdate=2010-09-28 |date=October 2006 |work=Natural Dyes|publisher=WildColours}}</ref> In the case of the Saltire, variations in shades of blue have resulted in the background of the flag ranging from [[sky blue]] to [[navy blue]]. When incorporated as part of the [[Union Flag]] during the 17th century, the dark blue applied to Union Flags destined for maritime use was possibly selected on the basis of the durability of darker dyes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb.html#col |title=Colour of the flag| accessdate=2009-12-12 |publisher=Flags of the World }}</ref> with this dark blue shade eventually becoming standard on Union Flags both at sea and on land. Some flag manufacturers selected the same navy blue colour trend of the Union Flag for the Saltire itself, leading to a variety of shades of blue being depicted on the flag of Scotland.<ref>{{cite news | first=Hamish | last=Macdonell |authorlink= | title=Parliament to set standard colour for Saltire | date=2003-02-19 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url =http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/standrewscross/Parliament-to-set-standard-colour.2403689.jp | work =The Scotsman | accessdate = 2009-12-09 }}</ref>\n\nThese variations in shade eventually led to calls to standardise the colour of Scotland's national flag,<ref>{{cite news | first=Hamish | last=Macdonell | title=MSPs are feeling blue over shady Saltire business | date=2002-06-03 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url =http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/standrewscross/MSPs-are-feeling-blue-over.2332166.jp | work=The Scotsman | accessdate = 2009-11-28 }}</ref> and in 2003 a [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|committee]] of the [[Scottish Parliament]] met to examine a petition that the [[Scottish Executive]] adopt the [[Pantone]] 300 colour as a standard. (Note that this blue is of a lighter shade than the Pantone 280 of the Union Flag). Having taken advice from a number of sources, including the office of the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], the committee recommended that the optimum shade of blue for the Saltire be Pantone 300.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hector |last=MacQueen |last2=Wortley |first2=Scott |authorlink= |title=(208)  Pantone 300 and the Saltire |date=2000-07-29 |publisher=The University of Edinburgh, School of Law. |url=http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/sln/blogentry.aspx?blogentryref=7261 |work=Scots Law News |pages= |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513070521/http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/sln/blogentry.aspx?blogentryref=7261 |archivedate=13 May 2012 }}</ref> Recent versions of the Saltire have therefore largely converged on this official recommendation. (Pantone 300 is #005EB8 as hexadecimal [[web colours]].)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pantone.com/pages/pantone/colorfinder.aspx |title=Pantone 300 Coated |accessdate=2009-12-09 |work=Find a PANTONE color |publisher=Pantone LLC }}</ref><ref name=\"BBCAzureThing\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2778189.stm |title=Flag colour is azure thing: Politicians have finally nailed their colours to the mast by specifying the precise shade of blue in Scotland's national flag |date=19 February 2003 |location=United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland |work=BBC News |author=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=1 November 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031101170046/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2778189.stm |archivedate=1 November 2003 }}</ref><ref name=\"PE512\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/petitions/public/petit-child/PE512.htm |title=Petition PE512 |date=2003 |accessdate=6 May 2004 |work=Public Petitions Committee \u2013 Petition PE512 Detail Page |publisher=The Scottish Parliament |location=Scotland, United Kingdom |quote=Tuesday, February 18, 2003: The Education, Culture and Sport Committee considered a petition from Mr George Reid on the Saltire flag. The Committee agreed that the colour of the Saltire flag should be colour reference Pantone 300. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040506123227/http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/petitions/public/petit-child/PE512.htm |archivedate=6 May 2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe flag proportions are not fixed, but 3:5 is most commonly used, as with other flags of the countries of the United Kingdom. (Flag manufacturers themselves may adopt alternative ratios, including 1:2 or 2:3).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flyingcolours.org/product-detail.php?ID=8 |title=Scotland \u2013 St Andrews Saltire) |accessdate=2010-09-20 |work=UK Flags |publisher=Flying Colours Flagmakers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726061622/http://www.flyingcolours.org/product-detail.php?ID=8 |archivedate=26 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lord Lyon King of Arms states that 5:4 is suitable.<ref name=\"lyon\" /> The ratio of the width of the bars of the saltire in relation to the width of the [[field (heraldry)|field]] is specified in heraldry in relation to [[escutcheon (heraldry)|shield]] width rather than flag width. However, this ratio, though not rigid, is specified as one-third to one-fifth of the width of the field.<ref>{{cite book|title=Discovering Heraldry|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=0-7478-0660-8|last=Fearn|first=Jacqueline|year=2008|quote=The proportions of the ordinaries and diminutives to the shield have been defined but are not rigid and are secondary to good heraldic design. Thus the chief, fess and pale occupy up to one third of the shield, as do the bend, saltire and cross, unless uncharged, when they occupy one fifth, together with the bar and chevron.|page=21}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=GzDDnhcuOoIC&pg=PA21&dq=saltire+one-third+one-fifth+width+charged+uncharged&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=saltire%20one-third%20one-fifth%20width%20charged%20uncharged&f=false Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504145712/https://books.google.com/books?id=GzDDnhcuOoIC&pg=PA21&dq=saltire+one-third+one-fifth+width+charged+uncharged&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=saltire%20one-third%20one-fifth%20width%20charged%20uncharged&f=false |date=4 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!--[[File:Pennon of James Douglas, Earl of Moray from Otterburn 001.jpg|thumb|Pennon of James Douglas, Earl of Moray ([[Walter Scott]], ''Border Antiquities'',  1814)]]-->\n[[File:Model of the 'Great Michael'.jpg|thumb|Model of the ''Great Michael'']]\n[[File:Unicorn and Thistle, heraldic panel of King James V at the gatehouse of Holyrood Palace, Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|upright|Arms of [[James V of Scotland|King James V]] (r. 1513\u20131542)<ref>A unicorn, holding the saltire (over the centre of which is a crown) supporting an escutcheon bearing a lion rampant, to either side and below are thistles, at the bottom in painted gold raised letters the inscription I R 5. Public Monuments and Sculpture Association  [https://canmore.org.uk/event/613230 (PMSA Work Ref.: EDIN0720)]</ref>]] The tradition of [[Saint Andrew]] being the [[patron saint]] of Scotland develops in the 13th to 14th centuries. The 1320 [[Declaration of Arbroath]] cites Scotland's conversion to Christianity by Andrew, \"the first to be an Apostle\". Depiction of the saint being crucified on a decussate cross, an iconographic tradition that had become current by the late 12th century, is used on a seal of the [[Guardians of Scotland]], dated 1286.<ref name='NAS'>{{cite web |url=http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp |title=Feature: Saint Andrew seals Scotland's independence |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2007-11-28 |publisher=The National Archives of Scotland |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916085046/http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp |archivedate=16 September 2013 |df=dmy }}{{unreliable source?|date=March 2019}}</ref> Bishop [[William de Lamberton]] (r. 1297\u20131328) also used the crucified figure of the saint in his seal.<ref>Henry Laing, ''Descriptive Catalogue of Impressions from Ancient Scottish Seals'' (1850), [https://books.google.ch/books?id=hlQJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA145 no. 865]</ref>\n\n<!--The [[Clan Maxwell|Maxwell family]] used a heraldic saltire as their emblem from at least the 1340s.<ref>Henry Laing, ''Descriptive Catalogue of Impressions from Ancient Scottish Seals'' (1850), [https://books.google.ch/books?id=hlQJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA98#v=onepage&q&f=false no. 573]</ref>\n-->\nThe [[saltire]] (decussate cross, diagonal cross) was used as a [[field sign]] in the medieval period without any connection to Saint Andrew. The connection between the field sign and the legendary mode of crucifixion of the saint may originate in Scotland, in the late 14th century. The [[Parliament of Scotland]] decreed [[English invasion of Scotland (1385)|in 1385]] that every Scottish and French soldier (fighting against the English under [[Richard II of England|Richard II]]) \"shall have  a sign before and behind, namely a white St. Andrew's Cross\".<ref>The Records of the Parliaments of Scotland to 1707, K.M. Brown et al. (eds.), St Andrews (2007\u20132019), [http://www.rps.ac.uk/mss/1385/6/4 1385/6/4]  \"ordinance made in council concerning the French army\": ''Item, que tout homme, Francois et Escot, ait un signe devant et derrere cest assavoir une croiz blanche Saint Andrieu et se son jacque soit blanc ou sa cote blanche il portera la dicte croiz blanche en une piece de drap noir ronde ou quarree.''</ref>\n\n[[James Douglas, 2nd Earl of Douglas]] at the [[Battle of Otterburn]] (1388) reportedly used a pennon with a saltire at the hoist. Similarly, a white saltire was shown in the canton of the  \"''Blue Blanket of the Trades of [[Edinburgh]]''\", reputedly made by [[Margaret of Denmark, Queen of Scotland|Queen Margaret]], wife of [[James III of Scotland|James III]] (1451\u20131488).<ref name='Bartram'>{{Cite conference| first=Graham | last=Bartram| contribution=The Story of Scotland's Flags| title=Proceedings of the XIX International Congress of Vexillology| publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale des associations vexillologiques| place=York, United Kingdom| pages=167\u2013172| year=2001 | contribution-url=http://www.flaginstitute.org/pdfs/Graham%20Bartram.pdf| chapter-format=PDF}}</ref> This is the flag of the [[Incorporated Trades of Edinburgh]], and the focal point of the Riding of the Marches ceremony held in the city each year.\n \nUse of the white \"Sanct Androis cors\" on blue as a naval flag is recorded for 1507, for the [[carrack]] ''[[Michael (ship)|Great Michael]]''.<ref name=\"Treas\">Balfour Paul, Sir James (1902). ''Accounts of the Lord High Treasurer of Scotland. Vol. iv. A.D. 1507\u20131513.'' H.M. General Register House, Edinburgh. p. 477. {{cite web|url= https://archive.org/stream/accountslordhig01offigoog#page/n573/mode/2up |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-12-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160403173248/https://archive.org/stream/accountslordhig01offigoog |archivedate=3 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> As a heraldic flag, the white saltire in a blue field is first shown in a 1542, in the armorial of [[David Lyndsay]]. Here, the [[Royal Arms of Scotland|royal arms]] are supported by two unicorns, each holding the saltire banner.<ref name=\"SCRAN\"  />\n\n[[Walter Bower]] in his ''[[Scotichronicon]]'' (1440s) supplies a legend according to which Saint Andrew appears to king  [[\u00d3engus II of the Picts|\u00d3engus II]] in 832, on the eve of a battle against the [[Angles]]. The saint advises the king to watch for the \"sign of the Cross of Christ in the air\". The \"Cross of Christ\" in this legend is later turned into the Saint Andrew's Cross or Saltire, in the account of [[George Buchanan]] (1506\u20131582), where \"a miraculous white saltire appeared in the blue sky\" during the battle.{{failed verification|date=March 2019}}<ref name=\"Bartram\"  />\n\n==Protocol==\n===Use by the Scottish Government===\n[[File:Scottish Government Logo.svg|250px|thumb|right|[[Scottish Government]] logo]]\nThe [[Scottish Government]] has ruled that the Saltire should, where possible, fly on all its buildings every day from 8am until sunset.<ref name=\"Govt\" /> An exception is made for [[United Kingdom]] \"national days\", when on buildings where only one flagpole is present the Saltire shall be lowered and replaced with the [[Union Flag]].<ref name='ukflagdates'>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/dates.html |title=Dates for Hoisting Flags on UK Government Buildings 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-14 |date=2008-12-16 |work=Flying the Flag on UK Government Buildings |publisher=Department for Culture, Media and Sport |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316062848/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/dates.html |archivedate=16 March 2009 }}</ref> Such [[Flag of the United Kingdom#Flag days|flag days]] are standard throughout the United Kingdom, with the exception of Merchant Navy Day, (3 September), which is a specific flag day in Scotland during which the [[Red Ensign]] of the [[Merchant Navy]] may be flown on land in place of either the Saltire or Union Flag.<ref name=\"Govt\" />\n\nA further Scottish distinction from the UK flag days is that on [[Saint Andrew's Day]], (30 November), the Union Flag will only be flown where a building has more than one flagpole; the Saltire will not be lowered to make way for the Union Flag where a single flagpole is present.<ref name=\"Govt\" /> If there are two or more flagpoles present, the Saltire may be flown in addition to the Union Flag but not in a superior position.<ref name='ukflagdates'/> This distinction arose after [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|Members of the Scottish Parliament]] complained that Scotland was the only country in the world where the potential existed for the citizens of a country to be unable to fly their national flag on their country's national day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ministers agree flag day review |date=2002-05-20 |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1997980.stm |accessdate=2009-11-30 }}</ref> In recent years, embassies of the United Kingdom have also flown the Saltire to mark St Andrew's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/News/Releases/2006/11/07155736 |title=St Andrews Day celebrations |accessdate=2009-12-01 |date=2006-11-07 |publisher=The Scottish Executive}}</ref> Many bodies of the Scottish Government use the flag as a design basis for their logo; for example, Safer Scotland's emblem depicts a lighthouse shining beams in a saltire shape onto a blue sky.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Justice/public-safety/17141/practitioners |title=Community Safety in Scotland \u2013 Information for Practitioners |accessdate=2009-12-01 |work=Law, Order & Public Safety |publisher=The Government of Scotland}}</ref> Other Scottish bodies, both private and public, have also used the saltire in similar ways.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/FactTheFlag.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020224/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/FactTheFlag.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-16 |title=The Flag of Scotland |accessdate=2009-12-18 |work=FactTheFlag |publisher=The Scottish Flag Trust |format=PDF }}</ref>\n\n===Use by military institutions on land===\n[[File:Challenger Desert Storm 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Challenger 1]] [[Main Battle Tank|tank]] of the [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]] flying a Saltire from the whip antenna.]][[File:050625-Kiel-x82-600.jpg|thumb|right|[[Royal Navy]] [[Westland Sea King|Sea King Mk5]] of [[HMS Gannet SAR Flight|HMS ''Gannet'']].]]\nThe seven [[British Army Infantry]] [[battalion]]s of the [[Scottish Division]], plus the [[Scots Guards]] and [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]] [[regiment]]s, use the Saltire in a variety of forms. Combat and transport vehicles of these Army units may be adorned with a small, (130x80mm approx.), representation of the Saltire; such [[decal]]s being displayed on the front and/or rear of the vehicle. (On tanks these may also be displayed on the vehicle turret).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/bw_prep_turret_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716124551/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/bw_prep_turret_hr.jpg |archivedate=16 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In [[Iraq]], during both [[Operation Granby]] and the subsequent [[Operation Telic]], the Saltire was seen to be flown from the communications [[whip antenna]] of vehicles belonging to these units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/land/rsdg_flag_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050514041537/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/land/rsdg_flag_hr.jpg |archivedate=14 May 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/shaibah_saltire_hr.jpg |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610061522/http://www.operations.mod.uk/telic/images/bwbg/shaibah_saltire_hr.jpg |archivedate=10 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Funerals, conducted with full [[military honours]], of casualties of these operations in Iraq, (plus those killed in operations in [[Afghanistan]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img147.imageshack.us/img147/5817/610xxe.jpg |title=The coffin of Black Watch soldier Kevin Elliot is carried from St Mary's Church on September 15, 2009 in Dundee, Scotland. |accessdate=2012-01-09 |publisher=trackpads.com }}</ref> have also been seen to include the Saltire; the flag being draped over the coffin of the deceased on such occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/home/article/13250061 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714222416/http://news.sky.com/home/article/13250061 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-14 |title=Funeral Of Black Watch Bomb Victim |accessdate=2012-01-09 |publisher=sky.com }}</ref>\n\nIn the battle for \"hearts and minds\" in Iraq, the Saltire was again used by the British Army as a means of distinguishing troops belonging to Scottish regiments from other coalition forces, in the hope of fostering better relations with the civilian population in the area south west of [[Baghdad]]. Leaflets were distributed to Iraqi civilians, by members of the [[Black Watch]], depicting troops and vehicles set against a backdrop of the Saltire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psywarrior.com/OpnIraqiFreedomcont3.html |title=Operation Iraqi Freedom |accessdate=2009-05-31 |publisher=Psywarrior.com }}</ref>\n\nImmediately prior to, and following, the merger in March 2006 of Scotland's historic infantry regiments to form a single [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], a multi-million-pound advertising campaign was launched in Scotland in an attempt to attract recruits to join the reorganised and simultaneously rebranded \"Scottish Infantry\". The recruitment campaign employed the Saltire in the form of a logo; the words \"Scottish Infantry. Forward As One.\" being placed next to a stylised image of the Saltire. For the duration of the campaign, this logo was used in conjunction with the traditional Army recruiting logo; the words \"Army. Be The Best.\" being placed beneath a stylised representation of the Union Flag.{{cn|date=November 2019}} Despite this multi-media campaign having had mixed results in terms of overall success,<ref>{{cite news | first=Ian | last=Bruce | title=Recruits down 15% as Army severs local links | date=2007-09-19 | publisher=Herald & Times Group | url =http://www.heraldscotland.com/recruits-down-15-as-army-severs-local-links-1.865513 | work=The Herald | accessdate = 2009-06-01 }}</ref> the Saltire continues to appear on a variety of Army recruiting media used in Scotland.\n\nOther uses of the Saltire by the Army include the cap badge design of the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], which consists of a (silver) Saltire, surmounted by a (gilt) [[lion rampant]] and ensigned with a representation of the [[Crown of Scotland]]. (This same design, save for the Crown, is used on both the Regimental flag and [[tactical recognition flash]] of the Royal Regiment of Scotland).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/593DD958-A1EE-4EE1-B1BB-F054822C0810/0/BlackWatch2.JPG |title=MoD image |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=MoD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806102825/http://www.mod.uk/NR/rdonlyres/593DD958-A1EE-4EE1-B1BB-F054822C0810/0/BlackWatch2.JPG |archivedate=6 August 2009 }}</ref> The badge of the [[No. 679 (The Duke of Connaught's) Squadron AAC|No. 679 (The Duke of Connaught's) Squadron]] [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] bears a Saltire between two wreaths ensigned 'Scottish Horse'; an honour they received in 1971 which originated through their links with the Royal Artillery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/aviation/22432.aspx |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-05-03 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126025101/http://army.mod.uk/aviation/22432.aspx |archivedate=26 November 2011 }}</ref> The [[Officer Training Corps]] units attached to universities in Edinburgh and Glasgow, plus the Tayforth University OTC, all feature the Saltire in their cap badge designs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/UOTC/5487.aspx |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903133135/http://www.army.mod.uk/UOTC/5487.aspx |archivedate=3 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fleet Air Arm]] of the [[Royal Navy]] adorned three of their aircraft with the Saltire. Specifically, the [[Westland Sea King]] Mk5 aircraft of [[HMS Gannet|HMS ''Gannet'']], operating in the [[Search and Rescue]] (SAR) role from [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport|Royal Naval Air Station Prestwick]], [[Ayrshire]], displayed a Saltire decal on the nose of each aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/operations-and-support/fleet-air-arm/sar-operations/hms-gannet/about-us/ |title=MoD web page |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027174415/http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/operations-and-support/fleet-air-arm/sar-operations/hms-gannet/about-us/ |archivedate=27 October 2010 }}</ref> (The SAR function was transferred from the Royal Navy to [[Bristow Helicopters]], acting on behalf of [[HM Coastguard]], part of the UK's [[Maritime and Coastguard Agency]], with effect from 1 January 2016.)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-35205477|title=Civilian team replaces HMS Gannet search and rescue at Prestwick |accessdate=2016-01-01 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not represented in the form of a flag, the [[No. 602 Squadron RAF|No. 602 (City of Glasgow) Squadron]] of the [[Royal Auxiliary Air Force]] uses the Saltire surmounted by a lion rampant as the device shown on the squadron crest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bshistorian.files.wordpress.com/2009/02/602sqn1.jpg |title=602sqn image |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=The BS Historian }}</ref> The station crest of the former [[RAF Leuchars]], [[Fife]], also showed the Saltire, in this case surmounted by a sword. The crest of the former [[RAF East Fortune]], [[East Lothian]], also showed a sword surmounting the Saltire, however unlike Leuchars this sword was shown inverted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-E.htm | title=RAF Stations \u2013 E | accessdate=2010-12-01 |publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation }}</ref> and the station crest of the former [[RAF Turnhouse]], [[Edinburgh]], showed a Saltire surmounted by an eagle's head.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Stations-T.htm | title=RAF Stations \u2013 T | accessdate=2010-12-01 |publisher=Air of Authority \u2013 A History of RAF Organisation }}</ref> The [[East of Scotland Universities Air Squadron]] crest features a Saltire surmounted by an open book; the book itself being supported by red lions rampant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/eastofscotlanduas/ |title=East of Scotland Universities Air Sqn |accessdate=2011-09-13 |publisher=MOD |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012070303/http://www.raf.mod.uk/eastofscotlanduas/ |archive-date=12 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===General use===\nIn Scotland, the Saltire can be flown at any time by any individual, company, local authority, hospital or school without obtaining express consent.<ref name=\"lyon\" /><ref name=\"Govt\"/> Many local authorities in Scotland fly the Saltire from Council Buildings.  However, in 2007 [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]] Council approved a proposal to replace the Saltire on Council Buildings with a new Angus flag, based on the council's coat of arms. This move led to public outcry across Scotland with more than 7,000 people signing a petition opposing the council's move, leading to a compromise whereby the Angus flag would not replace but be flown alongside the Saltire on council buildings.<ref>{{cite news | first=Philip | last=Murray | title=Saltire and new Angus Flag will be pole buddies | date=2007-11-12 | publisher=Johnston Press Digital Publishing | url=http://www.forfardispatch.co.uk/local/SALTIRE-AND-NEW-ANGUS-FLAG.3479868.jp | archive-url=https://archive.today/20120530080023/http://www.forfardispatch.co.uk/local/SALTIRE-AND-NEW-ANGUS-FLAG.3479868.jp | url-status=dead | archive-date=2012-05-30 | work=Forfar Dispatch | accessdate=2009-12-02 }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, owners of vehicles registered in [[Great Britain]] have the option of displaying the Saltire on the [[Vehicle registration plates of the United Kingdom|vehicle registration plate]], in conjunction with the letters \"SCO\" or alternatively the word \"Scotland\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_067666.pdf |title=Section 9: National Flags on number plates |accessdate=2009-12-03 |date=2009-04-27 |work=(PDF), INF104: Vehicle registration numbers and number plates |publisher=DVLA }}</ref> In 1999, the [[Royal Mail]] issued a series of [[Country definitives#Pictorial issues|pictorial stamps for Scotland]], with the '2nd' value stamp depicting the Flag of Scotland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanley Gibbons Great Britain Concise Stamp Catalogue|publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd|isbn=978-0-85259-808-5|year=2011|first=Hugh|last=Jeffries}}</ref> In [[Northern Ireland]], sections of the [[Protestant]] community routinely employ the Saltire as a means of demonstrating and celebrating their [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster-Scots]] heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/images/symbols/flags.htm |title=Symbols in Northern Ireland \u2013 Flags Used in the Region |accessdate=2009-12-01 |work=CAIN Web Service | publisher=University of Ulster }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Scottish Red Ensign.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|historical}} [[Royal Scots Navy]] red [[ensign]].]] Use of the Saltire at sea as a ''[[Maritime flags#Jacks|Jack]]'' or ''[[courtesy flag]]'' has been observed, including as a ''Jack'' on the Scottish Government's Marine Partrol Vessel (MPV) ''Jura''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/marine/Compliance |title=Marine and Fisheries \u2013 Compliance |accessdate=2011-09-28 |publisher=Scottish Government }}</ref>  The ferry operator [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] routinely flies the Saltire as a ''Jack'' on vessels which have a bow staff, including when such vessels are underway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calmac.co.uk/getimage.aspx.ID-146922 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613205238/http://www.calmac.co.uk/getimage.aspx.ID-146922 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-13 |title=CalMac image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=CalMac }}</ref> This practice has also been observed on the [[PS Waverley|Paddle Steamer Waverley]] when operating in and around the [[Firth of Clyde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waverleyexcursions.co.uk/pictures/25.jpg |title=Waverley Excursions image |accessdate=2009-12-01 |publisher=Waverley Excursions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608124506/http://www.waverleyexcursions.co.uk/pictures/25.jpg |archivedate=8 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The practice of maritime vessels adopting the Saltire, for use as a ''jack'' or ''courtesy flag'', may lead to possible confusion in that the Saltire closely resembles the maritime [[signal flag]] '''M''', ''\"MIKE\"'', which is used to indicate \"''My vessel is stopped; making no way.''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/navy_legacy_hr.asp?id=273 |title=US Navy Signal Flags |accessdate=2009-12-18 |date=2009-08-17 |publisher=United States Navy}}</ref> For the benefit of Scottish [[seafarers]] wishing to display a Scottish flag other than the Saltire, thereby avoiding confusion and a possible fine, a campaign was launched in November 2007 seeking official recognition for the historic Scottish [[Red Ensign]].<ref name=\"ensign\">{{cite news | first=Kurt | last=Bayer | authorlink= | title=Article: Why sailors want to fly the (red) flag for Scotland; FLYING THE FLAG: James Ross wants recognition for the Scottish Red Ensign. | date=2007-11-25 | publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd | url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-171756260 | work=The Mail On Sunday | pages= | accessdate=2008-07-25 |url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia Online Library]] }}</ref> Despite having last been used officially by the pre-[[Acts of Union 1707|Union]] [[Royal Scots Navy]] and merchant marine fleets in the 18th century,<ref>{{cite book|title=Flags at sea: a guide to the flags flown at sea by British and some foreign ...|publisher=HMSO|isbn=0-11-290389-4 |year=1986|first=Timothy|last=Wilson|author2=National Maritime Museum (Great Britain)|quote=Scottish red ensign 17th-18th century|page=66}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=0mUTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&dq=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&lr=&as_brr=0&client=firefox-a&cd=6 Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424193959/https://books.google.com/books?id=0mUTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&dq=%22scottish+red+ensign%22&lr=&as_brr=0&client=firefox-a&cd=6 |date=24 April 2016 }}</ref> the flag continues to be produced by flag manufacturers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.duncanyacht.co.uk/showpartnumber.asp?CategoryID=2558&PartNumberID=302707 |title=1yd Scottish Ensign |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=www.duncanyacht.co.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402124540/http://www.duncanyacht.co.uk/showpartnumber.asp?CategoryID=2558&PartNumberID=302707 |archivedate=2 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AboutFlagssheet.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716020145/http://www.scottishflagtrust.com/AboutFlagssheet.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-16 |title=Supply of Flags |accessdate=2009-12-19 |date=n.d. |work=PDF, Proper use of the Saltire |publisher=The Scottish Flag Trust}}</ref> and its unofficial use by private citizens on water has been observed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsindependent.org/features/orgs/images/red_ensign.jpg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121115618/http://www.scotsindependent.org/features/orgs/images/red_ensign.jpg |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-21 |title=The Scottish Flag Trust: \"Scottish Red Ensign\" (.jpg image) |accessdate=2009-12-18 |publisher=Scots Independent Newspaper }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the [[Unicode Consortium]] approved [[emoji]] support for the Flag of Scotland<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/01/27/emoji-england-scotland-wales-flags-released-year/|title=Emoji for England, Scotland and Wales flags to be released this year|last=Titcomb|first=James|date=2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> following a proposal from [[Jeremy Burge]] of [[Emojipedia]] and Owen Williams of [[BBC Cymru Wales|BBC Wales]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-40032325|title=Wales flag emoji arrives on Twitter|date=2017-05-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-36985749|title=Wales flag emoji decision awaited|last=Thomas|first=Huw|date=2016-08-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> This was added to major smartphone platforms alongside the flags of [[Flag of England|England]] and [[Flag of Wales|Wales]] in the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-41839176|title=Wales flag emoji arrives on iPhone|date=2017-11-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> Prior to this update, The Telegraph reported that users had \"been able to send emojis of the Union Flag, but not of the individual nations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/11/flags-england-wales-scotland-given-thumbs-emoji-chiefs/|title=Flags of England, Wales and Scotland given thumbs up by emoji chiefs|last=Reporters|first=Telegraph|date=2016-12-11|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Incorporation into the Union Flag==\n{{Main|Union Flag}} {{See also|Flag of England}}\n[[File:BeaumontScottishUnionFlag.png|thumb|right|alt=White saltire clearly visible over white-bordered red cross on blue background.| Scottish Union Flag depicted in the 1704 edition of ''The Present State of the Universe.'']]The Saltire is one of the key components of the [[Union Flag]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotshistoryonline.co.uk/saltire/saltire.html |title=Saint Andrew and his flag |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Scots History Online}}</ref> which, since its creation in 1606, has appeared in various forms<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Symbols of the Monarchy: Union Jack |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Royal Website |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref> following the Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of England]] first being merged to mark the [[Union of the Crowns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flaginstitute.org/index.php?location=7 |title=British flags |accessdate=2009-12-14 |last=Bartram |first=Graham |date=2008-10-18 |publisher=The Flag Institute}}</ref> (The Union of the Crowns having occurred three years earlier, in 1603, when [[James I of England|James VI, King of Scots]], acceded to the thrones of both [[Kingdom of England|England]] and [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]] upon the death of [[Elizabeth I of England]]). The [[proclamation]] by King James, made on 12 April 1606, which led to the creation of the Union Flag states:\n\n{{quote|By the King: Whereas, some differences hath arisen between Our subjects of South and North Britaine travelling by Seas, about the bearing of their Flagges: For the avoiding of all contentions hereafter. We have, with the advice of our Council, ordered: That from henceforth all our Subjects of this Isle and Kingdome of Great Britaine, and all our members thereof, shall beare in their main-toppe the [[Flag of England|Red Crosse]], commonly called [[St. George's Cross|St. George\u2019s Crosse]], and the White Crosse, commonly called [[Saltire|St. Andrew\u2019s Crosse]], joyned together according to the forme made by our [[herald]]s, and sent by Us to our Admerall to be published to our Subjects: and in their fore-toppe our Subjects of South Britaine shall weare the Red Crosse onely as they were wont, and our Subjects of North Britaine in their fore-toppe the White Crosse onely as they were accustomed. \u2013 1606.|sign=Proclamation of James VI, King of Scots: Orders in Council \u2013 12 April 1606.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fox-Davies|first=Arthur Charles|authorlink=Arthur Charles Fox-Davies|title=The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory|editor-link=The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory|publisher=Bloomsbury Books|location=London|year=1904 |origyear=1986|page=399|isbn=0-906223-34-2}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, in objecting strongly to the form and pattern of Union Flag designed by the [[College of Arms]] and approved by King James, whereby the cross of [[Saint George]] surmounted that of Saint Andrew, (regarded in Scotland as a slight upon the Scottish nation), a great number of [[shipmaster]]s and [[ship-owner]]s in Scotland took up the matter with [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|John Erskine, 19th Earl of Mar]], and encouraged him to send a letter of complaint, dated 7 August 1606, to James VI, via the [[Privy Council of Scotland]], stating:\n\n{{quote|Most sacred Soverayne. A greate nomber of the maisteris and awnaris of the schippis of this your Majesteis kingdome hes verie havelie compleint to your Majesteis Counsell that the form and patrone of the flaggis of schippis, send doun heir and commandit to be ressavit and used be the subjectis of boith kingdomes, is very prejudiciall to the fredome and dignitie of this Estate and will gif occasioun of reprotche to this natioun quhairevir the said flage sal happin to be worne beyond sea becaus, as your sacred majestie may persave, the Scottis Croce, callit Sanctandrois Croce is twyse divydit, and the Inglishe Croce, callit Sanct George, haldin haill and drawne through the Scottis Croce, whiche is thairby obscurit and no takin nor merk to be seen of the Scottis Armes. This will breid some heit and miscontentment betwix your Majesteis subjectis, and it is to be ferit that some inconvenientis sall fall out betwix thame, for oure seyfairing men cannot be inducit to ressave that flag as it is set doun. They haif drawne two new drauchtis and patronis as most indifferent for boith kingdomes which they present to the Counsell, and craved our approbatioun of the same; bot we haif reserved that to you Majesteis princelie determination.|sign=Letter from the Privy Council of Scotland to James VI, King of Scots \u2013 7 August 1606.<ref>{{cite book |last=Perrin |first=William G|title=British Flags; Their Early History and their Development at Sea, with an Account of the Origin of the Flag as a National Device |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.169115 |year=1922 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.169115/page/n247 207]}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=mtc8AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0# Google Books]</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Edinburgh Castle John Slezer.jpg|thumb|alt=Engraving of a castle on top of a steep hill, above the title \"The North East View of Edinburgh Castle\". On the castle flies a large Union Flag with Scottish saltire part of flag most visible.|[[John Slezer|Slezer's]] [[Edinburgh Castle]] c.1693 showing the Scottish Union Flag being flown above the Royal apartments.<ref>[http://www.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 National Library of Scotland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225215448/http://www.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 |date=25 February 2009 }}, Slezer's Scotland. Accessed 04 July 2010</ref>]]Despite the drawings described in this letter as showing drafts of the two new patterns, together with any royal response to the complaint which may have accompanied them, having been lost, (possibly in the 1834 [[Burning of Parliament]]), other evidence exists, at least on paper, of a Scottish variant whereby the Scottish cross appears uppermost. Whilst, in the absence of evidence to the contrary, this design is considered by most [[Vexillology|vexillologists]] to have been ''unofficial'', there is reason to believe that such flags were employed during the 17th century for use on Scottish vessels at sea.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartram |first=Graham |title=British Flags & Emblems |year=2005 |publisher=Flag Institute/Tuckwell |page=122}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=TD1mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&dq=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&pgis=1 Google books: ''\"Unofficial 1606 Scottish Union Flag\"''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822143725/https://books.google.com/books?id=TD1mAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&dq=%22Scottish+Union+Flag%22&pgis=1 |date=22 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Crampton |first=William |title=Flags of the World |year=1992}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith 1973\">{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Whitney |title=The Flag Bulletin |year=1973 |publisher=Flag Research Center}}</ref> This flag's design is also described in the 1704 edition of ''The Present State of the Universe'' by John Beaumont, Junior, which contains as an appendix ''The Ensigns, Colours or Flags of the Ships at Sea: Belonging to The several Princes and States in the World''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beaumont |first=John |title=The Present State of the Universe: Or an Account of I. The Rise, Births, Names, ... of All the Present Chief Princes of the World. ... |year=1704 |orig-year=First published 1701) |publisher=Benj. Motte, and are to be sold by John Nutt, 1704 |page=164}}</ref>\n\nOn land, evidence suggesting use of this flag appears in the depiction of [[Edinburgh Castle]] by [[John Slezer]], in his series of [[engraving]]s entitled ''Theatrum Scotiae'', c. 1693. Appearing in later editions of ''Theatrum Scotiae'', the ''North East View of Edinburgh Castle'' engraving depicts the ''[[Scotch (adjective)|Scotch]]'' (to use the appropriate adjective of that period) version of the Union Flag flying from the Castle Clock Tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=59 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=John Slezer, Robert Sibbald and Abel Swall |title=Theatrum Scotiae: Containing the prospects of their Majesties castles and palaces: together with those of the most considerable towns and colleges; the ruins of many ancient abbeys, churches, monasteries and convents, within the said kingdom. All curiously engraven on copper plates. With a short ... |year=1693 |publisher=John Leake |page=114}}</ref> A reduced view of this engraving, with the flag similarly detailed, also appears on the ''Plan of Edenburgh, Exactly Done''.<ref name='Slezer - Edenburgh, Exactly Done'>{{cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/slezer/engraving.cfm?sl=70 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref> However, on the engraving entitled ''North Prospect of the City of Edenburgh'' the detail of the flag, when compared to the aforementioned engravings, appears indistinct and lacks any element resembling a saltire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maps.nls.uk/slezer/view/?sl=58 |title=Slezer's Scotland |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=National Library of Scotland}}</ref> (The reduced version of the ''North Prospect ...'', as shown on the ''Plan of Edenburgh, Exactly Done'', does however display the undivided arm of a saltire and is thereby suggestive of the Scottish variant).<ref name=\"Slezer - Edenburgh, Exactly Done\"/>\n|{{FIAV|historical}} \n[[File:Union Jack 1606 Scotland.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|alternate}} ''\"Scots union flag as said to be used by the Scots.\"''<ref name=\"de Burton\"/>]]\nOn 17 April 1707, just two weeks prior to the [[Acts of Union 1707|Acts of Union]] coming into effect, Sir Henry St George, [[Garter King of Arms]], presented several designs to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] and her [[Privy Council]] for consideration as the flag of the soon to be unified [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]. At the request of the Scots representatives, the designs for consideration included that version of Union Flag showing the Cross of Saint Andrew uppermost; identified as being the \"''Scots union flagg as said to be used by the Scots''\".<ref name='de Burton'>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=de Burton|title=How Scots lost battle of the standard |date=1999-11-09 |publisher=Johnston Press plc |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-18715263.html|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2009-06-30}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} ''Partial view at [http://www.encyclopedia.com/ Encyclopedia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108025215/http://www.encyclopedia.com/ |date=8 November 2016 }}''</ref> However, Queen Anne and her Privy Council approved Sir Henry's original effort, (pattern \"one\"), showing the Cross of Saint George uppermost.<ref name=\"de Burton\"/>\n\nFrom 1801, in order to symbolise the union of the Kingdom of Great Britain with the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] a new design, which included the [[St Patrick's Cross]], was adopted for the flag of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb-hist.html |title=United Kingdom \u2013 History of the Flag |accessdate=2009-12-02 |publisher=Flags of the World}}</ref> A manuscript compiled from 1785 by William Fox, and in possession of the [[Flag Research Center]], includes a full plate showing \"''the scoth {{sic}} union''\" flag with the addition of the cross of St. Patrick. This could imply that there was still some insistence on a Scottish variant after 1801.<ref>{{cite book|last=Smith |first=Whitney |title=The Flag Bulletin |year=1973 |publisher=Flag Research Center}}</ref>\n\nDespite its unofficial and historic status the Scottish Union Flag continues to be produced by flag manufacturers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyingcolours.org/gallery-items.php?galleryID=32 |title=Unofficial Scottish Union 1606 Flag |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=Flying Colours Flagmakers}}</ref> and its unofficial use by private citizens on land has been observed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/30178831@N02/3589637303/ |title=Scottish Union (.jpg image) |accessdate=2011-09-16 |publisher=boonjiepam (Flickr)}}</ref> In 2006 historian [[David R. Ross]] called for Scotland to once again adopt this design in order to \"reflect separate national identities across the UK\",<ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Mair|title=Let's have a Scottish version of Union flag, says historian|date=2006-06-21 |url=http://news.scotsman.com/standrewscross/Lets-have-a-Scottish-version.2785666.jp |work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> however the 1801 design of Union Flag remains the [[Flag of the United Kingdom|official flag]] of the entire [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Union Jack |accessdate=2010-09-08 |publisher=The official website of the British Monarchy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Scottish Union Flag - detail.JPG|[[Union Flag#Scottish Union Flag|Scottish Union Flag]]. An unofficial variant used in the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] during the 17th century, following the [[Union of the Crowns]].\nFile:Ch\u00e2t\u00e9 L\u00eezab\u00e9 Couleu d'la Grande Br\u00e9tangne c (reverse).jpg|Union Flag used in the [[Kingdom of England]] from 1606 and, following the [[Acts of Union 1707|Acts of Union]], the flag of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] from 1707\u20131800.\nFile:Union flag.jpg|Union Flag since 1801, including the [[Cross of Saint Patrick]], following the [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union]] between the Kingdom of Great Britain and [[Kingdom of Ireland]].\nFile:Union Flag and St Georges Cross.jpg|[[Flag of the United Kingdom]], (''Union Flag since 1801''), flying alongside the [[Flag of England]]; the [[St George's Cross|Cross of Saint George]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Related flags==\nSeveral flags outside of the United Kingdom are based on the Scottish saltire. In [[Canada]], an inverse representation of the flag (i.e. a blue saltire on a white field), combined with the shield from the [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland|royal arms of the Kingdom of Scotland]], forms the modern [[Flag of Nova Scotia|flag of the province of Nova Scotia]]. Nova Scotia (Latin for \"New Scotland\") was the first [[Scottish colonization of the Americas|colonial venture of the Kingdom of Scotland]] in the Americas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ns.ca/cmns/flagspublic.asp |title=Public Flag, Tartan Images |accessdate=2009-12-09 |date=2007-05-29 |publisher=Communications Nova Scotia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202225111/http://www.gov.ns.ca/cmns/flagspublic.asp |archivedate=2 December 2009 }}</ref> By contrast, the saltire logo of [[St. Andrew's First Aid]] is red on white rather than white on blue, in  alteration of the [[Emblems of the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].\n\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] municipality of [[Sint-Oedenrode]], named after the Scottish princess [[Saint Oda]], uses a version of the flag of Scotland, defaced with a gold castle having on both sides a battlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sint-oedenrode.nl/sint-oedenrode.aspx |title=Gemeentevlag |accessdate=2009-12-11 |publisher=Gemeente Sint-Oedenrode |language=Dutch }} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Australian Scottish-heritage flag.svg|Flag of the [[Scottish Australian]] Heritage Council, [[Australia]]\nFile:Royal Regiment of Scotland Flag.PNG|Regimental flag of the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]]\nFile:Flag of Nova Scotia.svg|[[Flag of Nova Scotia|Provincial flag of Nova Scotia]], Canada\nFile:Sint-Oedenrode vlag.svg|Flag of [[Sint-Oedenrode]], Netherlands\n</gallery>\n\n==Royal Standard of Scotland==\n{{Main|Royal Standard of Scotland}}\n{{See also|Royal Standard of the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:Lionrampant.svg|thumb|The [[Royal Standard of Scotland]]]]\n\nThe ''Royal Standard of Scotland'', also known as the ''Banner of the King of Scots''<ref>{{cite book |last=Innes of Learney |first=Sir Thomas |title=Scots heraldry: a practical handbook on the historical principles and modern application of the art and science |year=1934 |publisher=Oliver and Boyd |page=186}} [https://books.google.com/books?cd=1&id=-7UrAAAAIAAJ&dq=Scots+heraldry%3A+a+practical+handbook&q=Banner+of+the+king+of+scots#search_anchor ''Google Books''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511193431/https://books.google.com/books?cd=1&id=-7UrAAAAIAAJ&dq=Scots+heraldry%3A+a+practical+handbook&q=Banner+of+the+king+of+scots#search_anchor |date=11 May 2016 }}</ref> or more commonly the ''Lion Rampant of Scotland'',<ref>{{cite book |last =[[Patrick Fraser Tytler|Tytler, Patrick F]] |first= |title=History of Scotland Volume 2, 1149\u20131603 |year=1845 |publisher=William Tait |page=433}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=RtJJAAAAMAAJ&q=Lion+Rampant+of+Scotland#v=snippet&q=Lion%20Rampant&f=false Google Books] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528172442/https://books.google.com/books?id=RtJJAAAAMAAJ&q=Lion+Rampant+of+Scotland#v=snippet&q=Lion%20Rampant&f=false |date=28 May 2016 }}</ref> is the Scottish Royal Banner of Arms.<ref name=\"lyon2\" /> Used historically by the [[King of Scotland|King of Scots]], the Royal Standard of Scotland differs from Scotland's national flag, the Saltire, in that its correct use is restricted by an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of Scotland]] to only a few [[Great Officer of State|Great Officers of State]] who officially represent [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|The Sovereign]] in [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"lyon2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/237.html |title=The \"Lion Rampant\" Flag |accessdate=2008-10-10 |publisher=The Court of the Lord Lyon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605030445/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/237.html |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} pointing at the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/aosp/1672/47/paragraph/p1 Lyon King of Arms Act 1672, c. 47] and the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/30-31/17 Lyon King of Arms Act 1867, 30 & 31 Vict. cap. 17]</ref> However, a 1934 [[Royal warrant (document)|Royal Warrant]] for [[George V]]'s [[silver jubilee]] which authorised waving of hand-held versions continues to be relied upon by fans at sports events and other public occasions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.djmcgeachie.co.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?t=60&sid=8a73745574828ff4e1edcebf28785078 |title=The Lion Rampant & Heraldry |accessdate=28 August 2009 |publisher=The McGeachie Surname Forum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301181901/http://www.djmcgeachie.co.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?t=60&sid=8a73745574828ff4e1edcebf28785078 |archivedate=1 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is also used in an official capacity at [[List of British royal residences|Royal residences]] in Scotland when the Sovereign is not present.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |title=Union Jack |accessdate=2009-08-28 |publisher=The Royal Household |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag of Scotland.jpg|The Saltire, the national flag of [[Scotland]]: A white (''[[argent]]'') [[saltire]] on a blue (''[[Azure (heraldry)|azure]]'') field.\nFile:Flags outside Parliament.jpg|The [[Flag of the United Kingdom]], Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of Europe]] at the [[Scottish Parliament Building]].\nFile:Slag om Grolle 2008-1 - Linie van Staatse troepen vuurt.jpg|The Scottish Red Ensign at a [[historical reenactment]] of the [[Slag om Grolle|Battle for Grolle]].\nFile:The Saltire - geograph.org.uk - 718800.jpg|A variety of Saltires at [[Murrayfield Stadium]]; the national stadium of [[Rugby Union in Scotland]].\nFile:Welcome to Scotland - geograph.org.uk - 931197.jpg|The Flag(s) of Scotland marking the [[Anglo-Scottish Border]].\nFile:Highland Games-Opening ceremonies in Canmore.jpg|The Flag of Scotland and [[Flag of Canada]] at the [[Canmore, Alberta|Canmore]] [[Highland Games]].\nFile:Hampden_Park_WP_EN.JPG|The Flag of Scotland seating design at [[Hampden Park|Hampden Park Stadium]]; the national stadium of [[Football in Scotland]].\nFile:Replica Covenanter flag, National Museum of Scotland.JPG|A replica 17th-century [[Covenanter|Covenanters']] flag.\nFile:The flag at North Berwick Golf Course - geograph.org.uk - 1523656.jpg|A [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] Saltire belonging to the [[Bass Rock]] [[golf]] club, [[North Berwick]].\nFile:Carrying the Royal Burgh Flag on Peat Hill - geograph.org.uk - 1354482.jpg|The defaced Saltire of the [[Royal Burgh]] of [[Selkirk, Scottish Borders|Selkirk]] leading the [[Common Riding]].\nFile:Scottish Flag.jpg|The Flag of Scotland; Proportions: 2:3.\nFile:Saltire.jpg|The Flag of Scotland; Proportions: 1:2.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Heraldry|Scotland}}\n* [[Bearer of the National Flag of Scotland]]\n* [[Flags of Europe]]\n* [[List of British flags]]\n* [[List of Scottish flags]]\n* [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of Scotland}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605020055/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/CCC_FirstPage.jsp The Court of the Lord Lyon website]\n* [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial/flag-guidance The Scottish Government \u2013 Flag Flying Guidance website]\n* [http://www.royal.gov.uk/ The British Monarchy \u2013 Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050914144924/http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/petitions/docs/PE512.htm Petition Number 512 ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130916085046/http://www.nas.gov.uk/about/051124.asp Saint Andrew in the National Archives of Scotland]\n* [http://www.visitscotland.com/about/arts-culture/uniquely-scottish/saltire The Saltire \u2013 Scotland's national flag]{{cbignore}} at ''VisitScotland''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{UKFlags}}\n{{Flag of Europe}}\n{{Nationalflags}}\n{{Scotland topics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of Scotland}}\n[[Category:Flags of Scotland| ]]\n[[Category:Flags of saints]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Saltire flags]]\n[[Category:National flags|Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "George Burgess", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeneral use:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "Choe Sihyeong", "text_new": "{{korean name|[[Choi (Korean surname)|Choe]]}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615\n|hanja=\u5d14\u6642\u4ea8\n|rr=Choe Sihyeong\n|mr=Ch'oe Sihy\u01d2ng\n}}\n'''Choe Sihyeong''' ({{lang-ko|\ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615}}) (1827\u20131898) original name Choe Gyeongsang, was the second leader of the Donghak Peasant Movement during the [[Joseon Dynasty]] and [[Korean Empire]] era. He succeeded [[Choe Je-u]] after the latter's execution by Joseon authorities in 1864. He was born in [[Gyeongju]] as a member of the local Choe clan. In [[Jeonju]], [[Jeolla]], he and his followers attempted to revolt against the Joseon authorities in the aftermath of the [[Donghak Peasant Revolution]], but he was caught by the authorities and executed by firing squad.<ref name=\"\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c\">\u300a[[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \uc138\uacc4\ub300\ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804]]\u300b,  \u3008\ub3d9\ud559\ud601\uba85\u3009, \ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615.</ref><ref name=\"p316\">\uc624\uc601\uc12d \u300a\ud55c\uad6d \uadfc\ud604\ub300\uc0ac\ub97c \uc218\ub193\uc740 \uc778\ubb3c\ub4e4(1)\u300b(\uc624\uc601\uc12d \uc800, 2007.4, \uacbd\uc778\ubb38\ud654\uc0ac) 315~316\ucabd.</ref><ref name=\"\ud55c\uc0c8\">{{cite book\n|author=\uc2e0\ubcf5\ub8e1\n|title=\ud55c\uad6d\uc0ac \uc0c8\ub85c \ubcf4\uae30\n|date=2001-12-20 \n|edition=\ucd08\ud310 2\uc1c4\n|publisher=\ub3c4\uc11c\ucd9c\ud310 \ud480\ube5b\n|location=\uc11c\uc6b8 \n|ISBN= 89-7474-870-3\n|pages=168~179\n}}</ref><ref name=\"parkus259\">\ubc15\uc740\ubd09, \u300a\ud55c\uad6d\uc0ac 100\uc7a5\uba74\u300b (\uac00\ub78c\uae30\ud68d, 1993) 259\ud398\uc774\uc9c0</ref><ref name=\"gul1996\">\uc591\ud544\uc2b9, \uc138\uacc4\uc0ac \uc18d\uc5d0\uc11c \uc804\ubd09\uc900:\ud55c\uad6d\ubbfc\uc871\uc8fc\uc758\uc758 \ud615\uc131\uacfc \ubb38\uba85\uc0ac\uc801 \uc704\uae30, \uc911\uc559\uc77c\ubcf4 WIN, 1996\ub144 7\uc6d4\ud638</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choe, Sihyeong}}\n\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1898 deaths]]\n[[Category:Korean educators]]\n[[Category:Korean religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Korean human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Joseon Dynasty people]]\n[[Category:Executed Korean people]]\n[[Category:Choe clan of Gyeongju]]\n[[Category:Korean Empire people]]\n[[Category:People from Gyeongju]]\n[[Category:People executed by firearm]]\n[[Category:Korean independence movement]]\n[[Category:Korean revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions by Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{korean name|[[Choi (Korean surname)|Choe]]}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615\n|hanja=\u5d14\u6642\u4ea8\n|rr=Choe Sihyeong\n|mr=Ch'oe Sihy\u01d2ng\n}}\n'''Choe Sihyeong''' ({{lang-ko|\ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615}}) (1827\u20131898) original name Choe Gyeongsang, was the second leader of the Donghak Peasant Movement during the [[Joseon Dynasty]] and [[Korean Empire]] era. He succeeded [[Choe Je-u]] after the latter's execution by Joseon authorities in 1864. He was born in [[Gyeongju]] as a member of the local Choe clan. In [[Jeonju]], [[Jeolla]], he and his followers attempted to revolt against the Joseon authorities in the aftermath of the [[Donghak Peasant Revolution]], but he was caught by the authorities and executed by firing squad.<ref name=\"\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c\">\u300a[[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c \uc138\uacc4\ub300\ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804]]\u300b,  \u3008\ub3d9\ud559\ud601\uba85\u3009, \ucd5c\uc2dc\ud615.</ref><ref name=\"p316\">\uc624\uc601\uc12d \u300a\ud55c\uad6d \uadfc\ud604\ub300\uc0ac\ub97c \uc218\ub193\uc740 \uc778\ubb3c\ub4e4(1)\u300b(\uc624\uc601\uc12d \uc800, 2007.4, \uacbd\uc778\ubb38\ud654\uc0ac) 315~316\ucabd.</ref><ref name=\"\ud55c\uc0c8\">{{cite book\n|author=\uc2e0\ubcf5\ub8e1\n|title=\ud55c\uad6d\uc0ac \uc0c8\ub85c \ubcf4\uae30\n|date=2001-12-20 \n|edition=\ucd08\ud310 2\uc1c4\n|publisher=\ub3c4\uc11c\ucd9c\ud310 \ud480\ube5b\n|location=\uc11c\uc6b8 \n|ISBN= 89-7474-870-3\n|pages=168~179\n|\uc778\uc6a9\ubb38=\n|\uaebe\uc1e0\ud45c=\uc608\n}}</ref><r